Panama </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Arosemena </PERSON> said. `` The Panamanian people are capable of solving their own problems.'' Banking and diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said bank would not open Friday even on a limited basis. They said bankers feared the government would use their deposits if they reopened. The government, whose deposits in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks have been frozen, has not met public payrolls since the crisis began. The last of 1,300 additional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers arrived Thursday at <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> outside <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, completing a buildup meant to provide greater security for the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, American installations and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. Late Wednesday, the government said it had issued arrest warrants for three leading opponents, including <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who has been in hiding in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. It also asked <ORGANIZATION> Interpol </ORGANIZATION>, the international police organization, to arrest <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Galindo </PERSON>, a former ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>'s envoy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and remains there. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` would regard any efforts by the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> regime to attempt arrests or prosecutions of President <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> and the others for their activities in urging and supporti