 <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, 69, a leading figure in the British newspaper industry for more than four decades and a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> news agency, died Thursday. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> began his career as a cub reporter on the <ORGANIZATION> Middlesbrough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> in northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in 1936. At age 28, he became personal assistant to newspaper proprietor <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemsley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> became editor of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Sunday Times, weekly companion of the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>, when Canadian Lord <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> bought the newspapers in 1959, as well as editorial director of the group. He was also editor-in-chief of <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> served as chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> from 1979 to 1985 during the British-based agency's expansion of its financial news services He was also the first president from 1978 until 1983 of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of more than 200 editors and publishers. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> introduced the color magazine supplement, now a feature of all the big national weekly newpapers, into British journalism.
