<BYLINE>Mozaffar Firouz</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mozaffar </PERSON> <PERSON> Firouz </PERSON>, a former Iranian vice premier who was known as the `` Red Prince'' for his close ties with the Tudeh Communist party, died at age 83. Members of his family did not say when he died. <PERSON> Firouz </PERSON> took part in negotations in 1946 on the withdrawal of Soviet troops from the Iranian part of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in the aftermath of World War II. He also held the labor ministry portfolio and helped draw up <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s first labor code. <PERSON> Firouz </PERSON> eventually was named ambassador to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> but resigned the post in 1947 to protest what he called undemocratic policies of <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>. He moved to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and published articles and books attacking the shah.
