<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: Supporting Actor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supporting Actor Nominees Are Diverse and None Has Won Before</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The race for best supporting actor of 1987 provides <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> voters a choice among a perspiring TV reporter, a steely <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> cop, a philandering <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> husband, a wily <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> pimp and a South African martyr. The nominees are a diverse lot, ranging from the first <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> to a stand-up comedian. None has ever won an Oscar. <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Connery </PERSON> is generally considered the quintessential 007, a role that seemed impossible for him to escape. But after 30 years in films, he has finally been recognized for his performance as another enforcer, the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> beat cop <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> in `` The Untouchables.'' `` I thought it was a very clever concept to take the old cop and use him as a kind of old dog who teaches a new dog tricks,'' says <PERSON> Connery </PERSON> of his role as mentor to the young federal agent, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Costner </PERSON>. Yet Connery is maintaining a classic Bond cool over the possibility of winning his first Oscar. `` To be honest, I've never really spent much time thinking about it before,'' he said in a recent interview. `` I just go on with my work.'' Neither is he bitter that it has taken the Academy some 40 films to even nominate him. `` It's all a matter of timing and how your films and image are presented,'' <PERSON> Connery </PERSON> told the Hollywood Reporter. `` There are a lot of my films which I'm very proud of, which I think were artistic successes, but were n't huge box office successes like the Bond pictures.'' There's no chance, though, that <PERSON> Connery </PERSON> will snub the Academy if he wins. `` It'd be important to me, and I'd definitely turn up to collect it. I'm not one of those actors who'd send along the cleaning lady instead.'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> accomplished the near-impossible: winning a nomination in a film released early in the year to scant notice. His role as vicious `` Fast Black'' in `` Street Smart'' was dynamic enough to remain in Academy voters' minds. Born in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> and raised in <LOCATION> Greenwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, before moving to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> built up an impressive number of stage credits before appearing in such films as `` Brubaker,'' `` Teachers'' and `` <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>.'' His performance in `` Street Smart'' prompted this outburst from the New Yorker's <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Kael </PERSON>: `` Is <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> the greatest actor in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> today?'' <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> admits to a rough life while growing up in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>: `` I stole, I conned, I passed the tests But I was scared. I'm not the violent type.'' This contrasts the brutal role he plays in `` Street Smart.'' Instead of sliding into delinquency, the young <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> found himself attracted to acting, and sold bottles so he would have money to go to the movies. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardenia </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cher </PERSON>'s excitable father in `` Moonstruck,'' has been in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> theater since 1954 and films since 1958. He also was a member of the `` All in the Family'' cast on television. <PERSON> Gardenia </PERSON> was ideal casting as the Italian plumber; his family emigrated from <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>, and he began acting in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Italian theater. He was delighted with the `` Moonstruck'' script: `` It was the first about an Italian family in a long time that you do n't see shooting, killings, bombings. It's about love, about family.'' <PERSON> Denzel </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> was cast in `` Cry Freedom'' after a worldwide search for an actor to play the vital role of <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Biko </PERSON>, the black leader who was beaten to death by South African police while in their custody. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> admits that his nomination was `` both a letdown and a great honor.'' The letdown came because <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> had been promoting him for best actor, and he had been nominated for a Golden Globe in that category. He adds that his reaction was n't the result of an actor's ego. `` It has more to do with my own feelings about <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Biko </PERSON>,'' he says. `` I would like to see him in -LRB- a starring -RRB- light, and I think most people do. He was not a supporting player.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> faced an imposing challenge: portraying a much-admired, even revered figure while making him a believable human being. `` I do n't know how to play a saint,'' he says. `` I could n't get any advice from anyone on how to play a saint. So that was no problem.'' Under <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Attenborough </PERSON>'s direction, he created a portrait of the martyr that was both human and convincing. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said the effect of `` Cry Freedom'' on the apartheid issue will be on a personal level. `` Most of the comments I've gotten from people were that they did n't know what goes on in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` That's where it will have its most important effect. I do n't think it's going to make a change in the government's attitude or the attitude of the black people there. It's just a movie, commenting on something from the outside.'' <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, the astute reporter and failed anchorman of `` Broadcast News,'' is noted for directing himself in films: `` Real Life,'' `` Modern Romance,'' `` Lost in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, a stand-up comedian before making films, says that the role of <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> was different from his own life: `` I do n't work in the news business I do n't have a 9 to 5 or even a 9 to 9 job. I do n't wear suits. I do n't have friends. ... Over a period of four months I hung out with a dozen reporters. I think what happens is you sort of compile little things from everybody.''
