<HEAD>Civilians Form `Dignity Battalions' To Repel Yankee Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In dusty fields and stadiums across <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, civilians turn out by the hundreds for military training to repel what the government says is an imminent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion. `` We get political speeches, and sometimes we see patriotic films,'' said <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, a government housing ministry employee. `` We do physical training and we have some weapons instruction.'' The volunteer units, called `` Dignity Battalions,'' formed, and have grown, since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> started announcing increases in troop strength in the former <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Canal Zone in mid-March. There is close-order drill, replete with slogans vowing death on behalf of the homeland and questioning the ancestry of all <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION>. About 300 volunteers showed up on one field near the capital Wednesday night, and some said it is one of the smallest battalions in the country. The battalion in the western city of <LOCATION> Davis </LOCATION> is said to have more than 1,000 participants. There is no reliable estimate on participation nationwide. In one corner of the field an instructor explained the basics of an M-16 rifle and passed several among his charges. Some, but not all, handled it uncomfortably. `` The Americans have them with a grenade launcher attatched. Do we have those too?'' asked one youth. `` Yes, we do,'' the instructor answered patiently. `` Hey, do n't point that thing at another comrade. The government press is predicting loudly that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will resort to invasion troops to oust Panamanian strongman Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. As head of the 15,000-member Panamanian Defense forces, <PERSON> Noreiga </PERSON> is the power behind the civilian government. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> normally keeps 10,000 troops in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to guard the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. In mid-March 500 military police were added, and 1,300 more troops arrived this week. The stated purpose of their open-ended assignment is to provide security for the troops, American installations and American citizens. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said 800 Marines will start arriving Friday for three weeks of routine jungle training. Evening papers Wednesday ballyhooed the planned arrival but neglected to mention the short planned stay. `` In Ships of Terror and Death, Contingents of War Veterans of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> Arrive in Open Plan of Aggression and Intimidation,'' read a headline in the government-owned Matutino newspaper. `` Gringo Invaders Begin to Arrive,'' read a headline in Wednesday's <PERSON> Critica </PERSON>, also government-owned. A cartoon shows Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> fleeing from gunfire from the `` popular forces,'' as the battalions also are known. The government closed all opposition media more than a month ago. All that Panamanians watch, read or hear comes from newspapers and broadcast stations owned at least partially by the government. Foreign newspapers brought in by travelers are confiscated at the airport. The volunteer battalions are instructed by <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> troops, who appear patient and have their work cut out for them. Most participants appear in their late teens or early to mid-20s. A few are easily 50. Many are women and all say they are not paid or required to attend the two-hour evening sessions held seven days a week. There is no roll call and no apparent other check of who shows up. `` We fight for our homeland and our dignity. The <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> only fight for money,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said. The instruction and the rhetoric were more reminiscent of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in recent years than a country where Americans have been well-tolerated, if not always cherished, for most of this century. The feeling is growing, it appears, but is far from universal. In a shabbier sector of downtown <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> a woman held up two shotgun shells fired by police during a minor demonstration. `` This is what they shoot at the people, like they are beasts,'' she said as the tear gas lifted. `` We've had it up to here. `` Panamanians are tired of this. We want the gringos to attack _ not tomorrow, today.'' `` Tonight,'' suggested a young man in a crowd that was gathering near two journalists. But those on the drill field felt otherwise. `` We believe an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> invasion is close, very close,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>. <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, an office holder in the nearby municipality of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miguelito </LOCATION>, speaks sincerely of American bodies going back to their home towns and said he is not worried about weapons availability. `` In revolutions in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> they did n't worry about weapons,'' he said. `` They took them from their dead enemies.''
</TEXT>
