<HEAD>Staying Tuned To Radio Free Europe On Polish State Radio</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A curious new program is going out over <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s state radio every Monday morning. It's called `` The West Speaks,'' and it is composed entirely of excerpts of Polish-language broadcasts by <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and other Western radio stations. The segments are broadcast without comment or counterpoint, but since the program went on the air the Polish media and officials have criticized the Western broadcasts with greater frequency. The Western stations always have been characterized here as hostile propaganda tools, but the Communist government says `` The West Speaks'' is one way to counter the influence of the broadcasts that deliver a mixture of uncensored news, features and commentary. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> stopped the electronic jamming of Western broadcasts Jan. 1 and Poles now can freely tune in to them. But government authorities have been raising the question of their fairness with Western officials, including the director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wick </PERSON>, who was here on a visit in March. The authorities say that in the struggle for the hearts and minds of the Polish people, they can not afford to overlook the influence of the Western stations. `` It does n't matter how many people listen to it when it is something very dangerous,'' government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Even if it's only 100 people, that is enough, because the report will spread.'' At one time, particularly during the Cold War years in the 1950s, it was a crime to listen to the Western stations. Today, however, the strains of `` Yankee Doodle Dandy,'' the sign-on tune of the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, can be heard coming from apartments in housing blocks. Urban said Polish authorities believed that countering the broadcasts with `` polemics and arguments'' was better than continuing the jamming. A public opinion poll quoted by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said 80 percent of respondents approved the decision to end the jamming, but it said the number of listeners has not risen significantly. How many people actually listen remains a matter of dispute. According to a survey quoted by Urban, the percentage of Poles who listen to Radio Free Europe either regularly or occasionally is 16 percent, up 2 percentage points since jamming ended. Only 3 percent, or 1.2 million out of the population of 37.5 million, listen as often as once a week, he said. But the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>, the body that oversees <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, says 59 percent of Poles listen to its broadcasts occasionally and nearly 14 percent at least once a week. An informal survey of half a dozen <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> residents indicated that most preferred the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> or the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> to Radio Free <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> RFE </ORGANIZATION>, on grounds that their information was more reliable. Recent <ORGANIZATION> RFE </ORGANIZATION> broadcasts were heavy with reports of demonstrations and protests in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, speeches and statements by leaders of the outlawed Solidarity trade union and accounts of opposition activities in other countries of the Soviet bloc. `` The West Speaks'' was conceived `` to show what sort of argumentation is used by these stations,'' said <PERSON> Witold </PERSON> <PERSON> Stankowski </PERSON>, an executive of Polish Radio One. He said the show, which premiered in October, was given a time slot when `` we have a pretty good audience,'' but said he could not judge its popularity or say how long it would be continued. In recent months a drumbeat of commentaries have shown up on the <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> service and in state-run newspapers disputing specific news items on the Western stations. Urban has made denunciations of the broadcasts almost a fixture at his weekly news conferences. In the interview, Urban noted that listenership tends to rise in times of public anxiety, such as during the 1986 <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He claimed <ORGANIZATION> RFE </ORGANIZATION>'s `` disgraceful methods'' frightened people in its reports on <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> and in its coverage of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s announcement in late January of price increases totaling 42 percent in 1988 `` Radio Free <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> presents the opinion that prices in fact will go up twice as much,'' he said. `` They want to cause, and really do cause, an increase in wage demands.'' <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> defends the broadcasts. `` The great bulk of what goes out seems to me to be a repetition of what already has been published in the West,'' he said. `` It is broadcast in, sometimes with comment, and comment is fair game.'' <PERSON> Wick </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> director who arrived in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on March 23 for a series of talks with Polish officials, said the Polish side raised objections about Radio Free Europe and the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and the complaints were discussed `` very forthrightly.'' <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, which is part of <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION>, which is privately opeated but largely funded by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, have charters that mandate that they be `` objective and accurate.'' `` I invited the authorities to give me specific instances when they were not,'' he said. He added that editorials on Radio Free Europe and the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> are not intended to be objective, but to `` reflect the editorial viewpoint of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government.'' As such, he said, they might not be pleasing to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.
