<SECOND>PM-Stung For Gifts, Bjt,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women Always Stung For Presents Throw Bash _ For Themselves</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ladies of the club _ <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Always </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> _ are throwing a bash today, and as usual the guests of honor are themselves. The dozen or so retired school secretaries plan to treat themselves to a fancy lunch, toast their single status and present themselves with an extra special gift. That's for the years and years of giving presents to their married friends, but never getting anything back. `` This is really to treat ourselves because no one else really has,'' explained <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Kieffer </PERSON>, 63, who's serving as the queen, or organizer, of today's gathering of the society, otherwise known as WASPS. `` Oh, Lordy, every time you turn around you're giving gifts. Wedding gifts and baby gifts and shower gifts. You could n't begin to count them. You're giving all the time, but you're not getting anything in return,'' said <PERSON> Alma </PERSON> <PERSON> Eck </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON>, 81, a founding member of the 38-year-old society. Miss <PERSON> Kieffer </PERSON> is giving herself a new white coat. Mrs. <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON>, a widow who married late in life, is celebrating with a watch on a necklace. Gifts can be whatever the women need or want. Over the years, presents have included diamond rings, new cars, houses, European vacations, even a custom-made girdle. `` She was quite a heavy girl and she could never get a girdle to fit her. So she had one made,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> said Thursday. Each woman writes a poem, to herself naturally, and gives herself a card that reads, `` I love me.'' They also sing this peppy tune: `` That's where our money's spent, on all the gals who went. We bought them everything to keep them supplied. We think the time is due to get a gift or two. So WASPS let's see what you brought you.'' The conversation covers just about everything except for children, grandchildren and, of course, men. `` That's why it's so nice. I do n't have to listen to stories about everybody's wonderful grandchildren,'' Miss <PERSON> Kieffer </PERSON> said, laughing. The members, ranging in age from their mid-50s to late 80s, have been gathering every April since 1950, when Mrs. <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> and 23 other never-wed secretaries for the <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION> decided enough was enough. They formed the society after learning about a similar group in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. To be eligible, women had to be single and employed as a secretary for the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION> for at least 10 years. `` If you were married, somebody would have had some plush party for you. So that was it. We'd be the contributors,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> said. `` But you could be married after that because once a WASP, always a WASP.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, says the society likely has its roots in the days when female teachers in some parts of the country were barred from saying `` I do.'' `` They just extended themselves through their kids'' in school, he said. The Women Always Stung for Presents Society grew to more than 60 members around 1970, but has since dwindled to 14, seven of them founding members. Two women are now married. Mrs. <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> is the only widow. `` A lot of them -LRB- members -RRB- have died,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> said. Secretaries nowadays simply are n't interested. `` They do n't want to have that brand,'' <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Viehman </PERSON>, 69, said. `` To say they've been working for 10 years and they are n't married, I guess it's terrible. It does n't bother me, but it does some people.'' The society meets once a year on April Fools' Day. The date was pushed back this year since Good Friday fell on April 1. The restaurant get-togethers are mandatory and planned months in advance. Members who can drive pick up those who ca n't. Just about everybody comes freshly coiffed and sporting a new outfit. `` We enjoy seeing each other because who knows who will be there next year,'' Miss <PERSON> Kieffer </PERSON> said. `` Our girls are all getting older,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> agreed. `` But we always say if there's one left, that one will go. We'll keep it up.''
