<HEAD>Anarchist Group Promises `National Anti-Yuppie Day'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As if <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s yuppies did n't have enough to worry about in the fallout from the stock market crash, they're now faced with anarchists plotting a `` National Anti-Yuppie Day.'' Adding to the misery of yuppie job losses, pay cuts and dwindling stock portfolios is Class War, an anarchists' group, which announced a 22-city rock concert tour in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> for August dubbed `` Rock against the Rich.'' It said in a statement made available Thursday to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that it hopes the tour will culminate in an anti-yuppie extravaganza on Sept. 10. Just who Class War is has never been clear. `` It's not a club you join,'' said a sympathizer, who gave his name only as <PERSON> Sean </PERSON>. Nor has the size of its membership been divulged. Group members sometimes surface in anti-capitalist stunts like a 1984 campaign in which bank windows were smashed, a smoke bomb exploded near the Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and about 470 people were arrested. But why pick on yuppies? Class War explained: `` All over <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, a plague of yuppies are descending on working-class communities like locusts. The time to resist is now _ let's Rock Against the Rich.'' In a telephone interview, <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> said it was `` because people have been pushed out from areas where they have always lived because of greed on the part of speculators, because it is n't possible to afford to buy somewhere to live in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> unless you have a hell of a lot of money.'' The story of the anti-yuppie campaign was broken, appropriately enough, in the Independent newspaper, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s newest daily and a favorite among yuppies. Its good-natured report Thursday on Class War's manifesto said: `` With this defiant, if ungrammatical, declaration, a new musical movement has been launched.'' B