<SECOND>AM-Hostage Fallout,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Guns Were Fake, Girl Wasn't Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mentally ill man killed by police was merely pretending to hold his teen-age girlfriend captive and used toy guns during a three-hour standoff, authorities said Thursday. The guns 19-year-old Israel <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> held to the girl's head and brandished at police from the window of his second-floor apartment were plastic water pistols and the `` hostage situation was a charade,'' York County District Attorney <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Rebert </PERSON> said at a news conference. The 15-year-old girl, a <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> runaway whose name was not released, was a willing participant, he said. Officials did not discuss the motive behind the charade. A police marksman shot <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> once in the abdomen and he died several hours later at <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. Police originally said the marksman fired when <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> threatened to kill the girl. But film taken by <ORGANIZATION> WGAL-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lancaster </LOCATION> showed <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> was shot seconds after yelling, `` I'm coming out'' and placing both hands on a window frame. No gun was in sight. <PERSON> Rebert </PERSON> and other officials refused to identify the officer who fired the fatal shot. They said he was on administrative leave without pay, pending the outcome of an investigation that is expected to last up to four weeks. The officials refused to say if any charges would be filed against the teen-ager.
