<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spring is in the air and so is courting _ especially among the Democratic presidential hopefuls as they woo the party's unpledged delegates to the national convention. Faced with the possibility that the primary process will not produce a clear-cut delegate leader, the candidates are focusing on the 645 `` super delegates'' who could tip the balance in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> July 18-21. Campaign brochures, news clippings and position papers fill the mailboxes of the super delegates _ 25 governors, 362 <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members, 253 members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and five elder statesmen _ who could push a candidate closer to the 2,082 total needed to nominate. Some campaigns rely on phone calls, such as those made to <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, a Democratic national committeewoman from <LOCATION> Keene </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, who remains uncommitted. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> phoned twice and his wife, <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON>, called too. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s staff called as well. Mrs. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> says she has heard from all the candidates except <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Since last fall, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign has been laying the foundation with the super delegates through phone calls, mailings and personal contact, said delegate counter <PERSON> Tad </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>. In recent weeks, aides have stepped up the pressure. `` It's much more focused, an intense effort,'' <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> said. `` When it looks like he's pulling away ... at that time we'll seek a more formal pledge of support.'' The <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> campaign has relied on congressional communication on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> as well as phone calls and mailings to the delegates, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutcheson </PERSON>, delegate counter for the senator. `` There's great potential among the super delegates,'' said <PERSON> Hutcheson </PERSON>, who describes the field as `` fertile territory'' for his candidate. `` The super delegates are most interested in a ticket that can win.'' The Jackson forces, however, are just getting started in their campaign for super delegates. `` I looked into what kind of a strategy he had to deal with them and who he had doing it,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> who is advising <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` It turns out they apparently had very little. There's some mail being passed back and forth.'' `` It's something they have to do and they're probably very late in doing it,'' he said. Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, a member of the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>, said last week he will lead the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> effort to court the super delegates. `` The front line is the congressional Black Caucus ... to talk to our colleagues in our states, to lobby people who are super delegates,'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> contends that if he leads in pledged delegates after the last primaries on June 7, he deserves the support of the super delegates and should get the nomination. `` We know that the super votes give rise to super delegates,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said last week after meeting with a select group of Democratic leaders. `` The delegates must respect and respond to the will of the people. `` If we do not believe that, why have a primary? Have a super-delegate convention and let the super delegates choose someone of their own,'' he said. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> speaker and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s national campaign chairman, said the campaign would use primary results to convince the super delegates. `` We will take the popular vote in their state or their district and say this is a factor you should consider,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. The constant communication _ by telephone and by mail _ is all too familiar to some super delegates. `` They do n't call on a per day basis,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerber </PERSON>, an uncommitted super delegate from <LOCATION> Norristown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> `` They called before and after <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, before and after <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. They tell us how well the candidates are doing.'' <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said the campaigns phone to find out `` if there's anything I want to know about the candidate, if I'm getting the mailings. They're very diplomatic.'' <PERSON> Dora </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivo </PERSON>, an uncommitted super delegate from <LOCATION> Rosenberg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, has received `` a lot of calls from <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' and expects it to get `` hot and heavy'' as the convention nears. Other delegates say the courting has n't even begun in earnest. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, a former supporter of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, said he had n't heard from any campaign since his candidate dropped out of the race two weeks ago. And <PERSO