<FIRST>r w PM-Teamsters-Truckers     04-08 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters-Truckers,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teamsters Trim Wage Increase To Improve Pension Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Teamster truck drivers and warehouse workers are giving up some of the wage increase their union has just negotiated for them in exchange for more pension and other fringe benefits. The new proposed National Master Freight Agreement unveiled Thursday differs from the tentative pact signed last week by the union and <ORGANIZATION> Trucking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the industry's bargaining arm. <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON>, a Teamster spokesman, acknowledged Thursday that some key provisions in the proposed contract were re-negotiated this week in response to pockets of opposition to them within the union. `` There were always some i's to be dotted and t's to be crossed,'' <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON> said. `` Obviously pension matters were of primary concern and the negotiators responded to the dictates of what the membership felt was important.'' <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON> said the union plans to begin mailing out ballots next week for a rank-and-file ratification vote, with ballot counting and announcement of the results to occur in mid-May. Under the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' constitution, rejection of a negotiated contract requires a two-thirds membership vote against it. About 200,000 workers are covered by the contract. When signed a week ago, the proposed three-year accord included an immediate 50-cent hourly wage increase followed by 35-cent raises in April 1989 and again in 1990. The 15-cent difference the first year is being switched to contributions by employers to the union's pension and health and welfare funds. The union's pension fund now provides retirees with a monthly pension check of up to $ 1,500. Instead of a 20-cents-per-hour increase in contributions to the two funds in each of the three years, trucking companies would now kick in 35 cents more an hour this year. If ratified, the contract would raise the base wage rate for truck drivers from the current $ 14.71 to $ 15.06 hour, retroactive to April 1. Wages would rise to $ 15.41 an hour in April 1989 and to $ 15.76 in 1990. So-called `` casual'' part-time workers now paid about $ 3 an hour less than the top scale also will get the same hourly wage and benefit increases under the renegotiated pact, <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Belous </PERSON>, a labor market analyst for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, a business research house, said the renegotiated contract belies a myth that, with lower tax rates, workers would opt for more pay than benefits. `` Given the choice between cash and security, workers are telling their negotiators to go back and get more security.'' <PERSON> Belous </PERSON> said. `` Once they reach a certain pay level, they want more protection against the vagaries of ill health and old age.'' The contract also recoups for <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> some of the concessions the union yielded to the industry in 1985. A two-tier wage system in which new hires started out at 70 percent of the base scale and rose by 10 percent a year to 100 percent at the end of three years is diminished by half. Under the new accord, new hires will start at 85 percent of the top scale, rising by 5 percentage points every six months until they reach 100 percent after a year and one-half. Many within the union had complained the two-tier scales were allowing the largest trucking companies who are adding new hires to their payrolls to undercut freight rates of small companies with older work forces.
</TEXT>
