<FIRST>r w PM-PrivateMail 530   04-08 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Private Mail, 530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Director, Postmaster General Disagree On Making Service
Private</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's budget director and the postmaster general disagree over whether the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mail ought to be turned over to private companies, and postal workers are siding with their boss. Budget director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said in a seminar Thursday that the Postal Service should not have a monopoly on letter deliveries. Postmaster General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> indicated to the same group he does n't like the idea of so-called `` privatization.'' As the two attended meetings sponsored by the conservative think tank <ORGANIZATION> Cato </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, union leader <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> led 100 picketers outside in a cold drizzle. `` <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, he's a jerk; privatization just wo n't work,'' the group chanted. <PERSON> Biller </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, called <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s proposal `` cockeyed'' and said it would cause chaos with the mail and increase costs to the public. The <ORGANIZATION> APWU </ORGANIZATION> is the largest of four mail unions, representing about 365,000 of the nation's 800,000 postal workers <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> said that accusations that the postal monopoly is causing increased costs are `` unmitigated lies.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CATO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, in a report issued as postal rates went up Sunday, said mail service is getting slower, more expensive and less reliable because of the lack of competition. Wearing a sign accusing <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of betraying postal reform, <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> stood at the doorway of the seminar room for a few minutes before the budget director arrived. As the doors were closed, he told seminar organizers, `` You're afraid of a free society.'' <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> later followed <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> into the hotel and shook his hand, saying he wanted to debate him on the idea of turning over the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to private business. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said in a speech: `` There is no good reason why it -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- should remain part of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, and no good reason why it should enjoy a monopoly over the delivery of letter mail.'' He accused the service of wanting to be a government-protected monopoly when it comes to letter mail and a federal agency when it comes to federal subsidies and other benefits. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> denied allegations from the postal unions and others that his <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> has tried to intrude into management of the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which is an independent government agency. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, who took over the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> March 1, suggested privatization could be a code word for union-busting. He said he is against eliminating the letter-mail monopoly the service has and does not believe private companies should be allowed to skim off profitable segments of the postal service. He said, however, he would support a genuine effort to promote efficiency by sharing work with private mailers and contracting more non-critical postal services. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said the Postal Service should be `` the most efficient, reliable, convenient public service in the country.'' He noted that private package services deliver only a tiny fraction of the 500 million items a day handled by the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. He said even advocates of privatization realize changes must be gradual, adding, `` I sense a desire to go slowly, a recognition that the mail system, like <ORGANIZATION> Humpty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dumpty </ORGANIZATION>, once broken, could n't be put back together again.''
</TEXT>
