<FIRST>r w PM-IcebergIncrease     04-08 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iceberg Increase,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antarctic Icebergs Increasing With Warming Trend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Earth's slowly rising temperature may be to blame for the recent increase in icebergs breaking off from <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>, government ice specialists say. They ca n't be sure yet, but officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy-NOAA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> note that as the global temperature has increased, so have the size and number of icebergs. `` An abnormally high amount of ice shelf calving is occurring in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> meteorologist <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON> said Thursday. Increases in the amount of carbon dioxide and other gases in the atmosphere over the last century or so have been associated with rising temperatures around the world. Some scientists believe that the temperature increase, amounting to one or two degrees Fahrenheit in the last century, could lead to major climate changes including melting the ice in the polar regions. This could cause a rise in the ocean level around the world and cause major changes in weather patterns, climatologists have warned. `` The poles are sensitive indicators of change'' in the Earth's climate, <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON> said But while the increase in icebergs may be a result of the rising temperature, there is n't yet enough information to be certain, said <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Koffler </PERSON>, who heads the satellite services at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have only 12 years of data,'' added <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON>. `` That is nothing in the geological bucket.'' But he noted that both abnormally large icebergs and an increasing number of bergs have been breaking loose in the last year or two. Whether this will be a continuing trend he declined to forecast, saying `` the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, as a system, is difficult to predict.'' <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON> said the iceberg increase was notable in the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> area. It's harder to determine if more bergs are arising in the arctic, where they tend to be smaller and larger in number anyway, he said. But in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> two exceptional iceberge have broken loose in the last two years. Last year a berg called B-9 broke off the <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> ice shelf. Measuring 86 miles by 23 miles, B-9 covered 1,978 square miles, nearly as big as <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. At 800 feet thick, it contains enough water to supply <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> for 700 years, said <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON>. And loose in the ocean it could be a serious hazard to shipping. B-9 has run aground on an underwater mountain, he said, but is likely to break free eventually, and could take from two to seven years to melt, he said. An even larger iceberg broke free from the other side of <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> in 1986, <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON> added, but that has since split into pieces, leaving B-9 as the largest floating mass of ice. Other smaller bergs have broken free also, though numbers were not available. Indeed, many bergs are too small to register on the satellites used to watch them, which track items about a half-mile across and larger. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Commander <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said that within a few years improved satellites will be in place to allow smaller bergs to be followed. The Center is responsible for monitoring ice conditions in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and most of the oceans of the world. The lone exception is the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, where bergs are tracked by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> operation set up in 1912 following the Titanic disaster. The two groups share data.
</TEXT>
