<FIRST>r w PM-TexasWine Bjt   04-08 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Wine, Bjt,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hold the Lone Star and Gimme a Long, Tall Armadillo Blanc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The longneck beer may be the beverage of choice for more Texans, but five wineries from the Lone Star State are hoping to make a big splash at <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s largest wine festival. The wineries hope exposure at the <LOCATION> Vin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> show in <LOCATION> Verona </LOCATION> will increase their credibility with financial institutions that have been slow to lend them money for expansion in a state better known for its chili than its <PERSON> Chenin </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanc </PERSON>. `` I think it will enhance the prestige of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> wines to have competed at the premier wine festival in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' Rep. <PERSON> Kika </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said before leaving for the show, which opened today. `` Secondly, the marketing part of it will allow the wine brokers and merchants to know we have good quality wines in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> said. As head of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> helped arranged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participation in the show. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> participants are hoping international exposure will lay the groundwork for exports once financing through. Obtaining such financing has been hard, industry and government officials say, for a young industry in a state riddled with a record number of bank failures. `` Wines from a new producing region are greeted with skepticism and I think our wines are beyond that in terms of quality, and I think that will be recognized in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowey </PERSON>, president of the participating <LOCATION> Llano </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Estacado </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. `` We're making a statement about the quality of the wines we produce here,'' said <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, a co-owner of the participating Pheasant Ridge winery, also in <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. Also sending wines are Messina-Hof Wine Cellars in <LOCATION> Bryan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> winery in the Hill Country town of <LOCATION> Tow </LOCATION>, and the <LOCATION> Bluebonnet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Winery </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Ballinger </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> had one winery in 1975 _ today it has 22. Five of those wineries will join 30 others across the country from five other states _ <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ in the first official exhibition of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> wines at <LOCATION> Vin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is sponsoring the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exhibit. It will be among 1,700 at the trade show, where more than 80,000 people are expected _ including wine critics, importers and distributors from 50 countries, according to de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>'s office. `` We are planting the seeds of a long-term harvest,'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> said. `` My interest is that the wine show is looking down the road several years,'' <PERSON> Lowey </PERSON> said Wednesday from <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. `` We're currently selling all of the wine we produce here in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> _ 45,000 cases this year We're very well supported here at home. So we do n't have a lot of wine to go to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> with. I'd like to lay the groundwork for developing a European market, and this is a good vehicle to do that with.'' Interest in American wines is growing and they are now a hot export item, says <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Dugan </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Wine exports rose 64 percent in volume and 75 percent in value in 1987 over 1986, <PERSON> Dugan </PERSON> said Wednesday, for a total value of $ 60.8 million last year. That's still a fraction of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wine market, which had sales of $ 7.2 billion last year of imports and domestic wines. Industry figures indicate wine imports totaled $ 1 billion in 1987, <PERSON> Dugan </PERSON> said. But the depreciating dollar makes American wines a better buy in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> countries like <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, where an upscale segment of the population has plenty of disposable income to afford fine wines and enjoys experimenting with new products, he said. American exporters hope to appeal to that part of the market and are n't attempting to compete with the less expensive Italian wines, <PERSON> Dugan </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> wines, and those from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and other states have an opportunity to find a market niche. ... There's a certain cache in having an unusual American wine,'' <PERSON> Dugan </PERSON> said.
