<SECOND>PM-Oscars-Security,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: Show's Top Cop Confident Of Safety, Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As top cop for the Academy Awards, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s job is to conjure up nightmarish scenarios and make sure he can respond to any calamity that might disrupt <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s biggest night. `` Woe be unto anyone who tries to disrupt the show,'' <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> said. Intruders simply wo n't get past <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s security phalanx at Monday night's 60th annual Oscar ceremony, which has moved to the refurbished Shrine Auditorium five miles south of downtown. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>, 60 _ a former professional wrestler, ex-policeman and retired security chief for <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> _ has been <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON>'s bodyguard for 17 years, and he's ready for just about anything `` By Monday, you just sit back and wring your hands and hope you thought of everything,'' he said. In addition 6,000 of the well-heeled and glamorous, the Academy Awards attracts a worldwide audience of millions, a curbside throng of squealing fans and sometimes a seamy contingent of malcontents, derelicts and fanatics. In the past, there have been bomb threats, political demonstrations, imposters, publicity-seekers and star-struck fans with elaborate schemes to get inside. There has never been a serious offense, however. `` We talk to young people and find out what the latest fad is,'' <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> said, when asked about anticipating untoward acts. `` There was the pie in the face fad, the streaker fad, you name it and there is usually a new fad.'' But discussions with students this year have n't given him any clues. `` Apparently the younger people are more intent on their studies,'' he said. `` We ca n't find any one thing that is really in the mind of the kids. We have to think of everything as being a possibility and use our imaginations.'' Many have tired to pass illicitly through entrances in the past, but only a few have succeeded. There was <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Opel </PERSON>, the infamous on-camera streaker of 1974. <ORGANIZATION> Opel </ORGANIZATION>, since deceased, was able to obtain credentials that permitted him backstage. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> said that security hole has been plugged. `` I have yet to convince myself there was n't some collusion there,'' he said. There was once an imposter in a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Highway Patrol uniform who looked like actor <PERSON> Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrada </PERSON>. And a camper was once flushed out of a Music Center men's room stall the day before the awards show. Demonstrators come almost yearly to the Academy Awards, drawn by the presence of the world's news media or irked by the nomination of a certain movie or star, such as <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON> <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>. Demonstrators clashed with police in 1979 when `` The Deer Hunter'' won best picture and angry <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans surged across the street fronting the Music Center. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> began planning Oscar security in January. He set up shop at the Shrine two weeks before showtime, a week earlier that usual because of the move from the Music Center. His job finishes when the last guest slips away from the post-Oscar Board of Governor's Ball More than 300 officers, under the direction of <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>, will be on hand Monday night, and he is guaranteeing the safety of Academy guests into and out of the area near the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> campus. Once they arrive, they wo n't have to leave, for the renovated Shrine, with new bathrooms, paint, red carpets and air conditioning, will be the site the Governor's Ball, instead of the Beverly Hilton Hotel crosstown. `` It will be a wonderful night,'' <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> said.
