<HEAD>FDA Effectively Bars Home AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has told prospective developers of home AIDS test kits they must limit market research to hospitals, clinics and other traditional health care settings. That and other restrictions contained in a March 30 policy statement effectively bar home test kits by heading off accumulation of the very kind of data that would be needed to convince the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to approve them. Despite the clear signal that the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is not disposed to look kindly on such mass distribution of an AIDS test, the policy letter said the agency will seek public comment that could lead it to revise the guidelines. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> said Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> will publish its guidelines for considering approval of home AIDS test kits in the Federal Register, along with its intention to convene public workshops on the issues surrounding such premarket research. The policy letter went to 17 people or companies who had expressed interest in marketing an AIDS test kit. Those parties, none identified by the agency, had been told earlier that <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> permission would have to be granted before they could be sold. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials have long expressed skepticism about any home AIDS test kit winning approval, because the disease is fatal and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> guidelines say any testing should be accompanied by appropriate counseling. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is a part of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. An official who insisted on anonymity for fear of being accused of prejudging applications before they are filed said the existence of home tests for pregnancy is no argument for the home AIDS tests. The official said the emotional impact of learning one has a life-threatening disease is far different. The policy letter, signed by <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biologics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evaluation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, tells companies not to even bother filing applications for premarket approval unless: _ Their kits are labeled and marketed for professional use only `` within a comprehensive health care environment -LRB- e.g hospitals, medical clinics, doctor's offices, STD clinics, alternative test sites and mental health clinics. -RRB-'' _ Blood is drawn only by a person `` recognized by a state or local authority to perform such procedures'' _ in other words a licensed technician _ The testing sequence includes a currently licensed screening test _ All results are reported directly to professional health care providers for reporting and interpretation of results `` as well as for counseling of the individual.
