<TEXT>
 It remains to be seen if struggling author <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> ever will get his books published, but he's already auctioned off his manuscripts and other memorabilia. He raised $ 965, much less than the $ 15,000 he spent staging to stage it Thursday in the penthouse of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION>, a huge publicity stunt that surpassed even his own expectations. `` I'm thrilled people even thought this was worth something,'' he said. `` We did good.'' <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> watched as an old <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> baseball cap sold for $ 50, a dogeared dictionary for $ 40 and a manuscript of an unpublished book he wrote about the second <PERSON> Claus </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulow </PERSON> trial fetched for $ 270. The money was of little importance. It was television news crews, magazine writers, newspaper reporters and other journalists that he hoped to snare. And snared they were as they came to his show, which included door prizes and an auctioneer who has sold memorabilia of <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Babe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> failed to find a publisher for his first two books so he planned the publicity stunt after finishing his latest novel, `` Run Red Riding Hood Run,'' a book that he said mixes murder, suspense and comedy. As was the case with his books on the second <PERSON> Claus </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulow </PERSON> trial and his experiences at the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, there's no publisher. As part of the hoopla, <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> started the day by marrying <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> Counts at City Hall. He also attempted to lure several better