<HEAD>Report Says Housing Agencies Do Little About Radon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While federal environmental officials say radon gas causes up to 20,000 cancer deaths a year, federal housing agencies see little responsibility to respond, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> says in a new report. The report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, made public Thursday, concludes that agencies in the housing business _ hamstrung in part by a lack of congressional guidance _ do little or nothing about the threat from deadly radon. The report scrutinizes the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Radon is a naturally occurring, odorless and colorless gas. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> says radon may cause from 5,000 to 20,000 lung-cancer deaths annually.
