<HEAD>Church Temporarily Suspends Mediation Effort; New Split in
Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAN1, NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Archbishop <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> called off his attempt to mediate between Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and the opposition, which has refused to negotiate unless the general first agrees to leave the country. Also Thursday, there was a split in the main anti-Noriega coalition. And police using tear gas and rubber hoses dispersed hundreds of anti-government demonstrators in the western city of <PERSON> David </PERSON>. A Roman Catholic church communique said mediation efforts were suspended because the opposition had insisted <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> _ the nation's de facto ruler _ agree to depart and the general had failed to agree in writing to mediation. `` The church in no way surrenders the difficult task of mediation. It still considers it urgent and every day more so,'' said the communique, which asked all parties to remove obstacles so that talks might begin. The opposition <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crusade </ORGANIZATION>, which has led the Panamanian fight to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, said in a statement issued after the church announcement that it stood by its negotiating conditions. A sign from <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> that he was willing to step down remained an `` indispensable and essential condition'' for opening talks, it said. In a communique that was not signed by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the government had agreed to church mediation without preconditions. Earlier Thursday, two leaders of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> announced they were breaking with the 10-month-old Civic Crusade to form the Popular Civic Movement. It was the first major split in the opposition. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Arosemena </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON> told a news conference the new group had the support of the Authentic Panamanian Party, the country's largest opposition party. <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON> said the splinter group also wants <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> out, but thinks it is a job for Panamanians, not Americans. The Civic Crusade's campaign to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, chief of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s 15,000-strong <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, has been backed by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> The new opposition group opposes church mediation and does not recognize <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, deposed by pro-Noriega lawmakers on Feb. 26, as <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s president. Government prosecutor <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Visuetti </PERSON> disclosed Wednesday that an arrest warrant had been issued for <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who is in hiding in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, in a videotape released to <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> Thursday, said he would continue to fight to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who he tried to fire the day before he himself was removed. `` Fellow countrymen, we can not allow a gang of inhuman drug traffickers to be the owners of our public institutions and of the country itself,'' he said. The tape was reported made Thursday. In February, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was indicted in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on federal drug trafficking charges. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has frozen Panamanian deposits in <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> banks, and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s banks closed during the first week of March. Civilian sources contacted by telephone in <PERSON> David </PERSON> said Civic Crusade members were beaten and arrested when police broke up a protest march Thursday evening. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Secchi </PERSON>, a Crusade member, said police used tear gas and rubber hoses to break up the march by more than 500 demonstrators. He said about 15 marchers were arrested. There were no immediate reports of injuries. With the arrival this week of 1,300 extra <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops this week, there now are about 11,800 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to protect the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> and guard American installations. Another 800 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Marines were to arrive today for jungle training that had been scheduled months ago. The Marines are slated to stay for three weeks. Banking officials put an end Thursday to government speculation the country's banks might open today or next week. Sources speaking on condition of anonymity said they feared the government would attempt to bleed deposits for its own use if the banks were to open. Lacking hard cash, the government has failed to meet its payroll for a month. People paid by check can not cash them. Panamanians with dollars are using them sparingly, and many now depend on charity for food.
