<HEAD>Shultz Ends Middle East Tour, But Plans Another Peace Trip To
Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Shultz
^By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> wound up a five-day quest for <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace talks today, acknowledging progress could be measured only in inches. But <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he expects to return to the region _ he did not say when _ to `` to struggle against the odds.'' He said his goal remains a comprehensive settlement between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and its Arab neighbors and self-rule but not statehood for the Palestinians. `` I think the stakes are very high and the opportunities very great, even if the probabilities are against you,'' the secretary told a news conference. He praised King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> for `` having engaged seriously with us for peace in the region.'' Earlier in the week, he called the king `` a partner for peace.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> did not offer an assessment of Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, whose position toward a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace conference was an obstacle <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> could not overcome. The secretary had hoped to convene a peace conference by mid-April to launch talks between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and a mixed delegation of Jordanians and Palestinians. `` I do n't think we are going to make it and that's obvious,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. But he bristled when one of the reporters at a news conference suggested his mission was doomed to failure. `` You have to be willing to do it,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` What am I saving myself for anyway? I have a few more months to go here and I want to try to leave something constructive for the region and for my successors, and so I'm going to put my back into it. Why not?'' The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has a little more than nine months left. The current trip is the third by <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> since October to try to break a 40-year impasse between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and its Arab neighbors. Since early December, Palestinians in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> have been rioting against their Israeli occupiers. At least 141 Arabs and an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldier have been killed in the wave of violence. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> objects to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal for a peace conference because he finds in it opportunities for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to side with the Arabs, as it usually does, and try to impose an unfavorable settlement on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> gave assurances the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would stand by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and not let that happen, but <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> held to his position. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he expected to return `` at some point in the future'' because it takes a special <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort to bring the two sides together. `` You measure headway in inches, not miles,'' he said. The secretary said he was leaving special <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy Wat Cluverius in the region to continue talks.
