<NOTE>For release 11 a.m. EDT, TIME set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Banks Criticize Lender Governments On Third World Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 9, 11, 14 to CORRECT spelling of Schulmann.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A spokesman for the international banking community said today that creditor governments, not banks, have done too little to help Third World countries with their debts. The Third World governments want either grants, more new loans or relief from the burden of paying many billions on old ones every year, said <PERSON> Horst </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulmann </PERSON>, a West German who heads the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION>. `` Creditor governments have not done enough in bilateral relations to provide more official financing, to open their economies, or to improve the regulatory and tax regimes for private lenders and investors,'' said <PERSON> Schulmann </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schulmann </PERSON>'s comments were in a letter to leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a joint group of the fund and its sister organization, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. The fund and bank are owned by 151 countries. Many of those governments' top economic officials, including <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, are expected to attend the two institutions' joint semiannual meetings here next week <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and other government leaders have criticized commercial banks for their slowdown of lending in recent years and have recently been encouraging a `` menu'' of possible actions by the banks. Many of these actions would require the banks to get rid of loans at less than their face value. <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, has quietly suggested that banks might also waive some of the billions of dollars of interest they collect every year. `` We have repeatedly noted the dramatic decline in commercial bank lending to developing countries and stressed the necessity for signficantly increased flows from the private banks as an essential ingredient of the debt strategy,'' he said in a report to be delivered to the Development Committee April 15. <PERSON> Schulmann </PERSON> said many debtor governments have refused to seek the fund's help because it insists on such `` adjustment'' conditions as cutting government subsidies and devaluing currencies that lower their people's living standards. Fund officials argue that Third World countries will be worse off if their govnernments do not ask its help. <PERSON> Schulmann </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> had been only partly successful in getting debtor countries to make similar changes in their policies and that its lending has grown less than expected. `` There is a need for the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to be more innovative in its approach to the debt problem,'' he said. He suggested that it should do more in the way of `` credit enhancements'' _ the kind of financing that lessens risk for banks. <PERSON> Schulmann </PERSON> came out for an issue of `` special drawing rights,'' the fund's own kind of money, to member governments. This measure has long been urged by Third World governments but opposed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on grounds that it would encourage inflation. Third-World debt is expected to reach $ 1.245 trillion at the end of this year.
</TEXT>
