<HEAD>Iranian Elections Under Way, Khomeini Votes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranians voted for a new parliament today, hours after <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> missiles crashed into several cities, in an election that will help determine the course of the Islamic revolution. The nation's 87-year-old revolutionary patriarch, <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, voted at an open-air election station near his home in the northern <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Jamaran </LOCATION>. State-run television showed the black-turbaned leader dropping his ballot into the box, followed by his son <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON>. The elections are the third to the 270-member Majlis, or parliament, since the 1979 revolution toppled the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>. The vote is seen as a test of strength between fundamentalists who support an Islamic-style capitalism and radicals who favor a socialist-style economy. The future course of the Islamic revolution is uncertain, and <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> is reported in ill health. Iranian leaders had expressed fear the Iraqis would blitz <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and other major cities to disrupt the polling, but nevertheless urged the country's more than 20 million voters to cast ballots in defiance. A loud explosion rocked the area near a <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> railroad station just hours before <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s 30,000 polling stations opened. Officials had no immediate details of the blast. But <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio, monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, reported that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> missiles crashed into the capital and the central city of <LOCATION> Isfahan </LOCATION>. It also said <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes raided the western cities of <LOCATION> Bakhtaran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hamadan </LOCATION>, killing an unspecified number of civilians. The official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, did not give any turnout figures but reported the Iranian people's `` massive presence'' at the polling stations <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> declared last week: `` The people will attend the election with God's help, even if they are under missile attack. I will vote under any circumstances.'' He warned: `` The people must beware and choose candidates among ... those loyal to <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>. They must choose their deputies from among those who have suffered from poverty and are real Moslems, not those who obey <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Islam.'' <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> was decked out in election posters, including bedsheet-size cloth banners bearing the names of the candidates. The 7 -LCB- - year-old war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, the country's most pressing problem, has not figured in the campaigning <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has decreed that the war will not end until his adversary, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, has been toppled. About 1,400 candidates ran for the four-year terms as parliamentary deputies. They were approved by provincial and city governors controlled by Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>. That's about 400 more than campaigned in the last election in 1984. This year, for the first time, about 30 women ran. The results may not be known for 10 days, and the new parliament may not sit until June while a new cabinet is screened and nominees scrutinized by the deputies.
