<HEAD>Famous Gorilla `Willie B.' Will Soon Move Outside</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `For Willie ...' to insert dropped word
`will'; Picks up 6th graf, `And zoo ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most famous gorillas, has a new human roommate who's trying to coax the pudgy primate into taking his first step outside in 25 years. Later this month, his keepers at <LOCATION> Zoo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> plan to introduce <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> and his fellow apes to a new outdoor habitat, which replaces the tile walls and steel bars of their old quarters. `` Gorillas tend to be very reticent, and after 25 years in the same place, he's just gotten used to his old home,'' zoo Director <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Maple </PERSON> said. `` This change, although it's a very positive change, is going to be viewed with some suspicion. We're going to have to induce him to enjoy his new habitat. `` Once he gets over this period, we think he's going to really enjoy it.'' For <PERSON> Willie </PERSON>, who arrived in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> 25 years ago at age 3, it might be the first time in his memory that he will have grass beneath his feet and the open sky above his head. And zoo officials have other surprises for <PERSON> Willie </PERSON>. They hope that within a year they can introduce him to another gorilla, probably a female. `` We're going to have to do it very carefully, so they do n't fight too much,'' Maple said Thursday Eventually, he said, it's hoped <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> will breed On Wednesday, Zoo <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> officials gave <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> his first complete physical, then showed him the new indoor quarters he will use for sleep and shelter. They hope he'll get used to that within two weeks, and then, they will open the door. To coax him outside, keepers will place <PERSON> Willie </PERSON>'s food near the exit of his night quarters. He already can see that something is going on; zoo staffers are keeping a round-the-clock watch in the night quarters, including his keeper of 14 years, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, who is sleeping in the next chamber. `` He's literally <PERSON> Willie </PERSON>'s best friend,'' Maple said. `` <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> is a very important part of our strategy of making him comfortable.'' In Wednesday's physical, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. _ named for long-time former <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartsfield </PERSON> _ weighed in at nearly 460 pounds, with a 40-inch neck and a 64-inch chest. That's about 60 pounds overweight, but for a gorilla who's lived in a cage for 25 years, it's not too bad, <PERSON> Maple </PERSON> said. `` The preliminary results are that he's in very good health,'' Maple said. `` We're surprised at his muscle tone and the quality of his condition.'' <PERSON> Willie </PERSON>'s first steps outdoors will be important for him, and equally important for <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Maple </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> named the 99-year-old zoo one of the nation's worst just four years ago, before Maple, a specialist in primate psychology, was hired and launched a plan to convert the old facility into a modern outdoor animal habitat. `` This is the dawning of a new era at <LOCATION> Zoo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; I have no doubt about that,'' he said. `` You can call it one small step for a gorilla, one giant step for gorilla kind _ and certainly for the zoo.''
