<HEAD>Officer Who Waited for Key to Apartment at Scene of Rape Is
Dismissed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city has fired a police officer who waited outside an apartment building for a key for nearly 30 minutes while officials say a 12-year-old girl was being raped inside. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Horka </PERSON>, 39, was dismissed Thursday night after a divided city commission found him guilty of violating five departmental rules. <PERSON> Horka </PERSON>, an officer for 14 years, said he would appeal his dismissal. `` If I could have changed it in any way, if I would have known what was going on, believe me, it would not have happened that way,'' <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> said. `` I still think I did the right thing. No one got killed.'' <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> was accused of breaking 10 department rules. The Police and Fire Commission dismissed the most serious allegation, failing to request assistance at the scene. City attorney <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenfeld </PERSON> said he was shocked by dismissal of that count but pleased that <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> had been dismissed. `` Officers who have a right to carry a gun and a badge have a tremendous obligation to the public,'' <PERSON> Rosenfeld </PERSON> said. `` They must meet that obligation if they wish to remain police officers. In our opinion, Officer <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> did not meet those obligations.'' <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> was found in violation of conduct unbecoming an officer, unsatisfactory performance in the line of duty, improper filing of a report, abuse of command at the scene, and violation of rules. The last means that since <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> was found in violation of any department rule, he was found in violation of that regulation as well. The disciplinary hearings began shortly after <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> and two other officers answered a report of a home invasion on Dec. 21. <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> maintained he did not break into the apartment upon arriving because he feared the assailant might harm the girl and her 10-year-old brother inside. They waited outside almost 30 minutes with the girl's frantic mother for the landlord to bring a key, rather than breaking in to rescue the girl. Four officers later entered the apartment through a back door, which had been unlocked, and arrested <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON> was charged with rape, burglary, home invasion and aggravated kidnapping; he is awaiting trial. The two officers who accompanied <PERSON> Horka </PERSON> also are scheduled for disciplinary hearings.
