<FIRST>r a PM-MarineHearings     04-08 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marine Hearings,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women Investigated In Lesbianism Probe At Marine Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARRIS ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> has carried out `` witch hunts'' for lesbians while tolerating homosexual men, says a Marine who says she is a target in a lesbianism investigation at the service's <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> boot camp. The Corps denies the accusation, although statistics show a disproportionate number of women have been dismissed for homosexuality. The <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation at the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> centers on 10 women and is likely to expand, said the woman <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION>, who denies being homosexual and has not been charged. Five Marine women have been charged with various counts, including committing indecent acts. Two other women who were due to go before administrative hearing boards are seeking discharges. `` Every base I've been on has had one of these so-called witch hunts,'' said the woman, a member of the Marines for six years who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` This is the only time I've know of that anyone has gone to the press.'' She said she did so `` to show there's an injustice being done.'' `` If they're going to conduct these investigations, they need to do it on the male side of the house as well,'' she said. `` It would be such an embarrassment for the men to do this,'' she said. `` They would have to admit that among the few and the proud they also have some gays in there.'' Each year, 20,000 recruits, men and women, pass through <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' only basic training base for woman Marines. There are 10,060 women in the Marines. According to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figures, 90 women and 219 men have been dismissed for homosexuality in the past three federal fiscal years, although women comprise less than 5 percent of the Corps. During the same period, 662 Marine homosexuality cases were investigated, the figures show. About a third of those investigations centered on women. However, <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Schilling </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said lesbians do not get special attention while homosexual men are tolerated. She said there is no clear reason for the disparity and that the matter has never been studied. She said that it would be a commanding officer's responsibility to check out any reported violations of a military law. The <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> investigation is not routine, but `` it's not an unprecedented thing,'' said Maj. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McLean </PERSON>, a base spokesman. The base does n't announce such hearings, but will answer media inquiries about them, <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> said. He said that while records of such cases are usually kept only about two years, he understands there were similar proceedings three or four years ago. The current proceedings are Article 32 hearings, which are similar to civilian grand jury hearings. They amount to an open investigation into the allegations in which the defendants have certain rights and witnesses for both sides can be called. Following the hearing, the investigating officer makes a non-binding recommendation to the Marine's commanding officer The recommendation may be that the charges go to a court-martial, that the Marine go before an administrative discharge board or that the charges be dismissed. An administrative discharge board would determine whether the defendant has the potential for further service. A court-martial could lead to a prison sentence. In addition to committing indencent acts, the defendants face various charges, including dereliction of duty, sodomy, conspiracy to obstruct justice and assault. <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> noted that not all the charges are related to homosexuality and `` in a larger sense, we are talking about breaches of good order and discipline.'' The Corps does n't tolerate homosexuality because it is `` contrary to good order and discipline, not because there is a statement being made about lifestyles,'' he said. He added that recruit training `` must be conducted with the highest standards of order and discipline.''
</TEXT>
