<TEXT>
 Four Israeli troops were wounded today when the army jeep they were in hit a roadside mine in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, an army spokesman said. The spokesman said the troops were patrolling near the village of <LOCATION> Merkaba </LOCATION> in the center of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s self-declared `` security zone'' when they drove by the mine. At the same time, attackers fired at the troops from a distance, the spokesman said. The troops fired back and gave chase to the attackers, who managed to flee the security zone. Two soldiers suffered light wounds and two suffered moderate wounds, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity in line with regulations. The four were evacuated to a hospital. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> established its security zone, a six-to-10-mile wide strip of land north of the Israeli-Lebanese border, when it withdrew the bulk of its troops from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1985 following a three-year occupation. The zone is patrolled by Israeli troops and Israeli-allied Lebanese militiamen.
