<HEAD>Mozambique Blames South Africa For Car Bomb Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government-controlled media blamed <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> today for a car bombing that seriously injured a white member of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> denied responsibility. <PERSON> Albie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>, a South African lawyer, remained in a <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION> hospital after the Thursday morning explosion that occurred as he entered his car outside his apartment in downtown <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>. Sachs was jailed by South African authorities for more than three months without charge in 1963. He also defended members of the congress. The congress, banned in 1960, is the major guerrilla group fighting <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s white-led government. He has lived in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> for 10 years and works at the country's <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>. `` The long and criminal arm of the <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> regime has again reached into <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION> to carrry out another savage and odious crime,'' said <PERSON> Noticias </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION> daily. `` Sachs committed what is, in the eyes of <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, the greatest of all crimes: he frontally opposed apartheid, he openly challenged the racist regime,'' the front-page editorial added. Reports on Mozambican radio and television also blamed <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the national news agency AIM reported. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s government-run television quoted Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roelof </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> as saying that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> `` could not be held responsible for the conflict in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and certainly not for violence which emanated from faction fighting in the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>.'' None of the Mozambican reports cited any evidence linking <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to the blast, but they noted a recent series of attacks carried out against <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> members. At least six congress members have been killed in countries outside <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> this year. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has denied responsibility for the deaths, although it repeatedly warns it will cross its borders in pursuit of members. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lodge </PERSON>, a political scientist at <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> and an expert on the congress, said <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> was a member, but that he was not actively working for the group in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and was not an officer in the organization, which is composed mainly of blacks. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION> condemned the attack and said, `` We note that the incident takes place after several recent attacks against purported members of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>.'' <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> signed a mutual non-aggression pact in 1984, but both sidely regularly accuse the other of violations. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>, born in 1935, was the son of a prominent trade unionist. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> was one of the few whites who participated in the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' defiance campaign that led to the organization's banning in 1960 The campaign urged people to ignore apartheid laws, resulting in thousands of arrests. After being released from detention in 1963, <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> wrote a book about his experiences, `` The Prison Diary of <PERSON> Albie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>,'' which was turned into a stage play in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. He worked in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> before going to <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>. As an employee of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, he had just begun drafting a new family law for <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, AIM said. The explosion shattered windows in the nearby <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION> and hurled pieces of the car as much as 50 yards away, AIM reported. By law and custom in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
