<HEAD>Contras Agree to Resume Peace Talks on April 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 U.S.-supported rebels have agreed to resume high-level talks with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s government to end a nearly 7-year-old civil war, but said several conditions must be fulfilled first. The directorate of the Nicaraguan Resistance said Thursday in a letter that it had agreed to come to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> April 15 for the talks, the first since leaders of the two sides agreed to a cease-fire plan on March 23. The second meeting had been scheduled for April 6, but the Contras said they were postponing it because the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> had failed to fully comply with provisions of the cease-fire agreement signed in the southern border town of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. Defense Minister <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, head of the government delegation and the brother of President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, had offered to hold the negotiations either April 9 or April 15. Spokesmen for the rebels, known as Contras, charged the government withheld newsprint from the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>, violating the accord's provision for full press freedom in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The government also failed to include all the prisoners the Contras had asked for when it released 100 political prisoners on April 1, as called for under the agreement, the Contras said. In Thursday's letter to <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, rebel leaders accepted as an `` involuntary error'' the failure to release all of the requested political prisoners. It said the government lacked enough time to arrange for all of the requested names to be released. Sandinista and Contra military delegations were to continue talks today on technical details of providing humanitarian aid to the rebels and controlling zones where the insurgents are to gather during a 60-day cease-fire that began on April 1. On Thursday, the delegations finished defining exact locations of the seven rebel zones and began considering a 34-point rebel plan governing conduct in those zones, said Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Jaoquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON>, head of the Sandinista military delegation. `` We already have discharged an important part of the agenda, which was the point on localization'' of the zones, <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON> said after Thursday's session in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON> said the government had not formally responded to the 34-point plan presented by the Contras outlining rebel conduct inside the zones. But he said the plan `` has several positive points, that perfectly can be considered by the government.'' The March 23 accord does not specify if and under what conditions the Contras are to lay down their arms. Contra leaders have vowed not to. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Urroz </PERSON>, a member of the rebel military delegation, called for complete Contra autonomy in the zones. `` What we want is that in the zones we have real control,'' <PERSON> Urroz </PERSON> said, adding the rebels were seeking `` security, integrity and communications without interference'' from the government. Still unresolved were pledges of security for the Contras, how they would receive food and other supplies, who would control the areas and how compliance would be verified. Meanwhile, President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> announced his government was prepared to administer a portion of a $ 48 million humanitarian aid package for <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last month to treat Nicaraguan children injured in the civil war. Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> rejected as `` illegal'' plans to have the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGAN