<HEAD>Parliamentary Election Day Announced, Official Campaign Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliamentary campaigning officially began today, and the government set <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> elections for April 26. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> called for fair and orderly elections and warned against any illegal campaigning. The elections will be the first time in 17 years that just one lawmaker is being elected from each district. President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, elected Dec. 16, is seeking a majority in the one-house legislature. Division among opposition parties may give the governing party the edge. Candidates immediately began to register with the committee. About 1,300 candidates were expected to register by the Wednesday deadline. Some campaigning already has begun, with posters going up in many places and politicians taking advantage of various gatherings to attack the opposing side. Under a new constitution that took effect Feb. 25 aimed at democratic reform, 224 lawmakers will be elected to four-year terms from single-member districts. An additional 75 seats will be decided under a bonus system based on the parties' nationwide polling strength. In recent elections, two lawmakers were elected from each district, but that system has been scrapped in response to public criticism that voters' wishes were not truly represented when the first runners-up were elected too. The governing party is hoping for a total of 163 seats in the direct voting, giving it 55 percent of the 299 assembly seats. In the presidential elections on Dec. 16, <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> won with just 36.6 percent of the vote. Main opposition leaders <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Young-sam </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON