<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Following is a chronology of the major events in the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> war:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1978</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 APRIL 27-28 _ Pro-Soviet Marxist party of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> overthrows republic and installs <PERSON> Nur </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Taraki </PERSON> as president. Armed, non-communist resistance begins.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1979</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 SEPTEMBER _ <PERSON> Taraki </PERSON> killed in intraparty showdown with deputy <PERSON> Hafizullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Amin </PERSON>. DEC. 24 _ Soviets begin massive airlift to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> that brings 40,000 troops to the country within days. DEC. 27 _ Amin killed and replaced by President <PERSON> Babrak </PERSON> <PERSON> Karmal </PERSON> in coup reputedly backed by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1980</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 JANUARY _ <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> demands `` immediate, unconditional and total withdrawal of foreign troops'' from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> announces sanctions against <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. JUNE 25 _ Soviets reject <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s proposal for settlement.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1981</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 APRIL _ President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lifts grain embargo imposed on <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1982</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 APRIL _ Number of Afghan refugees in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, rear base of Afghan guerrillas, reported at 2.5 million. JUNE _ In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> conducts first indirect peace talks between <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which speaks for Afghan resistance.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1984</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 JANUARY _ Guerrillas gain temporary control of <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>, the second-largest city in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. APRIL _ Soviets begin saturation bombing of guerrilla strongholds and villages.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1985</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 MAY _ In <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, fundamentalist Moslem guerrillas join moderates to form seven-party coalition. DECEMBER _ <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> offers timetable for Soviet withdrawal.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1986</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 MAY _ <PERSON> Karmal </PERSON> replaced by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, former head of secret police. SEPTEMBER _ Guerrillas, supported by significant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms shipments, reportedly receive first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Stinger anti-aircraft missiles. Within months, they reportedly shoot down average of one enemy aircraft per day. MID-OCTOBER _ 8,000 of the more than 100,000 Soviet soldiers withdraw from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 JAN. 15 _ Guerrillas reject any power-sharing with Communists. NOV. 30 _ <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> says Soviet soldiers could be withdrawn in 12-month period.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 FEBRUARY _ Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> offers to withdraw Soviet troops beginning May 15, if <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks produce accord by March 15. MARCH _ New round of U.N.-mediated talks begins in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. Talks stalled by disagreements between <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> over continued foreign aid to warring sides and makeup of future Afghan government. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviets disagree on military aid to rebels and government. APRIL 3-6 _ <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to work out plan to pull out Soviet troops in event negotiations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> fail to produce accord to end war. APRIL 7 _ <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> meet and issue statement saying all obstacles have been cleared in negotiations to end war and Soviets hope to start pulling their troops out in May. APRIL 8 _ <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> announces a peace settlement to end the war is completed and ready to be signed by April 14. Details of the accord, which calls for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to sign as guarantors, are not disclosed.
