<HEAD>Smog-Covered Soviet City Site of Mass Anti-Pollution Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 10,000 residents of an industrial city in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> staged a street demonstration to protest smog that has burned skin and caused lung and heart problems, a newspaper reported. <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION>, the daily of the youth organization <ORGANIZATION> Komsomol </ORGANIZATION>, said the protesters in the city of <PERSON> Nizhny </PERSON> <PERSON> Tagil </PERSON> demanded that two 45-year-old coke-burning furnaces at a steel plant be closed. `` Who will answer for the 54 stillborn children in 1987?'' a crying woman said at the demonstration. <PERSON> Komsomolskaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Pravda </PERSON> did not say when the protest occurred in the city of 405,000 people 900 miles east of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, but it appeared to have been in February or March. There have been several reports of environmental protests in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> since Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came to power three years ago and encouraged freer expression. <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION>, in an article published Wednesday, said the government lists <PERSON> Nizhny </PERSON> <PERSON> Tagil </PERSON> among the 50 Soviet cities whose pollution level exceeds sanitary standards. Smog is common in the city, and in the morning, the faces of children on the way to kindergarten burn, the newspaper said. One doctor said the number of children hospitalized for serious lung and heart ailments caused by pollution had risen by 33 percent. He did n't say over what period. A commission of the Presidium of the Russian republic's Council of Ministers, the republic's highest governmental body, ordered the two coke-burning furnaces at the <ORGANIZATION> Nizhny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tagil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metallurgical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Complex </ORGANIZATION> closed last September because of excessive pollution, the newspaper said. But the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ferrous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metallurgy </ORGANIZATION> decided to keep the furnaces open until new, cleaner furnaces were completed. The complex, which includes plants that build railroad cars and boilers, and a cement factory, spews out 629,000 tons of harmful substances a year, according to <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION>. The health problems led to what <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> called `` an explosion in public consciousness.'' Children sent the top party official of the metallurgical complex drawings of `` smokestacks, smog enveloping living areas and the handwritten words: ` I do n't want to die!''' After the demonstration, the minister of ferrous metallurgy ordered one of the two coke furnaces stopped, but the other `` continues to pollute the city,'' the newspaper said. A petition signed by 8,500 <PERSON> Nizhny </PERSON> <PERSON> Tagil </PERSON> residents demanding further action has been sent to the national <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, the newspaper said.
