<HEAD>Steiger Guilty Of Theft By Extortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BURT GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former top aide to impeached Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> has been convicted of theft by extortion for threatening a parole board member to get him to support a <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> appointee. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON>, 59, a former five-term congressman, was found guilty Thursday by a <ORGANIZATION> Maricopa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury that deliberated for 3 -LCB- hours. Neither <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> nor his attorney, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Karas </PERSON>, would say whether they planned an appeal. `` We'll take it one step at a time,'' <PERSON> Karas </PERSON> said. `` It's safe to say I'm not real pleased,'' <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> was found guilty of threatening to withhold permission for <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a member of the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pardons </ORGANIZATION> and Paroles, to work as a part-time <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION> justice of the peace, and threatening to remove him from the board unless he voted to retain executive director <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mecham </LOCATION> appointee. Judge <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinstein </PERSON> scheduled a May 6 sentencing for <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON>, who faces up to five years in prison. <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> is free on his own recognizance. `` We do n't take joy in a conviction, but we feel it was a fair trial,'' said prosecutor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Cudahy </PERSON>, an assistant attorney general. `` We felt it was a just verdict.'' Jury foreman <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said the deciding factor behind the verdict was `` the tapes of the phone call between <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> called <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> at home from the office of the state attorney general, who recorded the call. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said the jurors had no difficulty reaching a verdict. `` We listened to all the tapes and examined all the evidence again, but it was unanimous,'' he said. <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON>, asked what he'd do differently, said: `` I'd have probably hung up on <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> when he called me at home.'' Reached shortly after the verdict was announced, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> said, `` I'm sad to hear it. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> meant no harm to anybody, and I'm sorry to hear it.'' <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was removed from office Monday when the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted him of two impeachment charges. <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> denied on the stand Monday that he threatened <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> or told him how he should vote. But the state alleged that <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> followed up on the alleged threat in a letter and a telephone conversation after <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> voted with the board majority to seek Ms. <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>'s resignation on grounds of low staff morale. <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> testified that he did suggest that <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> should back Ms. <PERSON> Costello </PERSON> but denied that he tried to `` steal'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s vote by threatening his job. He acknowledged lying to an attorney general's investigator when he originally denied making the threat. <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> gave up his 3rd Congressional District seat in 1976 to run unsuccessfully for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>.
