<HEAD>Long Feud Between Texaco And Pennzoil Ends Quietly In Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf, `As a ...,' to explain why
transfer was made in four payments. A version moving on financial
wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the end, the four-year corporate war that forced oil giant <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy and the largest civil award in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history came down to a silent, 10-minute electronic payment of $ 3 billion to <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>. The transfer settling <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s takeover lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> took place Thursday in a high-security room at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank-Houston </ORGANIZATION> _ and, coincidentally, halfway between <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> headquarters and the Texaco Building. As a half-dozen tight-lipped bank and <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> executives watched, a green computer screen signaled the arrival of four <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> payments, starting at 10:03 a.m. and ending at 10:13 a.m.. About a dozen reporters and photographers watched The transfer had to be broken down into four payments, since the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> can transfer amounts only as high as one cent short of $ 1 billion. When the transfer was complete, a few people applauded. `` We're all very glad it's all over,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> assistant treasurer. `` Quite frankly, we've been in a holding pattern for over four years,'' <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Liedtke </PERSON> said later Thursday. `` We think we're now in a position to invest these funds and to make up for lost time,'' <PERSON> Liedtke </PERSON> said. The settlement of the suit, which stemmed from <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s 1984 acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Getty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, allowed the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based company to emerge from bankruptcy protection. It was part of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s bankruptcy reorganization plan, which a federal judge approved March 23. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> also will begin paying $ 2.6 billion to other creditors. <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>, looking for long-term ways to invest the windfall, actually borrowed $ 3 billion a couple of weeks ago so it could begin investing it in an orderly manner, spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said. The war began with <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s acquisition of <PERSON> Getty </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> sued <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, claiming interference with a planned merger between <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Getty </LOCATION>. In November 1985, a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> jury shocked <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> by agreeing with <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> and awarding the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> company $ 10.53 billion in damages, the largest civil award in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. A state appeals court upheld the verdict, but reduced the $ 3 billion in punitive damages to $ 1 billion. Nearly a year ago, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> filed for bankruptcy protection, saying it had to do so to avoid posting a potentially ruinous appeal bond. In November, the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to hear <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal and let the verdict stand <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> then said it was going to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, but a committee of shareholders proposed the settlement. The premise of <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s case was that a handshake and a person's word was as good as a written contract, and that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> violated that rule by plucking <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> from <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s grasp. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> contended <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> had invited it to bid and that there was no valid contract between <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> because all the papers had not been signed by the appropriate parties. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> also put <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' court system under scrutiny, challenging the trial judge's credentials and complaining that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judges were influenced by large campaign contributions from <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamail </PERSON>, who led the <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> case. Although he was delighted to settle the case, <PERSON> Liedtke </PERSON> said the outcome probably was not as good for <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> as gaining <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> would have been. `` I do n't think that -LRB- $ 3 billion -RRB- in any way replaces totally the loss the company has suffered. But it remains to be seen how astutely these funds are reinvested and perhaps we can make up for lost ground,'' he said. Attorney's fees, including <PERSON> Jamail </PERSON>'s, come to about $ 400 million, according to <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jamail </PERSON> declined to reveal his share. `` I'll spend -LRB- the money -RRB- on the important things like whiskey and women,'' he said, smiling. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> officials had no comment on the payment. <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> also announced Thursday that its board adopted a new anti-takeover defense, a preferred stock purchase rights plan, to replace a similar `` poison pill'' put in place after the jury made its award. The old plan was designed to block a corporate raider from appropriating the benefits of the <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> case before it had been resolved, <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said. The new plan also was designed to protect <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> from `` unfair or coercive actions by opportunistic parties'' and give <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> time to make acquisitions using the <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> money, <PERSON> Liedtke </PERSON> said.
