<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSVirus     04-08 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Virus,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Step In Activation Of AIDS Virus Discovered By Scientists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The AIDS virus must make a precise change in its protein coat before it can infect cells, and drugs that can block that change might be able to prevent AIDS infections, researchers say in a study published today. The researchers, from the <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, said they do n't know whether such drugs could be developed in a form that could make tham safe and effective for use in humans. The scientists discovered that the AIDS virus, a piece of genetic material housed in a complex envelope of fats and proteins, can infect cells only if its outer envelope protein is clipped into two pieces. If this cleavage does n't occur, the virus particles assemble and appear normal but are disarmed and unable to infect new cells, said the leader of the study, Dr. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McCune </PERSON>, who works in the lab of Dr. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Weissman </PERSON>, professor of pathology at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION>'s School of Medicine. The results appear today in the journal Cell. The scientists demonstrated their findings by constructing a mutant strain of the AIDS virus that could not complete the critical step. They found it was unable to enter and infect human cells in tissue culture. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome has struck 58,270 people since June 1981, the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> reported this week. The disease has killed 32,545. The researchers believe the cleavage step is critical to the virus' infectivity because it makes the virus' envelope protein `` sticky,'' which allows it to fuse to the membrane of a cell it seeks to infect. After the virus has fused to the cell's membrane, it can enter the cell and remain hidden from the body's immune system, reproduce and eventually begin to spread infection throughout the body. The scientists believe that if they can prevent the AIDS virus from sticking to cells, they might be able to suppress infection. The study was sponsored by grants from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
