<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Mount </PERSON> is a man of contradictions. Born and raised in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, he has the accent and manners of a British gentleman. A published biographer and <ORGANIZATION> Guggenheim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> fellow, he wears natty suits from the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Perhaps the biggest contradiction, however, is whether he is a scholarly collector of rare documents or a thief. Today a jury will be asked to decide if he is a scholarly collector of rare documents or a thief. Closing arguments were expected to be completed by midday, with jury deliberation to follow. Mount is charged with interstate transportation of stolen goods, letters and documents he allegedly stole from the <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>. The charge carries a possible sentence of 10 years in prison and $ 500,000. Mount's friends say the charges are unbelievable. His lawyer says they are unprovable. `` I do n't think he could have done it psychologically,'' said <LOCATION> Gloucester </LOCATION> artist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Manship </PERSON>, who testified for <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> during his three-week trial. `` He has too much respect for history and scholarship to steal from archives.'' An engaging man with a sharp wit and piercing blue eyes, <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> contends he has been reduced to poverty since the government seized his savings. He was evicted from his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> boarding house and has stayed at a YMCA during the trial. The court rejected his pleas for money to bring witnesses over from <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> who he claims can prove his ownership of the documents. `` I'm not allo