<FIRST>r a PM-CDC-Flu     04-08 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC-Flu,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Separate Flu Variations Floating Around U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dominant type of flu this season has evolved into four separate variations, complicating the task of developing the proper vaccine for next winter, federal health officials say. Deaths from influenza and pneumonia have exceeded the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>'s statistical `` epidemic threshold'' for the past seven weeks. That figure is one indicator that the flu season remains under way _ although the agency does not attempt to tabulate the specific numbers of Americans dying from flu. Data is collected from 121 cities but the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> does not attempt to project a national figure. Although the 1987-1988 flu season is winding down, some activity continues, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> reported `` widespread'' flu outbreaks last week _ covering areas including more than half the population. Eight other states _ <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ reported less severe `` regional'' outbreaks. The type A-H3N2 flu prevalent this season has long been associated with `` excess mortality,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. Late last year, when the influenza season got under way, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> saw evidence of an apparent `` drift'' in the type A-H3N2, one of three major types of flu. The A-H3N2 virus, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said at the time, was `` drifting'' away from the <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> flu, the A-H3N2 strain the 1987-1988 flu vaccine was designed to stop, and toward a somewhat different form. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday in its weekly report it has now identified four different variants of A-H3N2 flu virus circulating in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in recent months; they are known as the <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> flu, the <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> flu, the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> flu and the <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> flu. The 1987-88 vaccine did not protect patients against the various A-H3N2 viruses `` as well as it could have against -LRB- the -RRB- <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> -LRB- flu -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaventa </PERSON>, a researcher with the influenza branch. The four different viruses present a problem for immunization experts, Ms. <PERSON> Gaventa </PERSON> said. The Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Immunization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Practices </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> each year recommends which flu types the next winter's vaccine should protect against, and which specific strains of those types should be targeted The reports of the four different A-H3N2 strains circulating this past winter `` will be used in deciding which H3N2 antigen to use'' in next winter's vaccine, Ms. <PERSON> Gaventa </PERSON> said. A flu vaccine ca n't protect optimally against four different flu viruses belonging to the same type, she said. Instead, vaccine experts will try to determine which virus to target, and how much protection that vaccine might offer against closely related viruses. <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> recommends flu vaccine particularly for older people and those who might be prone to severe complications from the flu.
</TEXT>
