<SECOND>PM-Unhealthy Buildings,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy-Efficient Buildings May Pose Health Risk, Researchers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Poor indoor air quality caused by energy-efficient heating, cooling and ventilation systems is a serious health problem that may be aggravated by ignorance among contractors, says an industry spokesman commenting on a study released today. The study found that <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> trainees housed in modern barracks were about 50 percent more likely to contract a respiratory infection during basic training than those who stayed in older, better ventilated buildings. The study examined the incidence of influenza and other respiratory illnesses among about 400,000 trainees at four <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> training centers from October 1982 to September 1986. The study says the findings may apply to office buildings and other structures designed for maximum energy efficiency. `` In tight buildings with closed ventilation systems, airborne-transmitted pathogens are not only recirculated and concentrated but also efficiently dispersed through indoor living spaces,'' the researchers wrote in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. By contrast, in ` leaky'' older buildings, `` airborne-transmitted agents are diluted by fresh, outdoor air and -LRB- are -RRB- relatively quickly exhausted from indoor spaces,'' said the researchers from the <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insitute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` It is a serious problem, and there's a lot of talk about it ... but it does n't seem like too many people are doing too many things to correct it. Maybe it's because they do n't know what to do to correct it,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bevirt </PERSON>, director of research for the <ORGANIZATION> Sheet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conditioning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contractors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` As soon as you take in additional ventilation, you're losing more energy ... and so it's a trade-off'' between energy efficiency and air quality, he said in a telephone interview Thursday. Although there are modern ventilation systems that offer energy efficiency as well as improved air quality, they tend to be more expensive and many contractors may not know about them, <PERSON> Bevirt </PERSON> said. His association is putting together a manual for its members worldwide that includes information on how to test air quality and what can be done to maximize it while offering energy efficiency as well, he said. Most office buildings and other structures built during the energy-conscious 1970s feature tight insulation and ventilation systems designed to keep outside air outside, <PERSON> Bevirt </PERSON> said. In such buildings, `` Up to 95 percent of the air in the building is recirculated,'' exposing occupants to used air that may be filled with viruses and other contaminants, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> institute. The <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> study was not the first to examine the so-called `` sick building syndrome,'' but it covered a larger population over a longer time period, <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Thursday. The researchers, led by Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON>, noted that respiratory tract infections are the most common infectious illnesses in adults. They said recent studies indicate that such infections annually account for 75 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> physician visits, 1.25 million hospitalizations, $ 15 billion in direct medical costs and about 150 million lost work days. <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said the Army is reviewing the study's results to see how much the building-related illnesses cost and whether any changes are needed in the design and construction of its buildings.
