'' in those parts of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> under guerrilla control. Not all the leaders of the seven-party resistance agreed that formation of a guerrilla government was a good idea. <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Gailani </PERSON> of the moderate <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION> said it could cut the nation in half. `` If there are two governments in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, there is the danger of partition into north and south or east and west, as with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, or East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>,'' he said, advocating a transitional government in exile until the pro-Kremlin regime is overthrown. One congressional source who closely follows events in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> reached a similar conclusion, based on the formation of a new province in northern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, where the Soviets have taken steps to fortify natural gas fields. The guerrillas also are split over whether <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> should have an Islamic or secular government. <PERSON> Yunis </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalis </PERSON> of the hardline <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-i-Islami </ORGANIZATION> faction said that `` colonialist countries, the superpowers _ East or <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> _ have joined hands to prevent the creation of a total Islamic government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' Soviet analysts believe the pro-Kremlin government has a good chance of surviving. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> sent a cable to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last September advising the Soviets that <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s 110,000 troops in the arm