 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> today confirmed that Soviet troops will begin leaving <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15 but said it was not a present to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> reported. The broadcast said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> made the declaration during an address to <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials in the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION>, where he met Thursday with Afghan leader <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. `` At the same time, the Soviet leader said the withdrawal of the troops should not be regarded as a sort of present to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on the eve of his visit to the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> plans to visit <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from May 29 to June 2 for his fourth summit with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> also broadcast the news that an agreement to end the Afghan war had been completed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and was ready to be signed. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> that a signing ceremony is expected to take place Thursday. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> announced after their Taskkent meeting that all obstacles to a peace agreement had been removed. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said then that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s troops could start leaving on May 15 if the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords were signed soon. Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979. An estimated 115,000 are helping the Marxist government fight Moslem insurgents. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has bee