<HEAD>Shultz Ends Trip Without Middle East Breakthrough</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Shultz arrival in Washington mid-evening EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> headed for home Friday without a breakthrough on <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace talks, but he vowed to find the time to try again `` and struggle against the odds.'' En route, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> made a surprise stop in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> to make some headway on a new power-sharing arrangement in battered <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> helicopter flew Lebanese President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayal </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to meet with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said <PERSON> Gemayal </PERSON> was willing to consider Syrian demands to dilute the powers of his office, which traditionally is reserved for a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> worked out the terms with Syrian President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> on Tuesday. The Syrian leader did not offer to withdraw his army from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is hoping that could occur if the country, torn by civil war for 12 years, is stabilized. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> cautioned reporters in an airborne news conference not to assume the surge of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> diplomacy `` means some big new development in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> or on the hostages.'' Nine Americans are being held hostage in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> by groups that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> terrorism experts believe are controlled by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. In acknowledging only `` inches'' of progress over six days in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> did not assign blame to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, the key parties who did not accept his proposals. And he said he was not discouraged. `` Whether you are discouraged or not has to do with your expectations of what might happen,'' he said. `` If you have the expectation everything all of a sudden is going to fall into place you'd be discouraged, but I am not that naive to think the difficult problems fall away.'' In fact, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, `` I think we've probably gotten a little further than I expected we might. So we'll keep at it. And I will find time, as time goes along, to come back and work at it myself.'' After several days of praising King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> for taking a `` constructive' approach to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan for negotiations and implying <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> had not, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said: `` The Israelis are as interested in peace and stability as <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and the Palestinians, perhaps even more so.'' He said both <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> had urged him to keep at it, although <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> still has `` reservations'' about a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace conference. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> had hoped such a meeting could be called in mid-April, but he acknowledged that obviously was now impossible. He said he had not altered the `` time line'' of his proposal, however. It calls for a conference attended by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to launch negotiations shortly afterward on Palestinian self-rule. The talks would be held between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and a mixed delegation of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and Palestinians, approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The self-rule would give Palestinians on the Israeli-held <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> control over their daily lives, but not over security or foreign affairs for three years. Meantime, wider negotiations on an overall settlement of the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> dispute would begin seven months after the opening of the first stage of the talks. `` There's a big need, and a very explosive kind of area,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said of his determination to hold negotiations before the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration leaves office next January. `` So it's worth swimming upstream under the circumstances.'' Earlier, at a news conference in <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, his last shuttle stop, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> dismissed a reporter's suggestion his mission was doomed to failure. `` Who's afraid to struggle against odds?,'' he said. `` You have to be willing to do it. What am I saving myself for anyway? `` I've a few more months to go here and I want to try to leave something constructive for the region and for my successors, so I am going to put my back into it. Why not?''
