<HEAD>Stamp Sales Swamp Some Post Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shortages of 3-cent stamps are being reported at some post offices, but depleted inventories are being rapidly refilled, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. `` The stamps are out there, but some offices have a lot more than others,'' spokeswoman <PERSON> Tanya </PERSON> <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> said. More than 1 billion 3-cent stamps were sent to local post offices in preparation for the rate change, from 22 cents to 25 cents, last Sunday, <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> said. And another 600 million of the 3-cent stamps are in warehouses, being used to replenish stocks where needed, she said. `` We had asked local offices to predict how many they would need, and some had a lot more demand than expected. We've been filling orders all week,'' <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> said. Sales of coils of 100 of the stamps have been especially heavy, she said, rather than people buying just a few stamps to tide them over. On the other hand, <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> said plenty of the undenominated `` E'' stamps remain available. Some 6 billion E-stamps, which represent the new 25-cent rate, have been shipped to post offices. Apparently, <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> said, people are choosing to buy 3-cent stamps in order to use up the 22-cent stamps they had on hand, before buying the new higher rate stamps. <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> said that the stamp shortages are scattered across the country, rather than being confined to any particular area. Most offices also have 1-cent and 2-cent stanps available, she added, and stamps can also be purchased by mail and telephone.
