<HEAD>Probe Continues Into Drug Error That Killed Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No punitive action was planned and no charges were filed against a hospital where a man died after he was injected with the wrong drug while undergoing kidney dialysis, officials said. <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Carillo </PERSON>, 68, died Wednesday at Our Lady Of <ORGANIZATION> Lourdes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION>. He and two other elderly patients went into cardiac arrest after a technician accidentally injected them Wednesday with the wrong drug, authorities said. Investigations by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Prosecutor <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Asbell </PERSON> show that a technician accidently gave the patients an injection of the painkiller lidocaine instead of mannitol, which regulates blood pressure. The other two patients, a man and a woman, were revived and were in stable condition, hospital officials said. `` There's no criminality. It's a mistake. It's considered accidental,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerns </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Asbell </PERSON>'s office, said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said no punitive action by the department was planned. She said an initial report by a team of nurses from the health department said three certified kidney technicians working under a supervising nurse were involved. She said a bottle of lidocaine was incorrectly placed on a shelf where mannitol is stored. The technicians removed the lidocaine from the shelf without looking at the label and injected the patients, Ms. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said. Lidocaine is used in kidney dialysis as an anesthestic to numb the area where a large needle is inserted, while mannitol is used to stimulate kidney functions, Ms. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said. She said the kidney center staff has removed all lidocaine from the dialysis area and will use a topical anesthetic in its place. Kidney dialysis machines purify a patient's blood if the kidneys do n't function. The center has given 300,000 treatments since opening in 1969, officials said.
