<HEAD>Police Disperse Anti-Bases Demonstrators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police today dispersed about 800 demonstrators who tried to rally in front of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy calling for the dismantling of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> military bases in the country. Police said at least 20 police officers suffered minor injuries. Three demonstrators were arrested, they said. The demonstrators were negotiating with police officials late in the afternoon when a group of protesters dashed across the street towards the embassy. The police gave chase, using riot clubs, while another group succeeded in going to the side of the embassy. Other demonstrators hurled stones at the riot police. A fire truck opened their water cannons against the demonstrators who scurried into sidestreets fronting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy. Earlier, the demonstrators were chanting `` dismantle the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases'' and `` down with imperialists'' as they arrived near the embassy from a downtown plaza. Police Col. <PERSON> Conrado </PERSON> <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> said at least 20 policemen suffered stoning and clubbing injuries. A rally official who spoke on condition of anonymity said they had no figures on how many demonstrators were injured but said two leaders were apprehended by police. Police could not immediately confirm the arrest of the two officials but said they arrested three other demonstrators. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> began talks last Tuesday on the status of American military bases here. The outcome of the talks, expected to last three months, will determine whether the government allows the bases to remain after their lease expires in 1991. The six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases are the largest American installations left in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, head of the American negotiating p