<HEAD>Pope Denounces Abuses, Seeks Settlement with Rebel Bishop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Friday condemned doctrinal and liturgical abuses in the Roman Catholic church and said he still hopes for a settlement with rebel French Archbishop <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>. `` The need to distinguish from what authentically builds up the church from what destroys her is becoming in the present period a particular demand of our service to the whole community of believers,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> wrote Cardinal <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratzinger </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s powerful guardian of church orthodoxy. <PERSON> Ratzinger </PERSON>'s Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith has worked toward reaching a settlement with <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>, who heads the traditionalist <ORGANIZATION> Pius </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> X </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fraternity </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> was suspended from his priestly functions by <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> VI </PERSON> in 1976, meaning he is not allowed by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> to say Mass or give the sacraments. He continues to celebrate the forbidden 16th century Latin Tridentine Mass and claims to have millions of followers worldwide. In October, the pope charged Cardinal <PERSON> Edouard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON> with the task of trying to resolve the <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> case. <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> has ordained illegally more than 200 priests in the past 15 years. In February, he was quoted in an interview with the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> newspaper <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Figaro </PERSON> as saying he planned to consecrate three bishops this June, a move that would lead to his automatic excommunication. `` Your Eminence knows very well how many efforts have been made by the Apostolic See since the beginning of the existence of the ` fraternity,' in order to ensure ecclesial unity in relation to its activity,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Ratzinger </PERSON> in a letter released by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. `` I would assure your eminence once more of my desire that these efforts should continue. We do not cease to hope that ... they will bear fruit,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> wrote. Also referring to <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> wrote: `` All the bishops of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> ... are bound to collaborate with the Apostolic See for the welfare of the whole mystical body, which is also the body of the churches.'' In his letter, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said the church was striving to ensure that the doctrine of the 1962-65 Second Vatican Council was being followed. `` However, side by side with this effort there have appeared tendencies which create a certain difficulty in putting the council into practice,'' the letter said. `` One of these tendencies is characterized by a desire for changes which are not always in harmony with the teaching and spirit of Vatican Council II.'' `` These changes claim to express progress,'' the letter continued, `` and so this tendency is given the name ` progressivism.' In this case, progress consists in an aspiration towards the future which breaks with the past, without taking into account the function of tradition, which is fundamental to the church's mission.'' The pope also denounced what he described as the opposite tendency of `` conservatism'' or `` integrism.'' This tendency `` stops at the past itself, without taking into account the correct aspiration towards the future,'' he wrote.
