<HEAD>Campus and Health Editions Being Scrapped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> has decided to end its special editions, <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> on Campus and <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, both of which have been losing money. The decision was disclosed to the magazines' staffs on Thursday, said <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION>'s communications director. No editorial staff members will lose their jobs but six space sellers for the publications will be let go, she said. The publications' revenue came solely from advertising. <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, a quarterly that prints 500,000 copies and mails them to 250,000 doctors' and dentists' offices, will bow out after the spring issue. Newsweek on Campus will have two more editions, in May and September. Its 1.3 million copies are inserted into school newspapers at more than 200 colleges and universities and also are mailed to students who subscribe to <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION>. To cope with a 20 percent rise in print and postage costs, <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> also will raise its basic subscription rate by about 10 percent. The weekly's circulation is 94 percent by subscription and 6 percent at the $ 2 cover price at newsstands. <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION>'s current circulation base is 3,198,000, <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> said. The magazine is owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>.
