<SECOND>AM-Plastics Recycling,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Code on Plastic Bottles Intended to Promote Recycling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Plastic bottles soon will carry a single-digit number inside a triangle on the bottom to help guide recyclers and promote the practice, a plastics industry group said Friday. The numbers, a half-inch high or larger, will designate the kind of plastic used, according to Council on Plastics and Packaging in the Environment. `` There is a perception that plastics are not recyclable,'' but it is untrue, said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabourin </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Wellman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, a major buyer of used polyethylene terephthalate, or PET, soft drink bottles. <PERSON> Sabourin </PERSON> said his company buys 100 million pounds of used bottles a year, about two-thirds of the 20 percent of all PET bottles that are recycled. It could use twice as many bottles and in a few years could need three times the current amount, he said. `` The industry feels it's better to self-regulate than to be regulated,'' said <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Stack </PERSON>, recycling manager for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drink </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The council called a news conference to present its view that trash disposal should make room for recycling, incineration, landfilling and composting. Plastics, it said, are 7.2 percent of the national garbage stream of 133 million tons a year. The council knows of at least 256 bills in 35 state legislatures, `` probably more than on any other issue around,'' dealing with garbage, said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. There have been several bills that would simply outlaw certain plastic containers, although none has passed above the local level, <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said. Several other bills would require some form of recycling code. The voluntary identification system devised by the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plastics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> calls for number codes on all plastic bottles of 16 ounces or larger, and other containers of 8 ounces or more. Almost all recycling markets are designed to handle one kind of plastic at a time, though various efforts are under way to develop techniques to separate mixed plastics. The triangle surrounding the number will have an arrowhead incorporated in each side, the arrows pointing clockwise. Underneath will be letter abbreviations or acronyms representing the plastic. Codes should start appearing within six months and appear on all containers within three years, <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said. Currently, soft drink bottles are almost made of PET, and milk bottles are high-density polyethylene, and recyclers can recognize these easily. These materials and other plastics are used in other containers that could be recycled if they could be quickly identified also, the council said. Here are number and abbreviation codes: 1. Polyethylene terephthalate, PET. 2. High-density polyethylene, HDPE. 3. Vinyl, V. 4. Low-density polyethylene, LDPE. 5. Polypropylene, PP. 6. Polystyrene, PS 7. Other plastics, including bottles of more than one kind, OTHER.
