<HEAD>Foreign Relief Workers Leave Drought-Stricken Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign relief workers on Friday began complying with a government order to return from the drought-stricken north where civil war has stymied efforts to feed millions of people threatened with starvation. About 24 expatriates returned to <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, the capital, aboard a U.N.-chartered Hercules C-130 transport plane. Two of the aircraft had been used to carry food into the most severely drought-affected regions of Tigre and <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>. The returning workers included employees of the Geneva-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Belguim </LOCATION> group <ORGANIZATION> Medicin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Frontieres </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Doctor Without Borders -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internationale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Faim </ORGANIZATION>. They had been operating out of the Eritrean town of <LOCATION> Asmara </LOCATION> and are among about 60 expatriates sent to the north, where crop failure threatens more than 3 million people with starvation. It was unclear when the rest of the foreign relief personnel in other northern towns would be pulled out. The government <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday ordered all relief agencies to bring its foreign workers from the north `` to avoid personnel security risks'' from rebels operating in the area. The commission said it would assume responsibility for the massive relief operation, which already had been crippled by the civil wars in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and Tigre. The order came a week after President <PERS