<HEAD>Official Presidential Election Campaign Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The presidential campaign opened Friday, a race with few new faces and fewer new ideas that has evolved into a battle of personalities among the three major candidates. President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, a Socialist seeking a second seven-year term, continues to hold a wide lead in public opinion polls over conservative Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, 55, and former center-right Premier <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, 63. The other six candidates in the race stand little chance of accomplishing more than using the election to expound their ideas, ranging from radical left to extreme right. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, 71, will have no trouble winning the most votes in the April 24 first round, though he is likely to fall considerably short of an absolute majority. The real contest is between <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> for the No. 2 spot and the right to face the incumbent in the May 8 runoff. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> is the favorite in the battle for second place and has been increasing his lead over <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>. The polls show <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> defeating either <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> or Barre by as much as 55 percent. The conservatives are pinning their hopes on the large number of people who are undecided. In contrast to the 1981 presidential election, which featured a clear ideological choice between Socialism and free-market liberalism, the traditional cleavage has disappeared. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, who founded the modern <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and led it for a decade, did not once mention the words Socialist or Socialism in his 25-page `` letter to the French'' this week, setting out his platform. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, the standard-bearer of the Gaullist tradition, also has `` rounded off his corners.'' In a TV interview Thursday night, he said he wanted to enlarge the composition of his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> beyond his own political camp and admitted agreement with <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> on some subjects, such as defense and foreign policy. The platforms of the three major candidates all focus on the same themes, differences being largely a matter of nuance. All three say they are for the development of a unified <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> must be prepared for 1992 when the last trade barriers come down in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. All stress reforms in education as a key to reducing <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s 10.4 percent unemployment. And all recognize the need to spur technological research to improve economic competitivity. Both Socialists and conservatives admit there is no quick solution to unemployment, the overriding issue of 1981. The programs of all three focus more on general orientations and less on specific measures. The differences between <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> are even narrower, a difficult subject for the uninitiated. The presidential campaign effectively began in March 1986, when <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s conservatives ousted the Socialists from control of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. That created what the French call `` cohabitation'' between a leftist president and a rightist government _ a unique situation in the history of the Fifth Republic. The official campaign that began Friday means the final list of nine candidates has been published. It also means that from now until the elections, radio and television time is strictly rationed, with each candidate receiving the same amount of time. Also, law prohibits the publication of any opinion polls in the week immediately preceding the election. Lacking clear-cut ideological differences and innovative ideas, the race has evolved into a beauty contest among the major candidates. On one side is <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, once the most unpopular president of the Fifth Republic with poll ratings now soaring to be seen as the sage, lovable `` uncle.'' On the other is <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, the hard-driving bulldozer, workaholic, avid campaigner and flesh-presser in his second tour as premier. He contrasts with <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, the heavyset economics professor of intellectual brilliance but distant, somewhat cold personality. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> of having a vague program and said he was asking the French to elect him now and see what he does later. `` One does n't win a battle by idly dreaming at the fireside, one does n't engage the future in warming his slippers,'' <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> says <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s program has three characteristics, `` obvious immobilism, masked Socialism and constant imprecision,'' and his goal `` is to remain in place, and from that moment everything will be fine in the best of Frances.'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> says the right lacks heart and accuses it of unconcern for social justice. Rounding out the field of candidates are <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, 59, leader of the extreme right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lajoinie </PERSON>, 58, the official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate; <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Juquin </PERSON>, 58, head of a splinter <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> group; <PERSON> Antoine </PERSON> <PERSON> Waechter </PERSON>, 39, ecologist; <ORGANIZATION> Arlette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laguiller </ORGANIZATION>, 48, a Trotskyist; and <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Boussel </PERSON>, 67, another extreme left Trotskyist.
