<BYLINE>Khomeini Leads Iranians To Polls Despite Missiles
^By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranians chanting `` War, war until victory!'' defied threats of Iraqi missile attacks Friday and voted for a new parliament after being urged to go to the polls by <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s state-run television showed <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, 87 and reported in poor health, voting in the morning chill at an open-air polling station near his home in the northern <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Jamaran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> was one of the first to cast ballots when the country's 30,000 polling stations opened for 12 hours Later, the government extended polling hours until 10 p.m. because many people were still voting. Prime Minister <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON>, surrounded by Iranians chanting `` We're not tired of the war!'' voted early. The official media said the turnout among <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s 20-25 million voters was `` massive,'' but it gave no figures. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> had called on his followers to turn out in force to defy the Iraqis. The results may take up to 10 days to be announced. Polling stations in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> were crowded, although as many as half the capital's 6 million people have fled the city to escape Iraqi missile attacks. <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> reported that one missile crashed into the capital before dawn and that the cities of <LOCATION> Isfahan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qom </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tabriz </LOCATION> were also hit. No details were given. Iranian leaders had feared the Iraqis would launch a massive bombardment to disupt the election. <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> told <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> that the turnout was `` wonderful, a sign of the people's fierce resistance.'' It was the third parliamentary election since <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s 1979 Islamic revolution toppled the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>. The last was in 1984. The new parliament will be vital in determining the future of the revolution and in choosing a new leader when <PERSON> Khomeni </PERSON> dies. At stake were all 270 seats in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Majlis </ORGANIZATION>, or parliament. There were more than 1,400 candidates, including women for the first time. Parliament members are elected to four-year terms. One voter said he came to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> from <PERSON> Amol </PERSON>, about 120 miles to the north, to show that he was `` not scared.'' `` I decided to vote here after they said <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> would be the target for many missiles,'' he said. He declined to give his name. Anyone over 16 years old was entitled to vote, provided they produced photo identity cards. Analysts predicted the new parliament would be dominated by radicals who would give the government a broader mandate for reforms that have been blocked by the conservatives. The radicals favor a planned, socialist-style economy with price controls and stringent enforcement of tax laws. Conservative-leaning clerics made up only 20 percent of the candidates. People filled out their ballots openly. Voters did not seem to care if others saw whom they voted for. One man had his form filled out by a neighbor. The 7 -LCB- - year-old Iran-Iraq war, the country's most pressing problem, has not figured in the campaigning <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s undisputed patriarch, has decreed that the war will not end until his adversary, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, has been toppled The campaign dealt mainly with economic issues. In his pre-election message, <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> underscored his recent tilt to the left by urging voters not to back candidates `` who advocated a brand of Islam supported by the capitalists'' but those pledged to `` help the downtrodden.'' House Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s closest aides and considered a pragmatist on most issues, was expected to be reelected along with most of the leading figures in the hierachy. But the hardliners, such <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON>, were expected to make some gains, a development that could have far-reaching effects on the shape of the revolution in the post-Khomeini era.
