<TEXT>
 The battle to save Big <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> has failed, but the memory of the 150-year-old pecan tree is going to be preserved in furniture and mementos and by a party. The tree, said to be the fifth - or sixth-largest of its kind in the world, is n't likely to survive a move from the path of a highway expansion, so it's going to be cut down <PERSON> Dewayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, who has been working to save the tree, says he will begin negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to have the tree removed in late fall. Big <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> stands three miles south of <LOCATION> Corinth </LOCATION> on a farm <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> inherited from his grandfather. The decision to cut down the tree was made this week after forestry and horticulture experts from <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> completed tests that indicate the tree could not survive being uprooted and moved. So the tree will be used to make a piece of furniture for the governor's mansion and to make small wooden crosses that will be given to the 100 children who have become members of the Big <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunch </PERSON>, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. The horticulture experts also will try to make grafts of the pecan tree, which <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> plans to plant near where Big <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> now stands. And <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> is planning a party _ with hot dogs and lemonade _ in late November. `` We have much to celebrate,'' he said. `` It was a unified effort that brought the Big Ike Bunch together.''
