<HEAD>97-Year-Old Alien Is First Amnesty Applicant To Obtain Citizenship</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BRO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 98-year-old woman who moved to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1927 on Friday became the first person to gain citizenship under the amnesty program allowing aliens to legalize their status. `` It seems like it is not true,'' <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> <PERSON> Escobedo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said in Spanish after the ceremony. `` It is so big, it seems like a fairy tale.'' The widow and great-grandmother sat in a chair, raised her hand and took the oath of allegiance to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in Spanish from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Filemon </PERSON> <PERSON> Vela </PERSON>. `` What you're doing today, <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarita </PERSON>, very much is a heroic event,'' said <PERSON> Vela </PERSON>. A case of overnight nerves sapped some of her strength, Mrs. <PERSON> Escobedo </PERSON> said. But after it was over she felt strong enough to wave a flag provided by the local chapter of the Daughters of the American Revolution. A cake inscribed `` Congratulations Citizen Clara'' and a special luncheon held by the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> awaited her at the <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> about a quarter-mile from the Mexican border. <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> district director <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sewell </PERSON> said the reception was his agency's way of thanking Mrs. <PERSON> Escobedo </PERSON> for being a public relations agent for the one-year amnesty program ending May 4. Mrs. <PERSON> Escobedo </PERSON> appeared on parade floats and television commercials and helped motivate other aliens to apply under the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986 offering legal residency and ultimately citizenship to those able to prove they have lived here illegally since before 1982. `` She is the first person in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> who applied for amnesty to become a citizen,'' <PERSON> Sewell </PERSON> said. She is not the oldest person to apply for amnesty under the program; that distinction apparently goes to <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero-Gaitan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, a 101-year-old Mexican who was smuggled into the country in the back seat of his son's car 14 years ago. Joining Mrs. <PERSON> Escobedo </PERSON> in becoming citizens Friday were a 74-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Consuelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarate </PERSON>, and two granddaughters, 47-year-old <PERSON> Rakel </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarate </PERSON> and 44-year-old <PERSON> Genoveva </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarate </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>. `` It has given me new dimensions of my love for this country,'' said <PERSON> Rakel </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarate </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Escobedo </PERSON>, who said her husband was killed by <PERSON> Pancho </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON>'s men during the Mexican revolution, lived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> legally from 1927 until 1962 But in a bureaucratic mix-up, immigration officials took away her `` green'' card _ which is now blue and shows legal residency status _ because they thought she had been living in <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, in violation of the card's terms. She has lived as an undocumented alien with relatives in <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> since 1979. Officials gave her a new green card in February and were able to waive the normal five-year wait for citizenship because she satisfied that requirement 56 years ago, in 1932, said <PERSON> Sewell </PERSON>. Otherwise she would have had to wait until 1994, when she would have been 104. Mrs. <PERSON> Escobedo </PERSON> said she had always planned to become a citizen during her first 35 years in this country, but kept putting it off. She never learned to speak English, but the requirement does not apply to applicants over age 50 with more than 20 years of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> residency. She learned how to say at least one English word on Friday. `` Citifen? Citipen?'' Mrs. <PERSON> Escobedo </PERSON> said haltingly under her daughter's coaching. `` I am <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizen,'' she finally said, with a broad smile.
