<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Negotiations on an <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> settlement were completed Friday, allowing the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to pull out of a war with Moslem guerrillas to which it had committed a force of 115,000 soldiers. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said he expects the five-point peace plan to be signed by next Thursday. The signing will end nearly six years of indirect talks in which he was the go-between for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and its eastern neighbor, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, <PERSON> Therese </PERSON> <PERSON> Gastaut </PERSON>, said the date of the signing ceremony will be announced Monday. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> confirmed that Soviet troops will begin leaving on May 15, but added the withdrawal is not `` a present to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>.'' The two begin their fourth summit May 29 in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Although <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> has a mandate from all sides to promote dialogue within Communist-ruled <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, there is no guarantee the 10-year-old war will stop. The U.S.-supported insurgent alliance was not included in the negotiations and issued a statement Friday saying its fighters `` will not be bound by the outcome of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreements and they will continue the war as long as the Russians and their puppets are present in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' In a statement approved by all sides, <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> stressed that `` any questions relating to the government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'' are an internal matter. `` We have discussed, we have negotiated. That's over,'' he told reporters. `` The documents are now finalized and open for signature.'' He called the settlement a `` historic opportunity'' for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Agreement became possible after what diplomatic sources said was a secret understanding that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> will phase out aid to the guerrillas while Moscuw cuts off military support to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said all parties are ready to sign, including the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as guarantors, after a final round of negotiations that lasted more than five weeks. The agreement covers Afghan and Pakistani assurances of non-interference in each other's affairs, safe and voluntary return of Afghan refugees, and superpower guarantees. A fourth part ties the others together and <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said a memorandum of understanding was added on the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> role in supervising the agreement. Texts are to be published later. Moslem insurgents began fighting after a Communist coup in April 1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in December 1979. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> represented the guerrillas in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and delivers supplies to them, including highly effective <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Stinger anti-aircraft missiles. About 3.5 million Afghan refugees live in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, most in border cities and camps that serve as bases and supply points for the insurgents. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had said it would not sign the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> accord until the Soviets agreed to `` symmetry'' _ a simultaneous end to military aid on both sides. Diplomatic sources called the informal agreement on ending outside aid a face-saving solution for both sides. <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said it was not part of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> settlement. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> said the deal was made through behind-the-scenes diplomacy. In a clear allusion to the question of outside military aid, <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said he was convinced all parties `` will exercise restraint in taking any actions'' that might violate the letter and spirit of the accord. `` The agreement is designed to bring peace to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the conditions for such a peace would not be obtained if actions are taken which would fuel hostilities,'' he said. Intense Soviet diplomatic activity this week preceded the agreement. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> met <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, the Afghan leader, in the Soviet Central Asian city of <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION> earlier this week and they issued a joint statement Thursday saying all issues had been resolved. <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON>, deputy Soviet foreign minister, flew to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to meet the Afghan foreign minister, <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON>, apparently because <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> had been holding out over a border dispute with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The dispute, dating to 1893, had provoked arguments over the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> settlement's reference to boundaries. A source close to the talks said it was resolved on Friday. Early last month, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> agreed on completion of the Soviet troop pullout in nine months, with half leaving in the first three months. The timetable had been a major sticking point.
