<HEAD>South Korea's ``Peace Dam'' Nears Completion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>Hwachun, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first phase of a huge dam designed to prevent <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> from flooding out the Olympic Games in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> neared completion Friday on the line separating <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>. The first phase of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> `` peace dam'' is scheduled to be finished next month. The Olympic Games open in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> on Sept. 17. The rockfill dam sits in a valley close to the Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas. It will cut off the flow of the <LOCATION> Han </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which originates in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and runs past <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> before flowing into the Yellow Sea. Construction began in late 1986, shortly after <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> began building a hydroelectric dam on an upper stream of the river. Despite <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s repeated claim that its dam was designed only to generate power, <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> officials suspect that it also is intended to unleash a `` water offensive'' against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. If the North Korean dam collapsed, about 26 billion tons of water could submerge most of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and surrounding areas with a `` nuclear force,'' South Korean officials say. `` We have done something which was considered difficult to be done in time,'' <PERSON> Chung </PERSON> <PERSON> In-ho </PERSON> of the government's Industrial Site and <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> told reporters visiting the dam site near <LOCATION> Hwachun </LOCATION>, a border town 55 miles northeast of the capital. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kore