<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Congress     04-08 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Congress,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Operation Alliance Not Stopping War On Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Turf wars, mismanagement and lack of leadership plague a government task force created to stop the flow of drugs across the U.S.-Mexico border, a congressman who investigated the operation said Friday. `` Once again, a lack of leadership is undermining the war on drugs,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Government Operations justice subcommittee, which spent a year scrutinizing <ORGANIZATION> Operation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> and issued a critical report this week `` No one is in charge, no one is responsible.'' Operation Alliance, set up in August 1986 to coordinate drug-fighting efforts in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> by a variety of federal agencies, is headed by <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary for enforcement. Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s chose <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> this week to fill the No. 3 spot in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, that of associate attorney general. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it had no comment Friday on the report and a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which has several agencies involved in the alliance, referred questions to <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>. English, D-Okla., said he does n't fault <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> for <ORGANIZATION> Operation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to quell drug smuggling but blames the administration for not giving someone the authority to marshal staff and resources from the various agencies `` Operation Alliance is a good idea that is n't working because of turf battles and a lack of strong leadership from the top. The agencies, including the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION>, have been mired in the same interagency feuding which has frustrated nearly all of our federal anti-drug abuse programs,'' English said. `` In good conscience, I ca n't say Operation Alliance has made much of a contribution,'' English said from <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. English blamed part of the problem on <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s `` refusal to participate'' and also on Customs for not lending its air wing in the fight on drugs along the 2,000-mile border. `` Operation Alliance is limited to ground action, but 60 percent of cocaine comes in by air,'' English said. The report said that although administration officials had promised to put an additional 300 Border Patrol agents along the U.S.-Mexican border, where one-third of marijuana, cocaine and heroin are believed to be smuggled into the country, there has been a net loss of agents. Participating agencies failed to coordinate efforts and did not use the <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, or EPIC, where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> narcotics information is stored and disseminated, the report said. The subcommittee compared the number and size of seizures in the year before Operation Alliance with the first year after it went to work, and found the size of the seizures had increased dramatically. But it said it was concerned the number of seizures has `` not increased as dramatically as the administration has implied.'' According to the report, EPIC figures indicate there were 246 cocaine seizures along the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> border totaling 2,256 kilograms between July 1985 and June 1986. But during the following year, there were 120 cocaine seizures totaling 7,685 kilograms.
</TEXT>
