<HEAD>Accord Removes a Thorn, But Won't Speed Up a Treaty, Baker Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet decision to withdraw from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> will remove one contentious issue from next month's <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit agenda but probably wo n't speed negotiations on a superpower arms accord, the White House chief of staff said Friday `` I think it will have a salutary effect on attitudes, but I do not think it is likely to have a major impact on the other issues on the agenda,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told reporters covering President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who was vacationing in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> awaited notification that the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> had accepted an American proposal under which each side would continue aiding its allies in the Afghan war as the estimated 120,000 <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The Kremlin had rejected an earlier <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal that both sides stop arming the warring parties during the nine months over which the Soviets agreed to withdraw their troops, plus three months thereafter, said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> mediator, <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, told reporters in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> that an agreement could be signed by the end of the week, and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> could start leaving May 15. `` We have discussed, we have negotiated. That's over,'' mediator <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said. `` I want to inform you that the documents are now finalized and open for signature.'' Even though the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> accord is likely to improve the atmosphere, at the May 29-June 2 summit, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and other administration officials say they do not expect to reach agreement before the summit on the proposed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty. The treaty would cut <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet long-range nuclear arsenals by 30 to 50 percent. Soviet officials say publicly that a START treaty could be signed at the summit, but privately acknowledge it is unlikely they can reach agreement. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> denied published reports, attributed to anonymous <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> officials, that the superpowers had agreed to stop aiding the warring Afghan parties. And he stressed that the administration was withholding formal endorsement of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agreement until reading the final terms. `` We have made it known that we will continue to aid the mujahadeen if the Soviets continue their aid to the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government,'' he said. `` The mujahadeen are not being abandoned. They're not being put at a disadvantage. They will be supplied as long as there is a need for that and as the Soviets continue to supply the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government.'' `` After we've had a chance to examine the text of the agreement and heard formally from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, we will decide if all of the conditions have been met for us to continue and to participate as a guarantor of this agreement,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. Neither the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> nor the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> nor the Afghan guerrillas are direct parties to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> talks, which involve the government of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the Kremlin-backed regime in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say agreement on aiding the Afghan parties hinges on a clause in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> accord guaranteeing that foreign powers will not intervene or interfere in <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> affairs. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which has been channeling an estimated $ 600 million a year in covert <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to the guerrillas, has agreed to continue that program as long as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> aids <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, said administration officials who spoke on condition they not be further identified.
