<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Trade Missile Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Iran-Elections, Bjt
^By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> fired four long-range missiles into <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and other Iranian cities Friday before Iranians began voting in parliamentary elections. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said it fired rockets into <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> and other cities in retaliation. Each side said the other's missiles hit residential areas, killing civilians. The official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, also reported that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes hit a `` large maritime target,'' which usually means a tanker, off <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s Persian Gulf coast before dawn. There was no immediate independent confirmation. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, also monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, said Iranian artillery shelled the strategic <LOCATION> Dukan </LOCATION> hyrdoelectric dam in northeast <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, where Revolutionary Guards have captured a large chunk of mountainous <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION> in the last three weeks. It was not known whether the dam, 60 miles north of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kirkuk </LOCATION> oil fields, was damaged The Iranians occupy heights overlooking another important dam and power station on <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Darbandikhan </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Dukan </LOCATION>. Crippling or capturing the two facilities could leave the strategic region around <LOCATION> Kirkuk </LOCATION> without power. Both <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have fired nearly 300 long-range missiles into each other's population centers in the latest chapter of the so-called `` war of the cities.'' Hundreds of civilians have been killed on both sides since the battle broke out Feb. 29. The <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> news agency said that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> missiles were fired Friday into residential neighborhoods in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, the holy city of <LOCATION> Qom </LOCATION>, the central city of <LOCATION> Isfahan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tabriz </LOCATION> in the northwest. It said <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes raided several Iranian cities, but gave no details. The Iraqi missiles smashed into <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> hours before polling stations opened, killing or wounding civilians, the agency said. It gave no figures. However, the attacks appeared to fall far short of the missile blitz Iranian leaders had been expecting during the elections for the 270-seat Majlis, or parliament. The agency said the Iranians retaliated by firing two missiles into <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, two into the northern city of <LOCATION> Mosul </LOCATION>, two in the border town of <LOCATION> Khanaqin </LOCATION> and one into <LOCATION> al-Amarah </LOCATION>, an <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> military area in the south, causing `` considerable damage and casualties.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> confirmed one of the strikes on <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> and said civilians were killed, without citing a number. It reported other fatalities from long-range Iranian artillery fire on Iraqi border cities. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said its warplanes bombed military targets in northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, but the <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the jets hit residential neighborhoods in the northern city of <LOCATION> Amadiya </LOCATION> and in border towns, killing civilians.
