<HEAD>Knights of Malta Convene Secret Conclave To Select New Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> convened a secret conclave in a hilltop villa Friday to elect a new leader of the 900-year-old Roman Catholic charitable order. Thirty-six electors clad in black robes locked themselves in a third-floor room of a palazzo on the <LOCATION> Aventine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> to cast ballots for a new grand master. Two of the candidates are Americans. The previous grand master, <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mojana </PERSON> di Cologna, died Jan. 18 at the age of 82 after 25 years as the knights' leader. The result of the election is not expected to be announced until early next week after ratification by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. A grand master, who is elected for life, carries the title of prince and `` most eminent highness.'' Equal in rank to a cardinal, he is considered the highest ranking layman in the Roman Catholic church. The order's 78th grand master will be chosen from among 22 of the electors who have attained the rank of `` Professed Knights of Justice.'' To be eligible, the new leader must have followed vows of poverty, obedience and chastity and be able to prove 200 years of nobility on the side of both parents. The group _ formally known as the Sovereign Military Order of the <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION>, of <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> and of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> _ was founded during the crusades when it opened a hospice for pilgrims in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> in the early 11th century. It has the status of an independent state and has diplomatic relations with 50 nations. The order has about 10,000 members, led by <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> with 2,800. About 2,500 members live in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The knights operate about 200 hospitals and first aid centers in 90 nations, mostly in poor areas and war zones. The 36 electors, all members of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Complete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, assembled for a morning Mass in the villa's 18th century <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION> del <LOCATION> Priorato </LOCATION> church. In his homily, the prelate of the order, Archbishop <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Brini </PERSON>, said the new grand master should be `` a man of great faith, imbued with charisma of the order which Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II has not hesitated to count among the treasures of the church, a heritage which must be defended and strengthened to make it always more adaptable to the changing needs of the times.'' Following the service, the group walked in a slow procession around the church courtyard and through a passageway flanked by orange trees. The 22 Knights of Justice wore the order's eight-pointed white cross on their sleeves, while the others wore the emblem over their chests The officials then entered the villa and went to the Hall of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Complete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, where they sat at a long table covered by a red cloth. The room, which is reserved for elections of grand masters, is lined with portraits of previous leaders and has a splendid view of the capital. The 22 candidates include de Mojana's interim replacement, <PERSON> Giancarlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Pallavicini </PERSON>, a Hungarian-born American biochemist, and <PERSON> Cyrille </PERSON> <PERSON> Toumanoff </PERSON>, who was born in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and lives in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Their American hometowns were not immediately available. The others are nine Italians, four Austrians, two Englishmen, two Czechoslovaks, and one each from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. The rest of the council is made up of presidents of the order's associations around the world, including <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> financier <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Grace </PERSON>
</TEXT>
