<HEAD>Commerce Secretary Expects No Breakthroughs in Soviet Trade Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUSTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Commerce Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON> said Friday that he expected no breakthroughs in trade talks next week with Soviet officials in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. But <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION>, who is leading a delegation of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials for the tenth session of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said he was hopeful the negotiations could lay the groundwork for expanded trade. The joint commission was formed in 1973 to bring trade agencies of the two governments together. The meetings will take place at the same time a trade delegation of 400 American businessmen will be in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for talks on trade opportunities. <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION>, who will be meeting with Soviet officials including <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would seek expanded opportunities for American companies to sell their products in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Last year, trade between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> totaled $ 1.5 billion, two-thirds of that in grain sales. This represented just 0.5 percent of American export sales and was a decline from $ 4.5 billion in U.S.-Soviet trade in 1979, before President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> imposed the trade embargo after Soviet troops invaded <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` We are not going to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for any breakthroughs,'' <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We do not expect any dramatic increase in trade to result. What we hope to do is to create a new climate and a foundation for future trade.'' <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> said he would stress that expanded trade can only take place if the Soviets make `` further improvements elsewhere in our bilateral relationship, particularly on human rights and immigration.'' Asked whether the Thursday announcement that Soviet troops would begin pulling out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15 would help the trade talks, <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> said he believed that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was `` very happy'' with the development. `` There is n't any question in my mind that if the Soviets would continue to indicate that they would like to lessen tensions, that would certainly have an effect on the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people and the American <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION>, who will leave for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Sunday, won <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> approval earlier this week for a plan to set up high-level working groups with the Soviets to spur exchanges in five areas: food processing, energy, construction equipment, medical products and the services sector, including insurance. <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> said it was hoped that these working groups will provide channels to develop specific markets for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products. The meetings next week are expected to produce some agreements on the establishment of joint ventures between American companies and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The trade meetings will come six weeks before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> travels to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for his fourth summit conference with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.
