<HEAD>Lawyers Form International Body Against Nuclear Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers from 12 nations, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, announced the formation Friday of a group that will work to outlaw nuclear weapons and offer help in disarmament programs. The new organization brought American, European, East bloc and Asian jurists' associations together under one umbrella to coordinate activities against nuclear warfare. Soviet, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Swedish attorneys were elected co-chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> against Nuclear Arms, or <PERSON> ILANA </PERSON>. The group mirrored the International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War, which linked Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> doctors in a campaign that earned them the 1985 Nobel Peace Prize. The jurists, ending a two-day conference, said anyone contributing to the nuclear arms race could be held accountable in the same way that Nazi officers were convicted of crimes against humanity by the Nuremberg war crimes tribunal. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Sucharev </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> and a former justice minister of the Russian republic, said the ultimate goal `` is to outlaw nuclear arms ... possibly through changes in the constitutions of our countries.'' <PERSON> Sucharev </PERSON>, a co-chairman, said the organization also could offer to help monitor the verification of arms control agreements. Speaking through a translator, he said his participation in the founding conference reflected `` new thinking'' in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> co-chairman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said the organization may help defend arrested anti-nuclear activists and could sponsor cases at the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in The Hague. It also could launch multinational research projects into the legal aspects of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space defense program called `` Star Wars'' and the possible interpretations of arms control treaties, he said. The group believes that nuclear weapons violate international laws banning the threat of indiscriminate force and the use of weapons against non-military targets, said <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> attorney who also heads the <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Nuclear Policy. `` It is ironic that the two most powerful countries in the world rely for their security on an illegal institution, namely nuclear weapons,'' said <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>. Asked if he agreed that nuclear weapons in the Soviet arsenal also were illegal, <PERSON> Sucharev </PERSON> said, `` the reality is that nuclear weapons exist,'' and said that they should be outlawed. Co-chairman <PERSON> Stig </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafsson </PERSON>, a member of the Swedish <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, said the association will be financed by donations from its member organizations and by contributions.
