<HEAD>South African President in Namibia For Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WINDHOEK </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> came to <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> with senior members of his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday for talks with leaders of the territorial government, many of whom are demanding abolition of all apartheid-style legislation. Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, a prominent foe of apartheid, and other southern African Anglican bishops also are here for a weeklong visit that includes church services in the densely populated far north of the territory, commonly known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. It is <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s first official visit to <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> since June 1985, when the unelected, multiriacial government was installed to provide limited self-rule over the territory. In the ensuing three years, the so-called `` transitional government'' failed to win international recognition, and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> continued to call for independence elections that would include the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has designated <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> the `` sole and authentic representative of the Namibian people,'' and most observers feel it would win a U.N.-supervised election. During the past three years, four of the six parties in the territorial government have grown increasingly adamant in demanding a total break from apartheid _ <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s system of separate political, social and educational structures for different racial groups. <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Katjiuonga </PERSON>, chairman of the eight-man transitional <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview Thursday he and possibly other members would quit the government if <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> rejected their proposal for a constitution stripped of all references to race and ethnic groups. He said that even if the independence question remained unsettled for years, Namibians could promote reconciliation and unity if they were allowed to implement the proposals for a bill of rights and non-racial elections for regional and local governments. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> must decide whether to bow at least partially to these demands or side with those who want to retain `` group rights'' _ the phrase used in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to justify racially segregated structures. Group rights in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> are backed by the <ORGANIZATION> Rehoboth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basters </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative mixed-race party, and by the all-white <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION>, an offshoot of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s governing <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Namibian politicians say <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> is mindful of how developments here would be viewed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where his government is trying to convince right-wing whites of its steadfast commitment to group rights. About 88 percent of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s 1.3 million people are black, 6 percent white and 6 percent mixed-race. A major source of friction is that whites are by far the wealthiest group and are allowed to administer their own tax system to fund all-white schools and hospitals. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s chief representative in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, Administrator-General <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, said Thursday that the <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> government would be willing to negotiate major changes in the tax disbursement system and would accept for the first time the concept of regional, non-ethnic elections. But he indicated <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> would insist on maintaining special protections for racial minorities. <PERSON> Katjiuonga </PERSON>, of the transitional <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday that <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> would lose some of its appeal if apartheid were eliminated and might be induced to join negotiations on a post-independence government. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has ruled <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> since World War I, defying <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> calls for independence. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> says his government will not consider the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> proposals as long as <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troops remain in neighboring <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> aiding the Marxist government against South African-backed rebels.
