<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb that witnesses said may have been placed in a parked car by a passing motorist exploded Thursday, killing a man and scattering debris over a two-block area, police said. The car was engulfed in flames when firefighters arrived, said Lt. F.D. <PERSON> Tacker </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The victim was trapped inside. The bomb exploded shortly before 2:30 p.m., shooting flames high into the air and scattering parts of the car over about a one-block area. `` It's charred black, the roof is gone and all the doors are blown open on it and there are no tires on it _ they've all burned off,'' said Fire Department spokesman R.C. Knight. The identity of the victim was not immediately known. `` A couple of witnesses said another car pulled up and someone placed some type of bomb device in the car,'' said Homicide Sgt. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kratz </PERSON>. `` At this point, we do n't know what type of bomb it was. Obviously it was a pretty spectacular explosion.'' Witnesses said the victim had parked his car and walked across the street to a barbecue stand, before returning to the vehicle. `` One of the medical officers told one of our people that the guy had gotten out of his car to get a glass of iced tea and when he got back in it exploded,'' said Fire Marshal <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Peacock </PERSON>. Investigators were trying to gather pieces of the bomb, <PERSON> Peacock </PERSON> said. The car was rented on Feb. 25, <PERSON> Kratz </PERSON> said. Investigators know the name of the person who rented the car but have not been able to determine whether he was the victim because at least three people had driven the car, <PERSON> Kratz </PERSON> said.
