 <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> is n't dead, and he obviously is n't famous. But that did n't stop the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> author from putting his unpublished manuscripts up for sale Thursday, entering a market that usually belongs to the prominent or the deceased. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> was not expecting to pull in the $ 605,000 that <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>'s love letters brought at auction _ in fact, bidding on his works began at $ 2.75. Instead, he was hopeful of attracting a publisher for his latest novel, `` Run Red Riding Hood Run.'' So after 10 models in hooded sweatshirts simultaneously read excerpts from his book to about 50 people in the penthouse of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> watched as his literary properties, including two other unpublished novels, were sold for a total of $ 965. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> even auctioned off his collection of 30 rejection notices from publishers for $ 65. Also on the block were his dog-eared dictionary, which went for $ 40, various photos and letters, and cassette tapes of his dictated notes. `` I'm thrilled,'' <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said after the sale. `` We did good.'' `` I read PR releases before I read comic books,'' said <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, 34, who freely admits the auction was nothing more than a Barnumesque stunt aimed at getting him attention. `` Run Red Riding Hood Run'' has a little bit of everything: `` There's murder, there's suspense, there's black comedy,'' <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said. But, as was the case with his books on the second <PERSON> Claus </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulow </PERSON> trial and on his experiences at the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, there's no publisher. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> says his publicity efforts have cost him about $ 15,000 _ `` and it could get worse.''
