<HEAD>Presidents Promise `No Nuclear Race,' Move Toward Joint Economics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Presidents <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> signed accords on Thursday aimed at further propelling their nations, the largest in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, toward becoming a joint economic force. They said their venture also ends speculation of a Latin `` nuclear race.'' <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> on a three-day visit, and <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> signed three agreements eliminating tariffs on cars, automotive parts and more than 130 food products. The two neighbors began work in 1985 on a wide-ranging plan to unify their economies and create a South American Common Market. Their project has been slowed by their struggling economies and huge foreign debts, but progress has been evident. With the signing of nearly 25 agreements in all, trade between <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> jumped from $ 900 million in 1985 to $ 1.5 billion in 1987. In addition, hundreds of students and professionals from both countries now exchange information and work together at long-term joint projects in aviation, transportation, scientific technology and agriculture. For years, Spanish-speaking <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, with a population exceeding 31 million, and Portuguese-speaking <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, with more than 143 million people, were archrivals. They put aside differences to become stronger economically. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> in 1985 became <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s first civilian leader after 21 years of military rule. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> became president of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> in December 1983, the nation's first elected civilian leader following nearly eight years of military juntas. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> said Thursday, `` We are taking new steps in the fruitful and promising path of integration. We are widening our capability to compete in the world. We have never had such an excellent relationship.'' <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> arrived in the capital city of <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION> on Wednesday. It is the seventh time in three years the two presidents have met. During this trip, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> was also officially incorporated in the economic integration after a quick trip by President <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON>. He met with the other two presidents Wednesday. <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> has taken part in most of the talks between <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and it was expected to join the economic group, especially since the three countries share a border. The nuclear issue has been a touchy subject in the integration effort. Both <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> in the past two years were reported to have developed the technology to enrich uranium, a key step in building a bomb. But both countries say their nuclear programs are for peaceful ends. On Friday, <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> will take <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s nuclear experiment center of <LOCATION> Aramar </LOCATION>, outside of <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION> in the southeast. Last year, <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s nuclear installations. `` We are ending any suspicions that nuclear development in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> is not linked to peaceful purposes,'' said <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. Added <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, `` A year ago it was hard to imagine that a <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> president would visit a nuclear plant in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>.'' Foreign Ministry officials said details were worked out during this visit for a future nuclear accord.
