<HEAD>Art Island Is Cultural Oasis in West Germany's Industry Belt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLZHEIM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s most talked about new art museums is a pastoral island that boasts Rembrandts, Roman ruins and a resident sculptor who fires cannon salutes to Mother Nature. <LOCATION> Hombroich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> is a quiet cultural oasis in the heart of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s most heavily industrialized area. `` Art and nature come together at Hombroich,'' says <PERSON> Karl-Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, a wealthy businessman who owns the <LOCATION> Erft </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> island </LOCATION>, about nine miles west of <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION>. `` Hombroich is timeless. It does n't really have a purpose because it is not static. Nature constantly changes, as will the collection,'' says <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, a 51-year-old university dropout and admirer of Eastern philosophy. Hombroich is the home of <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>'s private collection of Rembrandt etchings, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON> watercolors, sculptures by <PERSON> Constantin </PERSON> <PERSON> Brancusi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Giacometti </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lovis </PERSON> <PERSON> Corinth </PERSON> portraits, African masks, ancient Cambodian idols and prehistoric pottery. The island has also been the site of open-air concerts by such world-famous classical musicians as violinist <PERSON> Pinchas </PERSON> <PERSON> Zukerman </PERSON> and pianist <PERSON> Svyatoslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Richter </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>'s property is also an archaelogical treasure. Experts say the ruins of two Roman villas lie beneath the soil, and there is also evidence of one of the earliest Stone Age settlements in nNorthern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The exhibition buildings are reached by labyrinthine paths that lead visitors past shrubs and trees transplanted from such far-away places as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hombroich </PERSON>'s resident waterfowl float near a foot bridge spanning the river. Ruminating on the links between art and nature is a favored preoccupation of <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, and has led him to adopt some unconventional art principles. He rejects the conventional practice of installing climate-control systems as a means of preserving his valuable collection. `` The pictures must have a chance to have their own lives, just like us humans,'' <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` What would be better for a human being _ to live in an air-conditioned room for 1,000 years, or to live normally? Besides, paintings can live hundreds of years without climate control.'' <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> also shuns the normal museum practice of hanging plaques near artworks to identify their creator and titles. He says signs would be a distraction. Like <PERSON> Hombroich </PERSON>'s lush vegetation, works of art also sprout, grow and bloom on <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>'s 42 acres of <LOCATION> Erft </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> property. Sculptor <PERSON> Anatol </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzfeld </PERSON> works nearly every day inside a shed on the banks of the Erft, producing wooden and metal objects that are scattered about the island and blend with the landscape. He periodically fires grass and flower seeds from his hand-built, scrap-metal cannon in what he calls a symbolic salute to nature. Since the island first opened in May 1987, tens of thousands of people have visited, including artists, musicians and intellectuals who <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> says are enchanted as much by the serene setting as by the art collection. Visitors pay about $ 9 to visit the island, but <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> says profit is not his primary motive. A speculator in industrial real estate, he purchased the <LOCATION> Erft </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> property in 1982 as a home for his expanding art collection. He chose <LOCATION> Hombroich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> after a long search. `` You look for years for the right property to do something special, and suddenly you find it. It was the law of chance,'' says <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, who refuses to say how much the property cost. <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> hired noted German sculptor <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Heerich </PERSON> to design <PERSON> Hombroich </PERSON>'s cubist art pavilions. <PERSON> Gotthard </PERSON> <PERSON> Graubner </PERSON>, a prominent West German painter whose work is also among the Hombroich collection, advises <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> on his art purchases. Another important partner for <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> is <PERSON> Bernhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Korte </PERSON>, a landscape gardener who helped transform <PERSON> Hombroich </PERSON> from a jungle of wild undergrowth. <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> went into business for himself in 1958, after quitting university because `` formal studying makes me nervous.'' `` I started out with zero money,'' he says. `` It took 10 years until I was able to buy my first art piece. I bought what I liked. You buy and buy and buy, and suddenly you have a lot of paintings.'' <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> says his purchase of <LOCATION> Hombroich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> means that his art collection will be evolving in new directions which he himself ca n't yet imagine. `` At first I had a collection. It grew. Now I have an island, where everything has its own importance _ the collection, nature and the buildings,'' he says. `` You do your work, and it changes with what you feel is right.''
