<HEAD>Staging Plays In the Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN GUSTAVSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Director <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> returned from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with an intelligence report for other Americans who plan to stage plays in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>: Do n't underestimate the audience. `` The audience is much maligned by many of the theater artists because they feel the audience is uncritical, is too pleased by too many things,'' said <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON>, artistic director of the <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` They're pleased by bad theater, by mediocre theater, by good theater, by brilliant theater. They'll go to all of it,'' he said. Last month, <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> became the first American to direct an American play in the land of glasnost. In staging his production of <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>'s `` Desire Under the Elms'' at the 1,000-seat <LOCATION> Pushkin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Theater </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, he also learned other lessons about the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s actors, theater technicians, designers, directors and playwrights. They may help three other American theater artists planning trips to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> through the <ORGANIZATION> Theatre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Nagel </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of the McCarter Theatre in <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Des </PERSON> <PERSON> McAnuff </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> LaJolla </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Playhouse </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> of Trinity Repretory in <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION> `` I ca n't tell you what it was like to have a 24-hour difference between watching my play in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> the night before I left, and being here for the second preview of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s play,'' said <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON>, who recently opened <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s `` Principia Scriptoriae'' at the <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` The difference was that there, you felt a sort of unified leaning forward and hunger for this,'' <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> said. `` Here, you look around the comfortable theater setting. ... People are listening, yes, but there are some empty seats at the preview, legs are crossed, arms are folded, people are waiting to be grabbed.'' But why, <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> wondered, should n't American audiences wait to be grabbed in what he referred to as `` the grabbiest place in the world' _ with thousands of stimulants `` from the 32-cable channels, to the video thing they can rent, to just life in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Those stimulants are hard to find in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> where audiences come `` eager to hear what's going on in the world, eager to be moved or eager to be preached to _ frankly, politically.'' The one play he saw in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> that was n't overtly political was his production of `` Desire Under the Elms,'' <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> said. `` Everything on their stage is political now in a very open and very critical way, but it still seems like it's 20 years old.'' <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> described himself as a `` collaborative director'' who wants to hear the views of actors, designers, lighting directors and sound engineers. `` I rely on the people I work with,'' he said. <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> had good working relations with Soviet designers, costumers and other behind the scenes people. `` They, I thought, were real artists,'' he said. However, it was impossible to have the same collaborative effort with Soviet actors, he said, because they have not yet developed a sense of mutual trust. <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Pushkin </LOCATION> company needs massive restructuring and its artistic director, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeremin </PERSON>, is working toward that goal. `` However, the socialist idea of tenure for the artists has crippled the Soviet theater for the most part,'' he said. `` It is carrying a lot of baggage ... they would like to lose.'' <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> said he was asked by many in Soviet theater how the American theater is structured: `` How we structure work, how we treat the actors, how we pay the playwrights, how we pay directors. `` They are intrigued by the idea that Americans can pull together an ensemble company in five weeks of rehearsal, and not two years of rehearsal for a company of 15 while the other 75 members of the company are stil getting a weekly salary while you're rehearsing and they're sitting home,'' he said. `` I think my way of working was as much a mystery to them as their way of working was as interesting to me.''
