<HEAD>`Hiding of Anne Frank' Based on Different Side of Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Miep </PERSON> <PERSON> Gies </PERSON>, the woman who helped hide the <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> family from the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>, says it was a long time before she could bring herself to read `` The Diary of <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>,'' even though it was she who saved it. `` Mr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> always said to me, ` Miep, read it, read it,' and I said, ` No, I ca n't,' because I was in fear of what I'd read,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> in halting English. `` But after the second edition, I finally read it, but only when I'm alone. `` Then there grow up something. It was -LRB- as -RRB- if <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> come into me. I heard her cry. She was with me. She was here, in here,'' she said, touching her heart, her eyes welling up with tears. `` For I'm so very, very happy. Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> is the author of her own book, `` <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Remembered </PERSON>,'' written with <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gold </PERSON>. It is the basis of the TV movie `` The Attic: The Hiding of <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>,'' airing next Sunday on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>. In a tender scene in the movie, young <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> suggests to <PERSON> Miep </PERSON> that marriage will keep her from being deported to her native <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> from German-occupied <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>. `` All we need do is find a handsome, intelligent, charming gentleman of Dutch birth, sound of mind and body, financially solvent with a fairly promising future in his chosen profession, offering you comfort and security in your twilight years,'' says <PERSON> Jan </PERSON>, played by <PERSON> Huub </PERSON> <PERSON> Stapel </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON>, 79, was joined by her 82-year-old husband at a recent news conference. They agreed that the scene, as well as the rest of the movie, was quite accurate. They were joined by <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Steenburgen </PERSON>, who portrays Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON>. The movie also stars <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Scofield </PERSON> in a rare television appearance playing <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON>, an employee of <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, helped hide his family and four other people in the attic above their offices for more than two years, until the group was discovered by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> died in a concentration camp, but her father survived and later published the diary <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> kept while in hiding. It became one of the most powerful anti-war statements ever written. It was Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> who preserved <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>'s diary and gave it to <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> after the war. Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> said she never had any desire to write a book, because she felt nothing could be more eloquent than the diary. But she was convinced by Gold that a history should be written of what it was like in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> outside the attic during that time. `` You must understand,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> said, `` it was very painful for us, but after many difficult _ we gave her the information for that reason.'' <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> plays the bright, mischievous <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>, for whom imprisonment in the attic was especially difficult. Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> fondly recalled <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> as a `` very charming child, lively, but very curious.'' `` She always ask us and ask us what happen outside. ... After a while my husband tell me, you must not tell her all the terrible things, because it is terrible enough to be in hiding. But she always ask in a different way until she get the answer she want, and I lost.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>' portrayal _ `` She did it very good.'' <PERSON> Steenburgen </PERSON>, she said, played her `` the way I looked to myself: No panic in a difficult situation. She was right. She was me.'' The movie is from director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Erman </PERSON> and screenwriter <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanley </PERSON>, who teamed on one of the best TV movies of last season, `` When the Time Comes.'' <PERSON> Erman </PERSON> also directed `` Who Will Love My Children?'' and `` An Early Frost.'' <PERSON> Hanley </PERSON>'s credits include the screenplay `` Something About Amelia.'' Rather than focusing on life in the attic, the movie portrays the courage of Dutch citizens who defied the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Gies </PERSON> insisted there was nothing especially heroic about what she did. `` We only did our human duty _ help people who need help. But there were heroes,'' she said, `` the eight people in hiding. `` I can say out of my heart I am so happy that I could give the diary to Mr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, and Mr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> could give the diary to the world. That was good.''
