<FIRST>s i BC-VanishingVenetians Adv17-2Takes   04-08 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Vanishing Venetians, Adv 17-2 Takes,0874</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Venetians Abandon City to Tourists and the Rich</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the world's most enchanting cities was founded 15 centuries ago by frightened citizens who sought refuge among its 118 islets in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> from the southward invasion of <LOCATION> Lombards </LOCATION>. Now their 20th-century descendents are fleeing in the other direction, heading back north to the Italian mainland and abandoning their lagoon city in the northern <LOCATION> Adriatic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> to hordes of tourists and real estate speculators. <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> has become too expensive for its natives and those still left say it is losing its soul. As Venetians flee, the city is trying desperately to save itself from high tides, floods, polluted canals, erosion and decay. After spending hundreds of millions of dollars provided by special national legislation, planners have come up with plans _ after 20 years of striving _ for movable dikes and sophisticated sewers to stop the lagoon's green-black waters from doing further damage. The initiative to do something took root after a disastrous flood in 1966 and the cry of `` Save Venice'' went up. Art lovers from around the world pitched in to rescue palaces, churches and paintings from the annual high tides. But no one came up with a `` save the Venetians'' campaign and most descendents of one of the world's most glorious republics do n't live in palaces on the Grand Canal. They can put up with stench from garbage and refuse in the canals, which also serve as sewers, and the winter floods _ even the summer floods of tourists. It is the lack of affordable housing that's forcing <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s proud, sea-loving natives to the Italian mainland Alarmed by the loss of regular customers, the city's bakers organized a conference this winter to discuss the exodus. A report prepared by a provincial agency informed the bakers that in 1951 <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> had 175,000 people, the most ever in modern times. Last year, the number was down to 83,000 and about one-fifth of those are older than 60. The report predicted by the year 2015 <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> could have only 20,000 permanent residents. `` If we go ahead at this rate, they'll be zero,'' said <PERSON> Giuliano </PERSON> <PERSON> Zanon </PERSON>, a Venetian who wrote the report. Butcher shops, grocery stores, carpenters and plumbers have been closing along the city's narrow, zigzagging streets. Popping up everywhere _ sometimes four, five or six to a street _ are shops selling nothing but <ORGANIZATION> Carnival </ORGANIZATION> masks _ in gold, ceramic, wood, face-sized and pocket-sized _ as souvenirs of the <LOCATION> Mardi </LOCATION> Gras festivities that pack the city with outsiders every winter. The mask shops have become a symbol for Venetians who say the loss of the city's natives is robbing <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> of something just as precious as its classic paintings and its mosaic-studded Byzantine basilica ceilings. `` <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s soul is emptying out. It's becoming a <ORGANIZATION> Disneyland </ORGANIZATION>, a spiritually poor one,'' said <PERSON> Gianluigi </PERSON> <PERSON> Casini </PERSON>, an architect who has helped restore canal-side palaces dating back to the 7th-century beginning of rule by the doges. `` When I was a boy, all the kids would be playing in the piazzas. Now there are few kids,'' said <PERSON> Casini </PERSON>, who at 34 is one of a dwindling number of young Venetians. `` Only old people stay, those who ca n't go away. There are so many empty houses. ... -LRB- Yet -RRB- most of my friends have gone ... for lack of houses.'' He lives with his parents in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croce </LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s six historic districts. Some of <PERSON> Casini </PERSON>'s friends, married or pursuing professions, moved to <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON>, on the other side of the 2.5-mile causeway going out of <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON>, which had about 50,000 people when <PERSON> Casini </PERSON> was born, now serves as a bedroom for a few thousand people who commute to <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> to work as hotel maids, souvenir sellers and waiters. Its population now is about 250,000, triple that of <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s historic center. <PERSON> Casini </PERSON> is thinking about moving. `` I'd like to stay, but it's just not possible.'' <PERSON> Casini </PERSON>, who supplements his architect's earning by teaching art history in a Mestre high school, explained that he ca n't afford <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s rents, which are the lire equivalent of $ 675 to $ 975 a month for a two-room apartment. By law, apartments should rent for far less under the city's rent-control program But as elsewhere in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, landlords prefer to keep apartments vacant hoping for a foreigner or an Italian rich enough to pay illegal high rents. A nighttime ride down the Grand Canal turns up many darkened apartments. Some belong to foreigners or the rich who come from <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, 165 miles away, for vacations or weekends. Many other houses are in no shape to live in. Waters lapping at the front door and sea breezes drifting by the balcony may inspire poetry, but flooding and salty air constantly erode foundations and beams. Restoration, especially of historic buildings, is more costly in <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>, chiefly because supplies must come by barge or by porters who handle small loads on carts in carless <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
