<HEAD>VENICE: carless Venice.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In the last few years, however, some young Venetians have taken advantage of government-subsidized mortgages to buy properties, and the city has bought many buildings to rent out. `` But the city ca n't buy all the houses,'' Mayor <PERSON> Casellati </PERSON> said. Not all Venetians are planning to leave. <PERSON> Gianfranco </PERSON> <PERSON> Tagliapietra </PERSON>, who runs a camera shop, said his teen-age daughter is looking forward to making money in the tourist business when she's old enough. Because of the exodus of Venetians, skilled laborers must be brought in from the mainland. `` To restore a house you have to sell a house'' is a Venetian byword. At the same time, the easy spending of tourists drives up prices for goods in stores. For example, natives complain that a pair of shoes that sell for 50,000 lire -LRB- $ 42 -RRB- in <LOCATION> Mestre </LOCATION> are twice that in <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>. Fruit and vegetables generally cost about 30 percent more in <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> than in the pricier neighborhoods of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. `` It's the middle class that's going away,'' said <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Casellati </PERSON>. `` If someone comes back, it's the rich.'' Disappearing with the exodus is the Venice of old, when everybody knew everybody else, <PERSON> Casellati </PERSON> added. `` In the old days, a doge would live next to a poor person; <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s classes were all mixed together. All this is being lost.'' Even some of <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s gondoliers live in <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON>. <PERSON> Zanon </PERSON>, who wrote the report on the declining population, said exodus that is siphoning off people has an ironic twist: it began because the city was too crowded. `` If the city had a plan, they could have done something,'' he said. `` But they did n't do anything.'' After the 1966 flood, tourism took off, perhaps inspired by the worry that <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> some day might be swamped for good by the tides. By the 1970s, real estate speculators started to move in, betting that the tourism boom would last. It became fashionable for big name companies, like <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION>, to restore palaces for headquarters, banquets or exhibitions. `` We Venetians are at our limits to transmit culture; we are outnumbered by tourists,'' <PERSON> Zanon </PERSON> said. `` My daughter does n't even speak Venetian,'' a dialect more lilting than a gondolier's song. `` The sadness about <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>,'' he added, `` is not the pollution'' _ or decay. `` It's the politicians who do n't do anything.'' The mayor said he'd like to see a law that would force real-estate buyers to live in what they bought or rent their properties for several years only to Venetians. But he acknowledges that might be impossible in a free-market society. In the last few years, however, some young Venetians have taken advantage of government-subsidized mortgages to buy properties, and the city has bought many buildings to rent out. `` But the city ca n't buy all the houses,'' Mayor <PERSON> Casellati </PERSON> said. Not all Venetians are planning to leave. <PERSON> Gianfranco </PERSON> <PERSON> Tagliapietra </PERSON>, who runs a camera shop, said his teen-age daughter is looking forward to making money in the tourist business when she's old enough.
