<TEXT>
 Many of the nation's major retailers have notched healthy sales gains in March, while the stock market wavered amid a mid-week advance. The early Easter holiday helped the March retail sales reported by major retailers, experts said Thursday. But although sales were strong for many, including F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> with a 29 percent jump over March 1987, there were some exceptions. The nation's largest retailer, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported its sales rose just 1.5 percent during the month. Analysts said the stores with lackluster sales suffered from general consumer caution. `` The shift in the Easter calendar should have helped in many cases to lift sales, but we're still in a very sluggish environment,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Tashjian </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Seidler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amdec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Consumers have spent cautiously since early last year, and analysts predict they will remain tight-fisted for at least the first part of 1988. In the financial markets on Thursday, stock prices managed to move higher in an erratic session and add to Wednesday's strong gain. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had gained 64.16 points Wednesday, edged up 0.50 to 2,062.17. Over the past three days, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> average has gained 81.47 points. New signs of stability in the dollar have boosted stock prices around the world. The <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stock market climbed Thursday to new highs, having recovered all the ground it lost in last year's crash. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bond market