<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise Above $17 a Barrel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices have edged back above the $ 17-a-barrel level in moderate trading, recouping losses recorded earlier in the week. Analysts and traders said the market appeared calm Thursday ahead of an <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> committee meeting scheduled to begin this weekend in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, even though there have been reports of trader nervousness. Contracts for May delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, rose 25 cents per barrel to $ 17.06. Among refined products, wholesale heating oil for May delivery rose 0.39 cent a gallon to 45.73 cents, and wholesale unleaded gasoline for May rose 0.40 cent a gallon to 48.82 cents. Longer-term contracts also rose. `` We had a very steady and constructive market that continued up all day,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, senior energy analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The fundamentals look good _ demand keeps edging up, and <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> is not overproducing,'' he said. Traders and analysts said the session's buyers included refiners who stepped up their purchases as prices inched above the $ 17-a-barrel level. `` They saw that the market was getting too high, too quickly, so they speeded up their purchases,'' noted <PERSON> Madison </PERSON> <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>. In addition, a large money management firm in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> reportedly purchased 3,000 May contracts for crude, a move that was believed to have absorbed much of the selling in the market. The upcoming <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting has not stirred much nervousness among traders. Most believe the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>' pricing committee will not take much constructive action at the April 9 meeting. Some market participants had hoped the 13-nation cartel would act aggressively to stabilize prices and enforce production limits to curb excessive supplies. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the group likely would only `` issue a bland statement.''
