<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 An early Easter helped lure consumers into stores in March, giving many of the nation's largest general retailers a respite from their sluggish sales of the past year. But experts do n't believe shoppers are on a long-term spending spree. Retailers and analysts attributed the strong March sales increases at some stores to a quirk in the calendar: with Easter falling earlier in April than usual, consumers did their spring shopping in March. That made comparisons with March 1987 look better. `` They're not as good as they appear,'' <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, a retailing analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said of the March figures. Among the retailers reporting strong sales was F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which registered a 29 percent increase over March 1987 sales. At the other end of the spectrum, the nation's largest retailer, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, reported its sales rose just 1.5 percent. The lackluster sales resulted from consumers' general caution, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Tashjian </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Seidler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amdec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` The shift in the Easter calendar should have helped in many cases to lift sales, but we're still in a very sluggish environment,'' <PERSON> Tashjian </PERSON> said. Consumers have spent cautiously since early last year, and analysts predict they will remain tight-fisted for at least the first part of 1988. The rate of spending is crucial to a retailer's bottom line, but economists watch it for signals of the nation's economic health. Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the gross national product. Apparel retailers continued to have problems because of consumers' continuing disenchantment with the stores' latest lines, said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sack </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> was among the stores having problems with their fashion lines, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> said The retailer said its sales for the first nine weeks of the fiscal year rose 1.9 percent over the same period a year earlier. K mart <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales rose 8.6 percent last month, and 5.5 percent so far this year. Its comparable store sales _ those from stores open at least a year _ rose 5.5 percent last month, and 2.6 percent for the year to date. Rapidly-expanding <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales rose 36 percent in March and 34 percent so far this year. <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION>'s comparable store sales rose 15 percent last month and 14 percent for the first two months of fiscal 1988 <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> posted a 10.2 percent sales increase last month, and a 5.7 percent year-to-date gain Its comparable store sales were up 9.3 percent last month and 4.9 percent so far this year. <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales were up 28.8 percent last month and 23.4 percent so far this year. Comparable store sales rose 10.5 percent in March and 5.4 percent for the first nine weeks. May <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales rose 12.1 percent in March and 6.5 percent so far this year. May's comparable store sales rose 7.9 percent last month and 2.6 percent year-to-date. <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its March sales were up 10 percent and its year-to-date sales rose 4.3 percent. Comparable store sales rose 7.7 percent in March and 1.9 percent for the first nine weeks. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> said its year-to-date sales were up 20.9 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales fell 0.4 percent in March and 2.4 percent for the nine-week period. Results reported Thursday were for department and apparel stores and general merchandisers. They do not include sales by automakers or supermarkets.
