<HEAD>U.S.-Made Hondas Coming To Japan, Sign Of New Direction In Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After years of thriving on a booming export trade, it might seem odd for <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Ltd. to celebrate the first arrival here of U.S.-built <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> automobiles But for the company and the domestic economy, today's celebration over the shipload of 540 Hondas built in <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, marked more than a simple welcoming party For <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, the shipment signaled maturity for a company that in two decades has transformed itself from a respected motorcycle maker into a worldwide maker of attractive cars. In a broader sense, the imported Hondas reflected ongoing changes in the surprisingly robust Japanese economy, which is being fuled more by domestic demand than because of exports, its longstanding source of growth. The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> has surged back from last October's worldwide crash On Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> surpassed its previous high, which was set on Oct. 14. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> exchange indexes are still about 10 percent below pre-crash levels. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s gross national product grew at a vibrant rate estimated at 7 percent to 8 percent in the last quarter of fiscal 1987-88, which ended March 31. Official figures are n't yet published. Most analysts expect it to expand at over 4 percent in the new fiscal year. The Japanese consumer _ the same Japanese whose propensity to save is legendary _ is changing. The car that <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> is importing is the Accord coupe, a type of car that has n't been much favored by Japanese buyers, who traditionally have gone for four-door family sedans. But in recent years, as the strong yen has greatly increased the wealth of some Japanese, sportier cars have been selling better, and the <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> Accord coupe is aimed at that increasing market. Still, why not make it in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>? <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bret </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> explained: `` This particular car, the coupe, is completely designed and set up by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, with <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; D -LRB- research and development -RRB- and engineering. So we do n't have facilities in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to build it. It was built for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. We see the car as an American car.'' The company saw the growing demand in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and `` thought that it probably would sell,'' he said. The company predicts sales in 1988 of the American-made coupe at 4,000, and hopes sales will grow to 50,000 in 1991. The Japanese domestic car market is the second biggest in the world after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has an export quota of 2.3 million cars a year. Oddly, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> sells more cars in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, about 740,000 last year, than in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, about 365,000. Importing the Accord coupe is part of the company's drive to increase its domestic market share. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> price for the Accord coupe is about $ 15,000; its price in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has n't been announced. The Japanese economy has spurted ahead on a combination of the high yen and some pump-priming undertaken by the Japanese government last spring when it looked as if 1987 might be a recession year. On Thursday, the Japanese parliament enacted another mildly expansionary budget of 56.7 trillion yen -LRB- $ 453.6 billion -RRB-, up 4.8 percent from the earlier year. The new budget includes a big increase in public works spending, up 19.7 percent at 7.3 trillion yen -LRB- $ 58.4 billion -RRB-, to keep domestic demand high. A strong factor fueling growth last year was private-sector housing investment, which leaped 21.7 percent, according to <ORGANIZATION> Fuji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> economists. They predicted in early April that the economy would expand at a 4.1 percent rate in fiscal 1988-89, inflation would be only 0.9 percent, and the dollar would average 122 yen, close to its recent level of 123-125 yen. A projection by the respected <ORGANIZATION> Okasan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> predicted 4.5 percent growth. The Okasan and <PERSON> Fuji </PERSON> projections agreed that private housing would stall after its hot performance in the previous year, but that personal spending and corporate capital investment would continue to fuel growth. The Okasan think tank said domestic demand would push the economy up 5.6 percent while external demand _ exports _ would shrink and reduce the economy's growth by 1.1 percent. Okasan expected the trade surplus to drop from $ 93.3 billion in the past fiscal year to $ 87.7 billion, and the dollar to average 124 yen.
</TEXT>
