<HEAD>Lucky Stores Rejects Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has spurned <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s offer for a $ 1.74 billion buyout and says it may undergo a major restructuring or sell the company elsewhere. Lucky said Thursday its directors unanimously had rejected <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>' unsolicited $ 45 a share tender offer as `` inadequate'' and not in the best interests of the company or its stockholders. The board also rebuffed the offer by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, a Salt Lake City-based grocery and drugstore chain, to increase its bid to $ 50 a share in a negotiated acquisition. In addition, Dublin-based Lucky adopted a stock purchase rights defense plan aimed at making a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive. The rejection of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>' surprise tender offer for Lucky's 38.6 million outstanding shares came 17 months after <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> blocked a hostile takeover attempt by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Asher </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>. A combination of the two companies would create the nation's biggest supermarket chain <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> vice president for investor public relations, said his company had no comment on the announcement. Lucky's stock closed at $ 52.50 per share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Thursday, up $ 3.75 from Wednesday's close. In addition to rejecting <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>' bid, Lucky's board also authorized company management and advisers to consider alternatives to an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> buyout to boost its stock price. Alternatives could include a possible reorganization to focus on Lucky's <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> operations, a leveraged recapitalization with possible distributions to stockholders by a dividend or share repurchase, and a negotiated sale of the company to a third party. `` We are confident that pursuit of one of these alternatives will provide our best opportunity to achieve greater value for our stockholders,'' stated <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lillie </PERSON>, Lucky's chairman and chief executive officer. The board also adopted a warrant dividend plan and has declared a dividend under the plan of one common stock purchase right for each share of outstanding common stock, payable to stockholders of record on April 8. The plan would act to dilute Lucky's common stock in the event of a hostile takeover, making such a move prohibitively expensive. The company stated the plan was aimed at preventing unsolicited attempts to acquire a controlling stake in <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> through a tender offer or on the open market `` at prices determined by the board to be inadequate.'' A merger of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, with 1,700 outlets in 40 states, and Lucky would have make Lucky the nation's largest supermarket chain, surpassing No. 1 <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Lucky has 480 outlets, 340 within the state <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> had indicated it would convert its struggling 240 Alpha Beta outlets in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to Lucky stores. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> last year posted $ 14.3 billion in annual sales, while Lucky had $ 6.9 billion in sales.
