<HEAD>Huge Supermarket Chain Reports Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> says it suffered a $ 487.7 million loss last year, largely due to interest expenses from its 1986 leveraged buyout and to income tax law changes. The privately-held supermarket chain, the nation's second-largest after Cincinnati-based <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, had posted a $ 14.3 million loss in 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> also said its revenue fell to $ 18.3 billion last year from $ 20.3 billion the previous year. However, <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION>'s operating profit rose to $ 448.3 million from $ 422.9 million the previous year, <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> said. Last year's loss was blamed on $ 576.4 million in interest expense, largely stemming from the leveraged buyout, and a $ 409.4 million bookkeeping charge resulting from the new tax law, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> believes its interest expenses have peaked and will decline over the next few years, said the company's controller, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Domeier </PERSON>. <PERSON> Domeier </PERSON> said the company trimmed its long-term debt by 32 percent to $ 3.1 billion in 1987 and is one to two years ahead of schedule in paying off its debt. The drop in revenue was attributed to the sale of several divisions, including the 105-store Liquor Barn chain and markets in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and four states, to raise capital and help pay off the debt. During the same period, sales for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stores grew 5 percent, <PERSON> Domeier </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
