<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar traded lower against all major foreign currencies except the Swiss franc and Canadian dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> early today. Gold prices rose. Foreign currency dealers said the market is waiting for a meeting of finance ministers of the seven major industrialized countries in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next week. Most said they expect the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> _ to reaffirm their wish to keep the dollar stable around its current levels. European traders said interest was likely to focus on the British pound again today, following intervention by the West German and British central banks Thursday to stop sterling's rise. `` Sterling is very healthy at the moment but that old fear of central bank intervention should keep the market from pushing it up too fast,'' said one trader with a major Italian commercial bank. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.52 yen to a closing 125.18. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 125.35 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's rates, included: 1.6725 West German marks, down from 1.6810; 1.3825 Swiss francs, up from 1.3817; 5.6740 French francs, down from 5.7022; 1.8855 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8865; 1,241.20 Italian lire, down from 1,246.50; and 1.2475 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2448 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.8775 to buy one British pound today, more expensive for buyers than late Thursday's $ 1.867. Gold prices were higher in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> than late Thursday's $ 447.75 a troy ounce. The gold metal opened at a bid price of $ 449.40 an ounce but at midmorning today the city's five major bullion dealers had fixed a recommended price of $ 448.60. One dealer said that after hitting a low of about $ 445 Thursday, gold has found some support at its current levels. Other bullion dealers said attention will be focused on the dollar, and that a major move in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency could send gold moving. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 448.65, up from $ 448 late Thursday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 3.06 to close at a bid $ 450.72. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.42 a troy ounce, up from Thursday's $ 6.40.
</TEXT>
