<FIRST>r f PM-FarmScene     04-08 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Offers Extensive Data On China Agriculture, Population</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in recent years has been losing its rural people, despite an overall growth in the country's population, according to a new statistical report by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> In 1982, when <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> reported a population of more than 1.01 billion, a record 803.9 million, or 79 percent, lived in rural areas. By 1985 the total population was more than 1.04 billion, but rural residents were down to 662.9 million people, or 63 percent. Population figures and many others are included in a new edition of `` Agricultural Statistics of the People's Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, 1949-86,'' by <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crook </PERSON> and others of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> The new version, which was distributed Thursday, expands greatly an earlier statistical report on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s agriculture issued in 1984, which was the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s first since the communists took charge in 1949. Although not likely to make this spring's best-seller lists, the 158-page report is expected to be in great demand from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> watchers and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural traders interested in that potentially huge Asian market. The first edition in 1984 was 71 pages long. The report relies on `` the important, although still incomplete, agricultural data that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reported during 1949-85, with some updates through 1986,' the authors said. Some 126 national and provincial tables of figures are included, along with an introduction, explanatory notes, references and suggested readings. Various sections include agricultural production; `` inputs'' such as farm machinery, fertilizer and labor; exports and imports; and consumption and procurement. The provincial tables include <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s population by region and province; agricultural areas by crops; hog slaughter; horse and camel year-end inventory; milk production for cows and goats; and consumption by peasants. Officials said the report may be ordered from: Superintendent of Documents, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Printing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> 20402, or telephone -LRB- 202 -RRB- 783-3238.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fierce competition for the world's soybean market has sprung up as demand increases for the high-protein, oil-rich crop that once was dominated almost entirely by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Soybeans have the potential to supplement diets of low-income people in the Third World, where it will be important to gain consumer acceptance for soybeans and soy-fortified foods, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analyst, said Thursday in a new report. `` A historical view shows that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dominance of world soybean trade, founded on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> research and development in the 1940s and 1950s, declined in the 1980s as <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries, spurred by high prices, developed large-scale production and processing facilities,'' he said. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> have been the main <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competitors in the international soybean market. <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON>, an agriculture and trade analyst in the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, added: `` Their success, mainly in temperate areas, has not been duplicated in tropical areas elsewhere in the Third World. The major factors behind the increased demand for soybeans in the Third World, he said, are rising incomes and population growth. As families have more to spend, their demand increases for meat and other food products such as margarine and cooking oil. `` Fierce export competition with the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> for these markets, as well as the developed country market, will likely continue,'' <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON> said. `` The expansion of large-scale soybean production in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will continue as long as soybean prices are high enough for Brazilian farmers to profitably open new lands for soybeans.'' Further encouragement would be in the Brazilian government's willingness to develop the rural transportation system connecting the new lands to ocean ports, he said `` If the price of soybeans is high relative to other crops, farmers in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and elsewhere will find it profitable to switch even more of their existing cropland to soybeans,'' <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreigners continue to own just under 1 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural land, slightly more than the level of a year ago, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday its 1987 year-end review of reports under the Agricultural Foreign Investment Disclosure Act found 12.5 million acres of agricultural land in foreign hands, 202,000 acres more than reported in 1986. Of the land owned by foreign interests, 50 percent was forest land, 17 percent cropland, 28 percent pasture and other agricultural land, and 5 percent used for non-agricultural purposes or unreported. Corporations held 80 percent of the foreign-owned land, with the balance held by individuals, partnerships, institutions and other entities. As in the past, much of the ownership is concentrated in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antilles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. Those countries combined to account for 69 percent of the foreign-held acreage, the agency said. <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> continued to have the heaviest concentration of foreign ownership, with holdings of almost 1.79 million acres, mostly timberland, or more than 14 percent of the total. `` Ninety-three percent of the foreign-owned acreage will remain in agricultural production, according to foreign owners,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
