<HEAD>London Shares Higher On Interest Rate Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices rose Friday when British commercial banks heeded a <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> signal to cut their base lending rate. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index rose 12.6 points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,773.6 at midday. Volume was light at 259.3 million shares at midday compared with 261.9 million shares at the same time Thursday. The commercial banks announced a cut in their base lending rate by half a percentage point to 8 percent, the lowest level in more than a decade. The banks cut the benchmark rate, effective Monday, after the central bank reduced its own money market rate by 0.375 percnet to 8 percent, apparently to stem the British pound's advance. `` That's what we want, some more good news like that,'' said one dealer, referring to the reduced interest rates. `` It should be just the tonic the market needs'' to take it higher. The dealer said the market had been sluggish all morning, held back in part by major new share issues by <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> to help finance a tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and a huge issue announced by <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. Other dealers were more wary of the benefits to equities from the interest rate cuts, saying the lower rates revive fears of inflationary pressures on <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s economy. One dealer also noted that the pound failed to show marked reaction shortly after the rate cut was announced, dampening the positive sentiment in the equity market.
</TEXT>
