<HEAD>Tate and Lyle Launches Tender Offer For Staley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a major British sugar refiner and distributor, announced today a $ 1.33 billion cash tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the second largest refiner of corn sweeteners in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Tate and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON>, which already owns nearly 5 percent of <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s stock, said it was offering $ 32 a share for the rest of its 30.4 million outstanding shares <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> stock closed at $ 30.12 -LCB- a share in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite trading Wednesday. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> has proposed that <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> build on its stake acquired in November and become a more substantial minority shareholder, <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> said it decided to launch the tender offer instead. The acquisition would give <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> its first interest in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn sweetener market. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> said it would become the only supplier of all three types of sugar _ corn, beet and cane _ in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We are confident that, as part of <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> division, the performance and competitive position of <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s corn activities will be significantly enhanced,'' <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lyle </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said. Tate and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> said it began legal action in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to overturn takeover defenses established by <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>, including a benefit package for its senior management. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> said the offer will be partly funded by the sale of new shares to its existing shareholders, cash resources and a bank loan. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> said it intends to sell <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s food distribution business, which <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> acquired in 1984 for $ 396 million, and that it was prepared to consider any offers immediately. The acquisition and stock issue must be approved by <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON>'s shareholders, who are to meet on May 3. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s principal corn product is high fructose corn syrup, known as <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION>. The largest refiner of corn sweeteners in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is <ORGANIZATION> Archer-Daniels-Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, also based in <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>.
