<HEAD>British Banks Cut Key Lending Rate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in 3rd graf that rate is at its lowest level since
1978 sted 1977.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s major commercial banks, heeding a signal from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION>, announced Friday a cut in their base lending rate by half a percentage point to 8 percent, the lowest level in more than a decade. <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> cut the benchmark rate, effective Monday, after the central bank reduced its own money market rate by 0.375 percent to 8 percent, apparently to stem the British pound's advance The base rate cut brought the rate to its lowest level since it stood at 7.5 percent in April, 1978, the banks said. The banks last cut the rate, by half a point, on March 17. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government has been concerned about the strength of the pound against the West German mark since early March. The pound has been buoyed by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s relatively high interest rates, which make pound-denominated investments more attractive, stimulating demand for the currency. A stronger pound could hurt <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s exports and corporate profits. However, there have been concerns that rate cuts would spur inflation, which is running at a modest 3.3 percent. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> repeatedly has said that reining in inflation is her top economic priority. Better commercial borrowers generally obtain loans at 1 percentage point above the base rate.
