<HEAD>Bargainers OK'd To Go For Ford-GM Pattern, Some Kenosha Workers
Admitted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> bargainers have received their marching orders: win for <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> employees the same pay, benefits and job protections enjoyed by their counterparts at the top two automakers. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> council wrapped up a two-day strategy session here Thursday and voted to seek a return to labor parity between the No. 3 automaker and its larger rivals, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Since 1979, the union's <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> contract has expired at different times than the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> pacts because the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> contract was reopened several times for company-saving concessions. But the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> will insist on a two-year contract with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> so all three pacts will expire together in 1990, adding to workers' bargaining power at a time when they will need it most because of the growing number of Japanese-owned factories building cars in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` There might be a wiggle here or there that will be different but the principles will be the same,'' <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. `` We are ready to do battle for justice, economically and socially, with the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> contract expires Sept. 14. Talks normally would begin in mid-July but the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> agreed to start early after <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s attempt to sell its <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> parts subsidiary ignited angry <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> opposition and left behind a bitter residue. The bargaining is set to begin April 18 in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. `` We will take the pattern agreement and as closely as possible fits those provisions -LRB- to -RRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> agreement,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. The Chrysler council represents 59,500 active and 8,000 laid-off workers, members of 49 <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> locals. The council also voted nearly unanimously to accept some former <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> workers into their fold under a compromise that ended days of potentially divisive debate. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> last August and announced last fall it will close a 5,500-worker assembly plant in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, leaving 1,000 workers at a <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> engine plant and a <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> parts distribution center to either bargain with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> on their own or come under the national contract. The soon-to-be-laid-off assembly plant workers will be covered under a separate plant closing agreement and will not join the union's <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> council. Local leaders who did not want to admit the 1,000 <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> workers said they feared the former <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> workers, whose seniority averages 18-20 years, would take jobs that otherwise might go to laid-off <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGAN