<HEAD>Saudi Monarch Calls for Cooperation by All Oil Producers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 King <PERSON> Fahd </PERSON> has called for `` solidarity'' among members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> to bolster the target price of $ 18 a barrel, the official <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` If this is achieved, then there will be immense benefits and the prices of oil will always be on the increase,'' he told college students Thursday night while on inspection tour of the al-Qasseem region some 200 miles north of here. The <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> monarch attributed the instability of oil prices to attempts by `` some'' to sell at discount prices, and expressed hope that adherence will be strict to production and price rulings laid down by the 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>. He affirmed that the kingdom `` has never at any time violated any agreement related to oil,'' thus adding yet another official denial to ongoing reports that <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> was also violating <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> prices and selling at a discount because of the weak market. Fahd did not name any of the member states of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> cartel that he accused of cheating on the rulings laid by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> for more than a year and designed to strengthen oil prices around an 18 dollars for benchmark crude. At <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s request, the five-member <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> pricing committee is meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> on Saturday to consider ways and means of firming up the world market's flagging prices. Fahd's call for `` solidarity'' among <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> member states was apparently aimed at pre-empting outbursts of inter-OPEC criticism to help the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> gathering formulate the proper recommendations. On Thursday, Iranian oil minister <PERSON> Gholamreza </PERSON> <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> accused <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> of trying to destabilize the oil market by not agreeing to have the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting held at an earlier date. He said that <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> blocked a call three months ago by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to have the pricing committee convene. Committee members are oil ministers of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>. Saudi Oil Minister <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> will be in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> after calling on two major non-OPEC oil producers _ <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> _ seeking their cooperation in helping stabilize the market by restraining their output. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> is the leading member of the cartel and alone possesses at least one-fifth of the world's proven oil reserves. Fahd stressed this point in his address saying that the kingdom `` now is one of the major countries with reserves in the ground that can suffice it for 200 years according to the estimates of world experts.''
