<HEAD>Saudi Arabia, Mexico Agree to Work for Oil Price Stability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> have agreed to create a bilateral consultative mechanism to seek price stability on the world petroleum market. The new mechanism was established `` to strive for the stability of the international petroleum market and the improvement of hydrocarbon prices,'' according to a statement released Thursday, following a meeting between <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> oil minister <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parastatal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiriart </PERSON> also attended the talks. <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> observed during the meeting that both oil-producing countries `` probably will remain in the world hydrocarbons market long after other exporting countries leave,'' according to the agency statement. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is not a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> but closely monitors its price and production guidelines. It was the world's fourth largest oil producer in 1985 but since has slipped to sixth place after the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hiriart </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> agreed `` that the stability of the international petroleum market and improvemnt of hydrocarbon prices only can be brought about with the cooperation of all producing countries, members and non-members of <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>,'' the statement said. Energy officials of both governments will meet periodically to evaluate the market situation, the statement added. On Monday, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s state oil monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> announced that it had lowered the price of its light Isthmus crude by $ 1.62 a barrel to Japanese customers in March. <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> revealed in a statement that the price of its light oil was $ 13.86 a barrel in March, down from $ 15.48 a barrel in February. The price for its heavy Maya crude fell from $ 12.83 to $ 11.20, the monopoly. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> buys 180,000 barrels a day of crude, accounting for 11 percent of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s total exports in March.
