<HEAD>GM Calls Wants Scaled Back Fuel Efficiency Standards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which helped persuade the government to reduce its car fuel economy regulations for each of the last three model years, has again called for the repeal or reduction of the rules. The No. 1 automaker said in a statement Thursday the Corporate Average Fuel Economy Standards are `` a disadvantage for full-line manufacturers'' that should be repealed or amended. Without some action, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said it could be `` subject to civil penalties in the hundreds of millions of dollars'' and may be forced to `` close plants or severely restrict product offerings to remain in compliance.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and other automakers were successful in efforts to win reduced CAFE standars in 1986, 1987 and 1988. The government had set a fleetwide goal of 27.5 miles per gallon for 1988 models, but agreed to lower it to 26 mpg. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> anticipates compliance with the reduced level in 1988, but the standard is scheduled to return to 27.5 mpg in 1989 model year. The company has said it might fail to meet CAFE regulations in 1989 if gasoline prices remain stable or continue falling. Stable gas prices have made the less fuel-efficient six - and eight-cylinder cars more attractive to consumers Companies are allowed to borrow credits from past and future years in which they have exceeded or expect to exceed the standard as a way to reduce current non-compliance. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> is asking the government to reduce retroactively the 1985 model year standard to 26 mpg from 27.5 mpg, which would give the company credit to offset any 1989 shortfalls. Other auto companies are doing the same.
