<HEAD>NYSE Boosts Capital Requirements for Specialists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after 3rd graf pvs, The Securities ...
with comment on the requirements. Picks up 4th graf, The exchange
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Specialist firms that control the rights to trade specific issues on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> will have to meet tough new capital requirements under the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s latest post-crash proposal. The capital plan, approved Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> board, is the latest in a series of steps taken to strengthen the market in the wake of Wall Street's October crash. The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> now must consider the plan. <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, who follows the securities industry industry for <ORGANIZATION> Lipper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analytical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said the new proposal appears mainly designed to bolster confidence in the marketplace. He said it may help keep trading orderly, but would not prevent another severe decline. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Torrenzano </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, confirmed that `` the vast majority of the specialists can meet'' the proposed new requirements today. Long said the new requirements could lead to more consolidation among specialists. The exchange currently has 54 specialist firms, which control the rights to market the stocks of the 1,650-plus companies listed on the exchange. Specialists are required to keep order in the market by setting opening prices and covering trades when there are not enough buyers or sellers. The specialist system came under scrutiny in the days following the Oct. 19 crash because of reports that some specialists failed to fulfill their roles during the market turmoil. Some specialist firms merged with bigger firms or had to give up their roles because of shattering financial damage suffered in the crash. Since the crash, five stock specialists have agreed voluntarily to give up their roles as market makers on the exchange. Under the proposed changes, a specialist firm must show it can meet, with its own liquid assets, a minimum capital requirement of $ 1 million or be able to buy 15,000 shares of each common stock in which it makes a market, whichever is greater. The rules currently require minimum capital of $ 100,000 or the ability to buy 5,000 shares in each stock in which the specialist makes a market. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive of the exchange, said one question asked repeatedly since the crash has been, `` Would the condition of the market during the week of Oct. 19 have been better than it was if specialists had more capital?'' `` The simple answer was ` no,' and the <ORGANIZATION> Brady </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> agreed with that conclusion,'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said, referring to the presidential commission that investigated the causes of the crash. But <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said the crash and subsequent volatility of the stock market served to `` underscore the need for strengthening the specialist system'' and he said the proposed changes were `` an appropriate interim step to be taken now to bolster confidence'' in it. He said other measures concerning the adequacy of the specialists' capital requirements are under review. Among other post-crash steps the exchange has announced previously was a curb on computerized program trading, which takes effect when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average moves 50 points in either direction from the previous day's close in one session. That curb was activated for the first time on Wednesday when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION>'s rise surpassed 50 points in the last hour of trading. The Dow finished with a gain of 64.16 points for the day. The exchange has also announced it has begun taking steps to improve its ability to handle heavy trading volumes.
</TEXT>
