<HEAD>March Consumer Prices Growth Slowest Since November 1985</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer prices rose 5.1 percent during March, the lowest monthly figure since November 1985, the central <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> announced. It said late Thursday that inflation recorded for the first three months of the year reached 31.5 percent, compared to 23.6 percent in the same period of 1987. Inflation last year soared to a record 159.2 percent annual figure. The government put into effect controls on wages and prices for goods and services it regulates in March, the second phase of a so-called Economic Solidarity Pact intended to brake hyperinflation and reduce it to 1 to 2 percent monthly by the end of the year. Under the program, the value of the peso _ 2,280 to the dollar _ and the minimum daily wage of 8,000 pesos, or about $ 3.50, will remain steady through the end of May.
