</ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Knouse </PERSON> of the meeting between <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gilchrist </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> was n't able to say much. I think he was already in shock ... `` <PERSON> Gilchrist </PERSON>, a graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>, had worked for the company for less than two years and was fired Wednesday for inefficient performance. <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Yager </PERSON> declined to be more specific about the reasons behind the firing. He said he did not know whether <PERSON> Gilchrist </PERSON>'s meeting with <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> had been scheduled. An unnamed associate was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> as saying <PERSON> Gilchrist </PERSON> went through eight jobs in 11 years before joining <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> in June 1986. He was told repeatedly that he would have to `` start performing'' there or lose his job, the associate said. `` <PERSON> Lonnie </PERSON> was doing very poorly,'' said an unidentified friend who told the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> he talked to <PERSON> Gilchrist </PERSON> by telephone Wednesday night, and that <PERSON> Gilchrist </PERSON> gave no indication that he had been fired. `` He was bright but he could n't communicate or sell. He could n't bring