<HEAD>EEC Questions Japan-U.S. Public Works Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Friday asked <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to clarify the terms of an accord with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> opening Japanese public works projects to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms. `` If it turned out that this agreement would be yet another bilateral deal between these two countries to the exclusion of others, that would be very damaging,'' <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> External Relations Commissioner <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> said Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> has criticized past efforts by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to open Japanese markets through preferential bilateral accords. Last month the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade said parts of a U.S.-Japanese accord on trade in semiconductors violated its international rules of commerce. The public works deal was signed Tuesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` We take this affair very seriously, not only because of the amount of potential trade involved but also because we feel that bilateral deals are hurting the spirit of free trade,'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> said in a statement. He said he would raise the issue at a meeting in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> next week of trade officials from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>. The public works accord signed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary <PERSON> Ichiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozawa </PERSON>, was termed a declaration of intent rather than a formal bilateral agreement. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said it was intended to provide market access to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> engineering and construction firms and for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> suppliers of a wide range of equipment for projects financed directly or indirectly with Japanese government funds. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> said he has not yet seen the text of the accord but sought `` an immediate, official declaration by the Japanese government clarifying the situation.'' `` There is a need for a binding commitment sufficiently specific to reassure the -LRB- EEC -RRB- and its industry that the latter will be able to bid for work under these major projects on an equal and non-discriminatory basis with regard to both Japanese and third country competitors,'' he said.
