<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Stocks Bjt   04-08 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Stocks, Bjt,0920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fueled By Strong Economic Performance, Tokyo Stock Market Recoups
Losses</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Less than six months after the global market collapse, <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> stock prices have surged above pre-crash levels, thanks to market resilience and renewed confidence in the country's healthy economy `` People have realized the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market has certain strengths,'' said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Smithson </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Kleinwort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benson </ORGANIZATION> investment firm. The main index of the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest in terms of money invested, fell 15 percent last October in the session after the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell a record 508 points, or 23 percent. On Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues finished making up all its lost ground as it surpassed its pre-crash level and reached its highest level in history, 26,769.22. On Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index slipped less than 0.1 percent, losing 20.33 points to close at 26,748.89. The Dow Jones index, meanwhile, still languishes more than 8 percent below its level of the day before the crash and 24 percent below its peak of last August. Other world stock exchanges are also below pre-crash levels. <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of the Vickers da Costa investment firm said the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market had been pushed by factors `` intrinsic and unique to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'' which had more to do with underlying domestic economic factors that could not be applied internationally. `` They were Japanese reasons,'' he said. Some of them are low interest rates, high corporate profits, strong economic growth estimated at a 7 percent annual rate in the last quarter of 1987 and inflation so low that consumer prices in February were 0.7 percent below a year earlier. Also, investors are reassured by controls on price movements of stocks, which they believe protect the market against a crash, <PERSON> Smithson </PERSON> said. Still, some Japanese officials worry that the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> is bouncing back too fast. <PERSON> Satoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON>, governor of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday that stock prices have risen too rapidly in relation to economic growth. Many investment strategists remain optimistic. <PERSON> Hisamichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawa </PERSON>, chief strategist at the <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bache </ORGANIZATION> investment firm, said the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stock market is sensitive to corporate earnings, and the Nikkei's rise was powered by substantial improvements in company profits. `` The domestic sector is now growing by more than 6 percent,'' <PERSON> Sawa </PERSON> said. Other analysts agree, and say the economy's overall growth _ compensating for a decline in exports _ will be 4 to 4.5 percent this year. <PERSON> Sawa </PERSON> attributed the market's resilience to a `` substantial level of liquidity and low interest rates.'' The prime lending rate in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is 5.5 percent. `` Investor sentiment is very optimistic,'' <PERSON> Sawa </PERSON> said. `` Money is flowing into the market from bond investments and savings accounts.'' Traders also agreed that a stable foreign exchange rate is contributing strongly to the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION>'s continuing bullish performance. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar fluctuated mainly in a narrow range of 125 to 128 yen last month. `` People realized the dollar was not headed for 120 yen as quickly as they originally thought,'' said <PERSON> Clap </PERSON> <PERSON> Ham </PERSON>, director of research at <PERSON> Jardine </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>. `` Removal of this fear has pushed the market up,'' he added. Many analysts said the country's system of government control over daily market movements also played a substantial role in fueling the rise. `` There is no doubt about it,'' said <PERSON> Ham </PERSON>. Investors are bound to feel comfortable with `` a market secured in government intervention.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> determines daily price-change limits for stocks from their previous day's closing level. At the bottom end, shares closing at less than 100 yen -LRB- 79 cents -RRB- are allowed to move a maximum of 30 yen -LRB- 24 cents -RRB- up or down, while at the top, those closing above 10,000 yen -LRB- $ 79 -RRB-, are given a maximum fluctuation of 2,000 yen -LRB- $ 16 -RRB-. Trading offers outside the stock's allowed range are not accepted, meaning shares with quick price changes sometimes are not traded for much of a session. Traders say the restrictions greatly inhibited the flow of money out of the market at the time of the crash, thereby limiting the overall decline. `` The limits had a positive calming influence on the stock market,'' said <PERSON> Smithson </PERSON> of <PERSON> Kleinwort </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>. The `` close relationship between the administration and institutions'' had an `` important role and slowed the rate of fall.'' <PERSON> Jardine </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Ham </PERSON> described the government as `` a guardian angel'' who will do whatever is needed to keep the market from falling. He added that numerous American investors have recently come into the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market, lured by the perceived benefits of the Japanese system. But while some analysts are predicting the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index will continue up _ possibly nearing the 30,000 mark by the end of summer _ they stopped short of saying <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, already the world's largest market in terms of total value of shares, will replace <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in dictating future market trends <PERSON> Sawa </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stock market will continue to wield a strong influence over <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> activity. `` Assuming <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> does not drop significantly or remains at its present level, the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market will move up,'' he said. He predicted prices will be bolstered by a new buying mood among the `` many financial institutions, including insurance firms and trust banks, who missed the bus because the market went up'' quicker than they expected.
