<HEAD>Testing Firm Wins 14-Year Battle With Federal Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Baltimore-based electrical testing company has won a 14-year battle with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and broken two other companies' hold on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market for product testing. <ORGANIZATION> MET </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> tried for more than a decade to get the federal agency to set standards for the national accreditation of product testing firms, and change a regulation that specifically listed two laboratories and thus kept others out. After settling two lawsuits brought in federal district court by MET, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday will publish standards for accreditation in the Federal Register. `` It's been a long time coming,'' said <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Frier </PERSON>, MET's founder and president The existing, and soon to be defunct, regulation says that testing shall be done by a nationally-recognized company, such as <ORGANIZATION> Underwriters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Factory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Frier </PERSON> said that for many years <ORGANIZATION> Underwriters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has had a virtual monopoly on the sort of electrical testing his company does That firm, established by the insurance industry in 1890, was not a party to any of the legal actions. `` The only thing they're guilty of,'' <PERSON> Frier </PERSON> said, `` is running a great public relations effort.'' <PERSON> Frier </PERSON>'s objections in correspondence and the lawsuits has been to the specific reference to UL, which tests more than 12,500 products, including consumer electrical appliances, and Boston-area FM, which primarily tests fire safety products. He said <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s regulation kept companies like his from certifying the safety of products that <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> itself will recognize as proper for the workplace, said <PERSON> Frier </PERSON>. UL, which has headquarters in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and additional laboratories in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, had no comment Thursday on <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s setting a time for the publication of new standards. Founded by insurance companies, <ORGANIZATION> UL </ORGANIZATION> now is an independent, not-for-profit corporation. <PERSON> Norwood </PERSON>, Mass.-based FM also had no comment Friday. The <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> businessman first requested that <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> set standards for accrediting testing firms in March 1974. His firm, which depends on field testing rather than new-product testing for its revenues, was growing and for several years he did not press the matter with <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>. Then in May 1982 <PERSON> Frier </PERSON> brought suit against the Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, who has ultimate responsibility for <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>. Before the suit came to trial, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> settled the legal action by agreeing to re-write an existing reference to accreditation by March 1984. Although <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> agreed that it would change its regulation, it did not and last June MET went back to federal court, charging that <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> had breached the settlement. In December, a federal judge directed <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> to comply with the settlement and set a time limit for publication of standards. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pipkin </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Towson </LOCATION> resident who heads <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s office of electrical and electronics safety standards, said Thursday that part of the long delay was due to `` the number of reviews that are necessary for something like this.'' He said there was agreement at <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> `` several years ago'' that its regulation `` kept other companies out, but for various reasons the changes just never moved forward.'' MET also has a branch in <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, in suburban <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. It has 125 employees and annual revenues of about $ 3.5 million.
