<HEAD>$80 Million Grocery Leaves Couple Overdrawn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALAMEDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No matter how many prime ribs or steaks <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> placed in her shopping cart, her husband knew the grocery trip did not cost what his bank account indicated _ $ 80 million. `` I was a little surprised. I knew it was a mistake,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, 41, on Friday. An innocent shopping trip March 23 to a local supermarket cost $ 121.78, but a bank error added another $ 80 million to the purchase, making it perhaps the most expensive grocery trip in history. Mrs. <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> had paid for the groceries with an automated teller card from <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, an electronics technician for the Bay Area Rapid Transit District, said he realized something was wrong several days later when he could n't withdraw money from their account. He tried unsuccessfully several times to withdraw money. Then, somewhat perplexed, he called up his balance. `` This huge number with a minus sign comes spilling out,'' <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said. Since the automated teller only goes up to $ 1 million, the machine showed his account overdrawn for that amount. Despite this shock, <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> wanted to purchase some flags and went to a flag store. `` I said ` I think I'm a million dollars short, so can I write a check?''' Since the owner knew him, <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> was allowed to write a check. He then called his bank's 24-hour hotline to notify them of the mistake. The bank, he said, insisted the <ORGANIZATION> Armstrongs </ORGANIZATION> had mistakenly written a check for $ 80 million. He noted, however, that $ 80,000,121.78 had been deducted from their account. <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> finally deduced that the bank's mistake stemmed from the $ 121.78 check for the grocery trip. Still, <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> was left without money last weekend. `` I was penniless. I had to rob my kid's piggy banks,'' he said. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON> corrected the <ORGANIZATION> Armstrongs </ORGANIZATION>' bank balance on Tuesday. A bank spokeswoman said it was a clerical error. <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said that even though he realized it was a mistake, it was hard to be without money on Easter weekend for his family, including his two children. `` It's pretty tough to convice people, ` Hey I'm $ 80 million dollars short, can you lend me a hundred dollars,''' he said.
