e.'' Addressing a meeting of <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> employee representatives, <PERSON> Tamm </PERSON> also said any solution should give top consideration to `` security for workers ... and to a stable leadership.'' Executives of the publishing house have been squabbling ever since the death of company founder <PERSON> Axel </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> in 1985. Under a complicated formula, <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>'s heirs and executors were given control of 27.1 percent of the company shares, the <PERSON> Burda </PERSON> brothers 25.9 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Kirch </ORGANIZATION> 10 percent. The rest were sold to the public. <ORGANIZATION> Kirch </ORGANIZATION> had maintained that he gained support from the owners of another 16 percent of <LOCATION> Springer </LOCATION> stock, which would give him and the Burdas a combined majority. <PERSON> Friede </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>, the widow of the founder, has been fighting the attempts by the <LOCATION> Burdas </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kirch </ORGANIZATION> to gain majority control. <ORGANIZATION> Kirch </ORGANIZATION> is involved in film distribution and production and other media areas. The <PERSON> Burda </PERSON> brothers own printing plants in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
