<HEAD>First Chicago Reports Increased Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's 10th largest bank holding company, said Friday that its first-quarter profit more than doubled from a year ago even though it raised its loan-loss reserves to cover troubled Third World debt. Net income for the three months ended March 31 totaled $ 141.5 million, or $ 2.38 per share, compared with earnings of $ 63.9 million, or $ 1.06 a share, in 1987. Chairman <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said improvement was made across the board during the period. `` Our performance this quarter was outstanding in all aspects of the consumer and middle-market banks _ the superregional segment of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> _ as well as in the global corporate bank,'' he said in a statement. Net interest income rose 14 percent, to $ 315.3 million from $ 277.9 million last year, while interest expense totaled $ 615.92 million, up from $ 515.92 million. <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> said it increased its provision for loan losses to $ 100 million from $ 75 million, half of which went to cover shaky foreign debt. `` We are continuing to see improvements in credit quality ... and we are continuing to maintian one of the strongest reserve positions for troubled-country debtors among our peers,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> noted. Quarterly non-interest income totaled $ 249.0 million, compared with $ 173.1 million last year. Non-interest expense rose to $ 311.5 million form $ 265.4 million.
