<FIRST>r f AM-InternationalBanks     04-08 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-International Banks,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Banks Urge New Money Creation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The International Monetary Fund should create about $ 29.5 billion worth of its own new money to help keep the dollar and other world currencies stable and to help solve the Third World debt problem, a leading group of the world's commercial banks proposed Friday. The idea came from <PERSON> Horst </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulmann </PERSON>, the West German managing director of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 165 banks in 38 countries. `` Not every one of the banks would endorse every line, but there's a consensus,'' <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> told a news conference. His nine-page outline was made public on the eve of next week's semiannual meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of the fund and its sister organization, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> Leading bankers and government financial leaders are due to attend, including <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. The new money would be given to member governments in proportion to their status in the fund. That means the wealthiest countries would get the biggest shares, including about $ 5.9 billion worth to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> alone. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> would get more than $ 2 billion, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> about $ 1.8 billion, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> $ 1.5 billion and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> $ 1.4 billion. <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could use this money for dealing on currency exchange markets to keep the dollar stable while other governments could hold more of this currency instead of dollars. At the news conference, he suggested that many believe they already hold too many dollars. The fund, owned by 151 governments, makes few public statements and had no official comment on the proposal. <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> said that he has had favorable comment privately. Representatives of Third World countries and some wealthier industrial governments have urged similar issues of new money by the fund in past years. They have come up against stiff refusal from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials who said it would promote inflation. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has the biggest single block of votes in fund matters. <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> wants the fund to create 21.4 billion more of its `` special drawing rights,'' known as SDR's. These are now worth about $ 1.38 each, based on the price of four other major currencies as well as the dollar: the West German mark, the British pound, the French franc and the Japanese yen. SDR's are handled only by governments and a few special governmental bodies. They exist not as coins or paper money but only as entries in ledgers and computers. The 15 heavily-indebted Third World countries, singled out by <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> for special help two years ago, would get about $ 3 billion worth among them. Most of these countries are in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Third World governments have in the past asked that the rules be changed so that their share would be larger, but <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> gave no support to that. `` It would be wrong to change the quotas in the fund,'' he said. `` These issues are for the needs of general international liquidity.'' He added that he did not rule out the possibility of the wealthier countries turning over their shares to the bank and fund, which could then make more loans to the Third World. <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> acknowledged that critics of his plan might call it a bailout for commercial banks. `` Commercial banks and other creditors would benefit from the improved creditworthiness of debtor countries,'' the proposal says. It suggests that debtor countries could use their shares to buy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars as collateral for new borrowing from banks, or to swing deals that would convert their old debts to banks into something else that banks would prefer to have. One possibility is the debt-equity swap, in which debt owed by Third World countries are exchanged at less than their face value for shares in businesses.
</TEXT>
