<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has tentatively scheduled a May 31 flight between <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, and the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION>. Soviet officials have yet to approve the flight, but unofficially they appear to favor the idea, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> official helping to organize the flight. `` There's a lot of interest from the Soviet Embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. It's aware of this project and they're excited about possibly getting involved,'' said <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, public relations director for the chamber. Commercial flights between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were banned for several years following the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1979, but the prohibition was lifted about two years ago. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> is the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline that flies between the two countries, operating flights between <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with a stopover in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> plans to introduce non-stop flights in a joint venture with <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION>, the Soviet national airline, starting May 15. For most of the post-war era, almost all contact between <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> has been cut off. And in recent years, the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> has been the scene of major military buildups by both nations. But last year relations began to warm. The Soviets allowed American <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> to swim between two islands that straddle the border in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, permitted an exchange of medical researchers from <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, and met with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fishing groups to discuss joint seafood ventures. <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Cancelmi </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the airline would donate the use of a plane for the half-hour flight between <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> and the Siberian city. The carrier has applied for authority to begin regularly scheduled service between the two cities next year. But <PERSON> Cancelmi </PERSON> stressed that <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> still needs more technical information about <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION>'s airport, as well as a formal nod from the Soviets, before the May flight can take place. In addition to dignitaries, the flight would also carry a group of western <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Eskimos who hope to be reunited with long-lost relatives in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. The flight is part of a broader initiative that state, university and chamber officials have launched to improve <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> Known as the Siberian Gateway Project, the goals include expanded trade and tourism between <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. On April 23, the project will sponsor a symposium in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Siberia-Alaska </LOCATION> re