RSON> Herbert </PERSON>'s personal trust under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code. They later did the same with the other brothers' trusts. Both sides have since been warring in federal and bankruptcy courts, maneuvering for a possible death blow or at least some kind of legal advantage. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON> in January allowed the banks a $ 7.8 million first lien against revenues from the Hunts' Green Canyon drilling project in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> The lien represented money Placid had spent on <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canyon </ORGANIZATION> in violation of a court order. When the Hunts experienced cost overruns _ including the loss of nine miles of pipe being towed to the site _ the project's outside investors declined to cover the loss. The outside investors, <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mavericks </ORGANIZATION> owner <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> media giant <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaylord </PERSON>, said they would commit more money only if the bankruptcy judge put those funds ahead of the banks' prior lien The banks' desire to close <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canyon </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>'s balking at considering the need for additional money an emergency, `` brought Placid to the table,'' one bank attorney said. Without Green Canyon, <PERSON> Placid </PERSON>'s reorganization plan would be untenable and, by default, <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON> would have accepted the bank plan calling for the outright sale of Placid.
