antage,'' for slander of <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s title to its Windows 2.03 software product and for violations of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> unfair business and practices laws. Apple spokesmen failed to return phone calls Friday seeking comment on the lawsuit. <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>'s suit had said <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s Windows 2.03, a graphics program used with <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> software, are `` illegal copies of the Macintosh audio-visual works and exceed the limited license rights <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> previously granted to <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>.'' The suit asked that <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> be prevented from copying, selling or marketing <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION>'s New Wave software and Windows 2.03. Apple also sought unspecified damages. Windows operates with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and compatible computers using <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s MS-DOS operating system. New Wave provides an audio-visual display upon which applications software can be run. In its countersuit, <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> said Windows 2.03 does n't infringe on any Apple copyright or patent and that <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> did n't contribute to any alleged copyright infringement by <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> The software company also asked the court to require <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> to live up to a 1985 settlement agreement concerning the use of the visual displays in question.
