<HEAD>IBM Announces Higher Ceilings On Patent License Fees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th graf, Under the ..., to UPDATE with
lawyer, analyst calling fees reasonable; picks up 10th graf, Many
companies .....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, moving to earn more money on its intellectual property, said Friday it will raise the ceiling on its patent license fees to 5 percent from the current 1 percent. The decision is likely to put pressure on the profit margins of companies that require licenses to make products compatible with those of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest computer company. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> holds 9,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> patents and more than 23,000 counterpart patents around the world. The decision does not affect existing license agreements. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement came just weeks before the expected announcement of computers compatible with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s year-old Personal System-2 personal computer. `` They certainly intend to cash in on their development effort'' on the Personal System-2, said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> also said it was reaffirming its long-standing practice of making its patents generally available for licensing to others under reasonable terms and conditions Some companies refuse to license some of their patents or license them selectively, to particular companies, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mihalec </PERSON> noted. He said <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> makes its patents generally available `` because it's good for the industry.'' Under the new rates, licensees will pay a maximum of 1 percent of sales revenue on a product using a single <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> patent. They will pay up to 5 percent of sales revenue on products using multiple patents, depending on the number of patents used and the extent of their use. Under the old rates, which were last changed 10 years ago, the maximum royalty was 1 percent regardless of the number of patents used. License fees of 3 to 5 percent are fairly common in industry, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnevale </PERSON>, director of the microcomputer service of InfoCorp, a consulting and research company based in <LOCATION> Cupertino </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` I would say that's in the ballpark,'' agreed <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernacchi </PERSON>, an intellectual-property attorney in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. He said patents have become more valuable since the federal court system has become more consistent in enforcing them. Many companies have cross-licensing agreements with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> that allow the companies to use each other's patents without fees for specified periods. In other cases, the agreements provide for free use of certain patents and require payment for use of others. `` Any licensee can look at the license they have from <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and figure out what they're covered for,'' <PERSON> Mihalec </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the companies rumored to be preparing to announce a Personal System-2 computer, has a long-standing cross-licensing agreement with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, according to <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Juge </PERSON>, director of market planning. <ORGANIZATION> Amdahl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes big mainframe computers that run the same software as <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s mainframes, also has a cross-licensing agreement with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, which expires at the end of 1991, spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. `` It will have no current effect on us,'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> noted that a patent license is not a license to copy products that use the covered patent. It is not a transfer of the technology or trade secrets that went into developing a product and it does not allow a licensee to infringe other forms of intellectual property rights such as copyrights. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> has said it has applied for both patents and copyrights on Micro Channel Architecture, the internal data pathway that is a critical part of its new Personal System-2.
</TEXT>
