<HEAD>Discount Real Estate Broker Closing Doors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A real estate company that tried to be a maverick by selling homes for fees well below the prevailing rate is going out of business eight months after opening. <ORGANIZATION> Barclay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Stubbs </PERSON> is being forced to close its doors mainly because it could not attract top agents, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinzly </PERSON>, the company's president, said Thursday. The real estate agency was offering to sell houses for a 3 -LCB- percent commission, sharply below the going rate of 6 percent. Buyers were also being offered a 1 percent bonus for purchasing a home listed by <ORGANIZATION> Barclay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Stubbs </PERSON>. Agents for the company were offered a salary instead of the standard commission _ a factor that others in the real estate business had predicted would hinder <ORGANIZATION> Barclay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Stubbs </PERSON>' recruitment efforts. <PERSON> Kinzly </PERSON> said she believed agents were reluctant to join the company because of fear of something new and concern about how they would be viewed by others in the business. If <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON> represented both the buyer and the seller, the agency would net only a 2 -LCB- percent commission. Other brokerages were offered a 2 percent shared commission, so <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON>'s net commission could be as little as half a percent. Although real estate commissions are negotiable, most are 6 percent, shared equally between the listing and selling brokers. The company had sold four or five houses, and had deposits on another six, <PERSON> Kinzly </PERSON> said, adding that many of the sales had been on a shared-commission basis. A few dozen homeowners had listed their houses with the agency, and `` things were picking up a lot,'' said <PERSON> Kinzly </PERSON>. She said she disagreed with Chairman <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' decision to quit now. <PERSON> Kinzly </PERSON> said she would have liked to see the company remain in business at least through the spring house-selling season. `` That could have made it go,'' she said. The company had been at the center of a controversy in the real estate community after it sued four area brokers in February, charging unfair trade practices and conspiracy to restrain trade. The other brokers had offered <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON> a lower shared commission than that offered to other agencies. Last month, a judge granted a motion by two of the defendants to have the case referred to the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> for arbitration. One of the other companies reached a settlement with <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
