<HEAD>Cattle Futures Advance Sharply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Cattle futures advanced sharply Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting expectations of improved beef demand. On other markets, grain and soybean futures moved higher, energy futures declined and precious metals were slightly higher. Livestock traders got clipped earlier in the week with limit declines in some cattle deliveries. `` Now we've gone a long way to return a little optimism to the market,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. There seemed to be a general belief that cash cattle prices will improve next week along with wholesale beef, he said. `` The expectations are for improved demand throughout the beef trade,'' said <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>. `` There should be a return of retail interest in beef and the packers will have to buy live animals because they've done little of it in recent days.'' Hog and pork belly futures also did well, in part because of spillover support from the cattle pit, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said. `` Also, a lot of traders are expecting a seasonal bottom in hog prices,'' he said. Live cattle settled .05 cent to 1.47 cents higher with the contract for delivery in April at 74.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .58 cent higher with April at 80.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent lower to .70 cent higher with April at 45.37 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .70 cent to 1.15 cents higher with May at 54.47 cents a pound. Grain and soybean futures prices advanced on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Soybeans set contracts high early in the session, then in a wild finish slumped to the day's lows before reaching new highs again. Large speculative buying, led by <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, accounted for much of the activity, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It was a day of wild gyrations,'' he said. `` There were some big sellers, too, but I think this market does not want to go down.'' The market is expecting a government report coming out Monday to show a further drawdown in soybean stocks, said <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>. `` This would give a very low stocks-to-usage ratio,'' he said. `` So if any problems develop with the weather later this spring or summer, this market could explode to the upside.'' Wheat and corn futures also were higher, partly in response to the performance in the bean pit. Wheat also got help from export activity. Wheat settled 2 cents to 4 -LCB- cents higher with the May contract at $ 3.16 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2 cents higher with May at $ 2.09 a bushel; oats were 1 -RCB- cents to 3 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 1.66 -RCB- a bushel; and soybeans were 5 cents to 8 cents higher with May at $ 6.78 a bushel. Energy futures took a dip, heading into the weekend meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> pricing committee. `` Up to this morning there was some speculation that there might be a surprise'' coming out of the meeting that would send prices higher, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON>, senior oil analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION>. A change of feeling came on remarks by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Rilwanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON>, who indicated the pricing committee would meet only one day, said <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON>. The implication is that the session would be a perfunctory one, with no recommendation for a special <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting or for production cuts. `` Those anticipations were put to rest today by <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON>'s remarks,'' said <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON> On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate crude oil settled 18 cents to 20 cents lower with the May contract at $ 16.88 a barrel; heating oil was .27 cent to .57 cent lower with May at 45.46 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .05 cent to .45 cent lower with May at 48.77 cents a gallon. Stock index futures at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> advanced with the June contract for the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settling at 269.90, up 2.30 points. The underlying spot index was up 3.27 at 269.43. Precious metals futures advanced slightly on the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gold was 70 cents to $ 1 higher with the June contract at $ 453.70 a troy ounce; and silver was .3 cent to .4 cent higher with May at $ 6.438 a troy ounce.
