<HEAD>Hughes to Buy Flight-Simulator Firm for $283 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a unit of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday it has agreed to buy <ORGANIZATION> Rediffusion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Similation </ORGANIZATION>, one of the world's largest suppliers of flight simulators, for $ 283 million. Rediffusion, which is based in <LOCATION> Crawley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and has operations in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, is owned by <ORGANIZATION> BET </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a conglomerate headquartered in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Rediffusion manufactures 40 percent of the military flight simulators in the Untied Kingdom and 35 percent of the simulators for training pilots of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and other foreign airlines. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> is one of the world's leading suppliers of high-technology electronics for military, scientific and commercial use. Acquisition of Rediffusion will expand <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>' existing operations in the pilot-training field. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> currently builds a weapons tactics trainer for the F-A18 jet and the mission trainer for the F-14A jet. Rediffusion, with a work force of 2,500 and annual sales of about $ 260 million, will be operated as a subsidiary of <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>. `` Hughes expects that simulators will be used increasingly by military customers to train pilots and operators as defense budgets flatten out,'' said <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheelon </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive of <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, adding that the acquisition will `` make <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> a a major factor in this field.'' The current world market for military and civilian simulators is $ 3 billion a year and that is expected to grow to $ 4 billion a year by 1993. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said it expects the use of simulators will be expanded into non-aircraft areas, such as factory automation and machine repair.
