<HEAD>Boeing's New 747 Delayed By Electrical Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first flight of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s new 747-400 jumbo jet has been delayed by electrical problems, the company said. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday that the first deliveries of the plane, which was formally introduced by <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> in January, are still expected in December but are n't a certainty. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> both said they are scheduled to receive two of the planes in December. Analysts said that if the four planes planned for December delivery are delayed into January, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s 1988 sales could be reduced by about $ 500 million and pre-tax operating profits could be cut by as much as $ 100 million. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Brannon </PERSON>, an aerospace analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said he estimates <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> would receive close to $ 25 million in operating profit on each 747-400. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Nisbet </PERSON>, analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, estimated each plane could generate $ 35 million in profit. <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> said it is possible the airplane's problems could delay certification of the jetliner by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The first flight had been scheduled for March 21, but <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> said he now expects it to be `` the latter part of this month.'' <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> said the electrical problems involve the main power generation system. He said the new 747, the world's largest commercial jetliner, has proven to be more complex to build than originally expected. The sophisticated electronics of the plane include a computerized cockpit that allows for a crew of two, rather than the three required on the earlier 747s. Also, the four-engine plane has improved aerodynamics with a bigger wingspan and added vertical winglets at their tips. It is powered by new engines. <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> said the job also has been complicated by `` customer pressure to change things, to tailor-make it to suit their requirements.'' The 747-400 is designed to carry as many as 479 passengers and has a range of 8,000 miles. Northwest, the initial customer for the plane, has ordered 10 of the jets with spare parts, worth $ 1.5 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has ordered 14 and taken options for six others, for a total value of $ 3.3 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> has received $ 13 billion to $ 14 billion in firm orders for 118 of the jets, plus options for 66 others. Each plane sells for about $ 125 million. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had profit of $ 480 million, or $ 3.10 a share, on sales of $ 15.35 billion in 1987. The company expects sales of $ 17 billion this year.
</TEXT>
