<FIRST>r f AM-TextileImports     04-08 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Textile Imports,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Textile Manufacturers Urge Legislation To Protect Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cheaply-manufactured textiles from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and other nations fueled a 17 percent increase in the textile trade deficit in 1987 while taking away jobs from Americans, industry representatives said Thursday. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Textile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, meeting here through Saturday, said that unless federal legislation is passed setting a 1 percent annual ceiling on import growth, textile production in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could cease by the mid-1990s. Imported clothing now accounts for 54 percent of all garments sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to institute figures. About 2.2 million people make their living in the nation's textile industry, according to institute figures This represents a loss of about 350,000 jobs since 1980, including 10,000 jobs lost in March alone, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laidlaw </PERSON>, president of the group. He blamed the situation in part of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Administration's failure to enforce import quotas. <ORGANIZATION> Laidlaw </ORGANIZATION> urged passage of the Textile and Apparel Trade Act, which faces a vote in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> next month. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imposed an embargo against the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> last year after the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> exported 12 million yards of fabric to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> instead of the 4 million yards provided under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> quotas, he said. But <ORGANIZATION> Laidlaw </ORGANIZATION> added the embargo was lifted when Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> visited the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. He said a 1988 limit was set at 23.5 million yards. `` The government is happily giving away our industry, and people are not going to re-invest if they do n't have confidence,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Laidlaw </ORGANIZATION>. The primary competition comes from government-subsidized manufacturers in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and other nations producing textiles for as little as 20 cents an hour in wages. `` On an even field, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry can compete with anyone,'' said <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON>, institute spokesman. `` But it ca n't compete when governments subsidize exports made by low-wage earners in deplorable conditions that would be illegal in the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> It's crazy. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> figures show imports of textiles and apparel in 1987 reached a record $ 29 billion, while exports totaled $ 4 billion. The industry's $ 24.8 billion trade deficit for textiles and apparel now equals 14.5 percent of the nation's overall trade deficit, according to <ORGANIZATION> Laidlaw </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we look at the growth of the nation's overall trade deficit from 1986 to 1987, one fourth of that diastrous growth has been at the expense of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> textile and apparel industry and its 2 million employees,'' he said.
</TEXT>
