<HEAD>Quaker State Gets Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OIL CITY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An investor group led by a New York-based investment banking firm said Friday it is offering $ 695 million to buy <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the motor oil refining company. <ORGANIZATION> Ardshiel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it is offering $ 26.50 per share for the Oil City-based company, which refines and sells <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> motor oil, owns <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minit-Lube </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> drive-in automobile lubrication centers, and manufactures truck lighting systems and automobile brake lights. <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> common stock closed at $ 22.62 -LCB- per share, up $ 1, in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading Friday before <PERSON> Ardshiel </PERSON>'s offer was made public. <PERSON> Ardshiel </PERSON> said it currently owns about 3.3 percent interest in the company. It did not disclose the identities of other investors. <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON> said the company had no comment on the offer. Rumors have been circulating for weeks that an offer was in the works, although it was expected to be about $ 30 per share or higher, said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, a broker with <ORGANIZATION> Butcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Singer in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ardshiel </PERSON> said it might be willing to raise the offer. It said it has enough money to fund the acquisition. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ardshiel </PERSON>'s senior managing director, said <PERSON> Ardshiel </PERSON> wanted to continue <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s core businesses. `` Surveys indicate that <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is one of the 10 best-recognized consumer brand names and we believe the value of that name recognition and <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s position have not been fully developed,'' <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON> said. <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ardshiel </PERSON> would `` accelerate growth'' of the company's <ORGANIZATION> Minit-Lube </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary based in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON> said the subsidiary, the company's latest area of expansion, has grown to 280 outlets in 20 states in the last few years. <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, founded in 1931 from many small <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> refiners and marketing companies, concentrates on the sale of high-quality motor oil and petrolum byproducts. It has about 6,300 employees, including about 450 at its headquarters and research centers in this <LOCATION> Venango </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> oil center of about 13,500 people. It also has refineries in <LOCATION> Farmers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> McKean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Newell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. Its Truck <ORGANIZATION> Lite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, based in <LOCATION> Jamestown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, manufactures vehicle lighting Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> reported a net loss of about $ 48 million, or $ 1.82 per common share, on sales of about $ 848 million, according to <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ardshiel </PERSON> said it has been involved in more than a dozen leveraged buyouts since 1977. In 1986, it was involved in the $ 1.6 billion leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Car </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> from <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
