<HEAD>Investor Leads Buyout of Metropolitan Broadcasting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group led by <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> communications investor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F.X </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON> said Friday it had agreed to buy <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns seven radio stations and the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON> said his group will pay about $ 40 million to the owners of the privately-held broadcasting concern and will assume about $ 260 million in debt. `` <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> is a premier radio group,'' <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON> said. `` We believe our financial resources and strong broadcast operating expertise will provide Metropolitan with a solid foundation for renewed growth.'' The sale is subject to approval by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Metropolitan Broadcasting was created in November 1986 when a group that included the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and managers of <ORGANIZATION> Metromedia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s radio division bought the division for $ 285 million in a leveraged buyout In a leveraged buyout, the buyers often borrow heavily against the assets or cash flow of the company being acquired to make the purchase. Metropolitan originally included nine radio stations and the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> radio network, but sold two stations in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> last fall. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> McAlpine </PERSON>, a media industry analyst for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the stations were sold to help meet the heavy interest costs associated with the debt incurred in the buyout. Metropolitan currently owns WNEW-AM and WNEW-FM in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, WMMR-FM in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, KTWV-FM in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, WWBA-FM in the Tampa-St. <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> area in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, WOMC-FM in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, KRLD-AM in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, which provides programming to radio stations in that state <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON> said his company would cancel <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION>'s announced plan to sell WNEW-AM and would review <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed sale of WWBA-FM. But he said the previously-announced sale of WOMC-FM in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> would go forward, pending <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> approval. <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> is being acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Sillerman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquisition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which was formed for the purpose of buying the radio properties. <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON> is chairman and chief executive of that company, as well as of <ORGANIZATION> Sillerman-Magee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based communications investment concern. In addition, <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON> and his associates are the largest shareholders in <ORGANIZATION> Legacy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>, which owns and operates 10 radio stations in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, Minneapolis-St. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> D.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON> said the Metropolitan stations had been profitable and were not for sale when he began conversations about the acquisition only nine days ago He said the stations should be able to generate more profit and revenue through additional investment in more aggressive promotion. He said his group's purchase should also end speculation about whether more of the group's stations would be sold. He said Metropolitan's corporate and station management would remain `` substantially intact.'' <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brazell </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` We look forward to building on strong expected results and to an era of expansion and enhanced profitability for <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>.''
