<HEAD>Eastern Files Brief in Appeal of Court Ruling on Shuttle Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> on Friday filed an opening brief in its appeal of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that blocked the sale of the profitable <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shuttle </ORGANIZATION> to a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The appeal will be heard May 5. In its brief, the airline said the court ruling was wrong because the air shuttle sale was a managerial move that did n't violate collective bargaining agreements Eastern said the court's decision denied the company $ 225 million the sale would have brought and permitted the court to assume potentially unlimited oversight authority over the airline's affairs, threatening its ability to manage its finances The company also said the ruling gave the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union reason to delay negotiating a contract. Eastern said the shuttle sale involved no involuntary employee transfers and would not cause any <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> workers to lose employment rights. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> declared March 10 that Eastern was in contempt of court for trying to sell the shuttle. <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company, broke federal labor law when it arranged to sell the shuttle. He also said the sale violated an order he issued last July barring Eastern from transferring 6,000 ground workers into a new subsidiary called Airport Ground Services.
