<HEAD>Disney Scraps Plan for $300 Million Burbank Entertainment Complex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In an unexpected move, the <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> scrapped plans Friday for $ 300 million entertainment complex in <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>, and city officials indicated they were looking at other alternatives including a proposal by <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> rival <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In a two-page letter to the head of <ORGANIZATION> Burbank </ORGANIZATION>'s redevelopment agency, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ovrom </PERSON>, <PERSON> Disney </PERSON> said the project was n't justifiable economically. Based on projected costs and attendance at the planned complex, `` the projected return on <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s investment simply did not meet corporate thresholds for an investment of this magnitude and anticipated business risk,'' the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Okun </PERSON> declined to elaborate on what that profit threshold is. Last May, <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> entered into an agreement with <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION> to negotiate exclusively to develop 40 acresof city-owned land alongside the <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Freeway </LOCATION>, about 15 miles northwest of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Since then, <PERSON> Disney </PERSON> said, the company has invested 22,000 man-hours and spent $ 2.5 million on planning studies, market research and related economic analyses. The complex was envisioned as including movie backlot tours, theaters, shopping areas, a hotel, a planetarium, rides and nightclubs _ a different format that the company's <ORGANIZATION> Disneyland </ORGANIZATION> theme park in <LOCATION> Anaheim </LOCATION>, about 30 miles away in neighboring <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The complex was to be about two miles from <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s crowded studio and headquarters in <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>. The exclusivity of the negotiating agreement was attacked by rival entertainment conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> and operator of a successful studio backlot tour in nearby Universal City. <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> claimed it had been unfairly barred from making a competing proposal to develop the <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION> site and has filed suit to block the Disney-Burbank agreement. <PERSON> Ovrom </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>'s redevelopment chief, said in a three-page memorandum to the mayor and city council that he felt `` a tremendous amount of disappointment'' over <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. But he added, `` We are all big boys and big girls, and we know going into this agreement that it was just a feasibility study ... We, too, shall immediately shift gears.'' <PERSON> Ovrom </PERSON> noted that <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION>, in its lawsuit, had indicated it was interested in making a proposal for developing the <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION> site. `` I am sure we all anxiously await to see what they will submit now that <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> is no longer in the picture,'' <PERSON> Ovrom </PERSON> said in the memorandum. <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Haas </PERSON> said the company had no comment on its plans. <PERSON> Ovrom </PERSON> said he had no regrets about granting Disney the exclusive agreement. `` The concept that -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive -RRB- <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisner </PERSON> originally envisioned was very exciting and could have been very special for <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Ovrom </PERSON> said in the memo. `` Had we turned down <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s offer to study these possibilities, we would have gone to our graves always wondering what might have been.''
